<FIRST>r i PM-GuardianAngels     02-09 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guardian Angels,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Subway Vigilantes To Go Ahead With London Chapter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Guardian Angels say that with the backing of
the director of two Charles Bronson movies and a British businessman
they will start training recruits in London next week _ despite
official opposition.
   Curtis Sliwa, leader of the New York-based group that wants to
send civilian patrols into the London Underground, had threatened to
abandon the plan unless the crime-fighting group could find training
space.
   He said police and some government officials had ``dug their
heels in'' and refused to allow the Angels to train in public places.
   Police and lawmakers have said law enforcement on the subways
should be left to professionals, not civilians.
   After discussing the Angels' plight on a highly popular British
Broadcasting Co. television talk show, Sliwa said Wednesday that he
had received two offers of help _ from Bill Fagan, owner of a chain
of public recital halls throughout London, and from director Michael
Winner.
   Winner directed ``Death Wish'' and ``Death Wish II'', both
starring Bronson as a tough vigilante who settles the score with
cold-blooded criminals.
   Sliwa said Fagan offered the Angels the use of a hall evenings
``with no strings attached'' for a three-month training course and
Winner guaranteed that if there were any problems, he would pay for
a training facility.
   ``It gives us a mandate to continue,'' Sliwa said.
   The Guardian Angels had also received hundreds of calls from
people who offered gardens, rooms, attics and backyards for
training, Sliwa said.
   He said 60 young people, one-third of them women, had applied to
become Angels and would on Monday begin a training program in basic
self-defense, first aid, performing citizens arrests and ``human
relations.''
   ``We're going to give it a go for the three months of training,
and hopefully by early May be able to produce a Guardian Angel unit
of young men and young women from the greater London area to go down
into the Underground and give you a permanent, regular presence of
Guardian Angels,'' he said.
   Supporters of the Angels say a sharp rise in assaults and
robberies in London's subway system indicate the 2.2 million
passengers who use it every day can't be protected without deploying
many more uniformed police.
   The Guardian Angels, who turn 10 years old on Monday, became
famous for patroling New York's subways and have branched out into
60 cities in the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</TEXT>
