<FIRST>r a PM-PlanesCollide     02-09 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Planes Collide,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Escape Collision of Small Planes at Honolulu Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two single-engine airplanes collided as they
attempted to land on the same runway at Honolulu International
Airport, authorities said. The three people aboard were not
seriously hurt.
   The aircraft ran into each other on approach to the runway
shortly before 6 p.m. Wednesday, according to Marilyn Kali, a state
Department of Transportation spokeswoman.
   There was no immediate explanation why the Cessna 150 and Cessna
152 were descending for a landing on the same runway.
   Jeffrey Weller, a Federal Aviation Administration spokesman, said
officials would review tapes today to determine the cause of the
accident.
   There were conflicting reports that the planes were 40 and 20
feet off the ground at the time of the collision, Weller said.
   Barbara Jackson, a passenger aboard her husband's Cessna 150,
suffered a bruise, Weller said.
   Her husband, James, was flying the plane and is a pilot for Aloha
Airlines, Weller said.
   Ki Jung Kim, a student pilot, was flying the Cessna 152 owned by
Eveland Aero Services, Weller said.
   Ages were not available.
</TEXT>
