<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     02-09 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed at a record high despite some
losses in the afternoon session on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
Thursday, while the dollar edged lower against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues gained a marginal 13.31
points, or 0.04 percent, to finish at 32,078.43, a new high. It
closed at a 32,065.12-point record high Wednesday. The Nikkei was
higher during the morning session Thursday, but it erased most gains
in the afternoon.
   The dollar closed at 129.39 yen, down 0.11 yen from Wednesday's
129.50-yen finish. The currency opened at 129.40 yen and traded
between 129.35 yen and 129.43 yen.
   Dealers said the dollar barely moved as market participants
stepped off to the sidelines in anticipation of President Bush's
budget address to the Congress on Thursday evening.
   If Bush shows a strong commitment to cut the U.S. budget deficit,
the dollar could gain further ground, while weak remarks could lower
the currency, said a dealer with a commercial bank in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
