<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     02-09 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Hearing on AIDS Home Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration will hold a
public hearing to more closely examine the controversial issue of
AIDS antibody testing kits which could be used in the home.
   The FDA has been concerned about the accuracy of such tests and
whether adequate counseling can be incorporated into a home-testing
system for the fatal disease.
   ``The whole Public Health Service is very much concerned that you
have a system that gives adequate results and that the results can
be explained to people,'' said Paul Parkman, director of the FDA
office that regulates the materials used in the test kits.
   The FDA last April turned back requests by manufacturers who
wanted to market an AIDS test kit, and the agency said research on
such kits would have to be done in hospitals, clinics and other
traditional health care settings.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>SEC Proposes to Crack Down on High-Pressure Phone Tactics</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is
seeking new regulations that would crack down on stockbrokers who
use high-pressure telephone tactics to sell penny stocks.
   The SEC rule, proposed by a 5-0 vote on Wednesday, would not
entirely ban unsolicited ``cold calls,'' but would require brokerage
firms to sign a written agreement with a new customer before
completing a transaction.
   Brokers would also have to interview new customers to determine
if they were suitable for risky investments and keep the suitability
documents on file for inspection by regulators.
   The stocks typically sell for less than $3 a share. Some are
issued by legitimate companies, but many are sold by companies with
an erratic earnings history.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Manufactured-Home Producer Settles Federal Suit for $945,000</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest producer of manufactured
homes has agreed to pay $945,000 to settle a federal suit charging
it failed to meet federal construction and safety standards in
building some 20,000 homes.
   The agreement with Fleetwood Enterprises Inc. settles a suit
filed by the government last year alleging that the manufactured
homes Fleetwood built in 1983 and 1984 failed to meet such
standards, the Department of Housing and Urban Development said
Wednesday.
   Glenn Kummer, president of Fleetwood Enterprises in Riverside,
Calif., said that in making the payment the company ``hasn't
admitted that the homes violated any standards.''
</TEXT>
