<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Laurel 1stLd-Writethru a0438 02-09 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Laurel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laurel Trip To Marcos Bedside A Bid To Boost Dying Political Fortunes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to FIX typo, 6th graf to CORRECT style on `persuade.'
Picks up 7th pvs, `The government ...' ^AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Salvador Laurel's visit
to Ferdinand Marcos' bedside in Hawaii is widely seen as a bid to
revive his dying political fortunes and angle for right-wing support
as he seeks the presidency.
   On Saturday, Laurel returned from Honolulu carrying what he said
were secret messages from the ailing Marcos for President Corazon
Aquino.
   Laurel appealed to Mrs. Aquino's ``Christian values'' to allow
the ex-president to come home to die. But Mrs. Aquino refused to see
Laurel, reflecting the low esteem in which she holds the vice
president.
   Furthermore, many political commentators accused Laurel of
``grandstanding'' in the sensitive national question of whether to
allow the 71-year-old Marcos to return from exile in Hawaii.
   ``The nakedness of Laurel's ambitions leaves little room for
respect,'' wrote The Manila Chronicle. ``It has become clear that
the man is so obsessed with winning power that he would grab at
straws to support his bid.''
   Laurel has so little influence with Mrs. Aquino that it seemed
virtually impossible that he would be able to persuade her to relent
and allow Marcos to return home.
   The government says Marcos and his associates embezzled up to $10
billion during his 20-year rule and Mrs. Aquino has refused to
discuss his return until he gives back the money.
   Several congressmen and political commentators believe Laurel
intended through the trip to ingratiate himself with Marcos'
followers, especially those in northern Luzon island, and use them
as a base of support in the 1992 presidential campaign.
   Inheriting the Marcos mantle would enable Laurel to outflank
other potential center-right candidates, such as Sen. Juan Ponce
Enrile, who might appeal to those who would not support Mrs. Aquino
or anyone seen as her favored candidate.
   Mrs. Aquino has said she will not seek re-election.
   ``With the demise of Marcos, the so-called `solid north' is in
need of someone to rally around,'' said Rep. Florencio Abad.
   The 60-year-old Laurel would seem an ideal ``reconciliation
candidate'' to bring together a nation still deeply divided three
years after Marcos was ousted in a popular uprising.
   Laurel announced he would run for president against Marcos in
1985, but stepped aside under pressure to become Mrs. Aquino's
running mate.
   A member of an elite political clan, Laurel maintains links to
the business community and the military.
   But a series of political blunders has reinforced his deeply
entrenched public image as an opportunist.
   After a bloody August 1987 coup attempt, Laurel traveled to
military bases, ostensibly to investigate soldiers' complaints.
   Before the television cameras, he would shout, ``Do you want
Communists out of government?'' That brought cheers from the troops
but contempt from more liberal-minded urban voters, who joked that
Laurel was becoming a ``Filipino McCarthy.''
   In September 1987, he resigned as foreign secretary, citing
widespread differences with Mrs. Aquino on the 20-year-old Communist
insurgency and other issues. A year later, he demanded she resign
and call new elections, but she refused.
   Instead of winning sympathy by his moves, Laurel's popularity
plunged. Manila newspapers and television stations rarely report his
activities and his speeches draw only modest audiences.
   Despite Laurel's personal campaigning, his nephew, Benjamin
Laurel, was defeated in the January 1988 race for governor of
Batangas province, the Laurel family stronghold.
   Since formally breaking with the administration in August,
Laurel's attempt to organize a broad-based opposition movement have
faltered.
   He complained last year to foreign reporters that he was
virtually ignored by the media. His principal public forum in the
capital has been occasional interviews by Tagalog-language radio
stations.
   ``It would be a gross understatement to say that Doy has an image
problem,'' wrote columnist Ed Olaguer, referring to Laurel by his
nickname.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Reid has been AP bureau chief in Manila
since 1986.
</TEXT>
