<FIRST>u a AM-RocketAccident 1stLd-Writethru a0432 02-09 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocket Accident, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0432,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industrial Accident Kills One During Test</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with officials now saying the
projectile was not a rocket was not involved, CORRECT name of plant involved,
UPDATES with identity of man kiled. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``giant pressure cooker'' at an aerospace
plant blasted off like a rocket through the ceiling Wednesday night
and crashed in a parking lot, killing one person, police said.
   Three others working in the Kaiser Space Products building
escaped without injuries, authorities said.
   Robert Renkemeyer, was standing near a steam-driven pressure
kettle used for curing aerospace parts when it exploded and ``the
lid blew off,'' killing the 66-year-old consultant from Pensacola,
Fla., said Kaiser President Bill Sidney.
   ``It's impossible to know how the pressure vessel blew up,''
Sidney said.
   The 14,000-poundlid blasted through the roof and landed in a
parking lot 50 or 60 feet away, said Fire Department spokesman
Charlie Stimmel. The west and south walls of the building also were
blown out.
   ``The pressure vessel had 1,000 pounds per square inch of
pressure and was being fed 310-degree steam when it blew. Right now
we're thinking it was some type of pressure buildup,'' Stimmel said.
   Earlier, Police Sgt. Robert Williams said the object launched
through the roof was a rocket nose cone.
   The plant supplies rocket nozzles to NASA, the Air Force and
private satellite operations.
</TEXT>
