<HEAD>Pilot, Flight Attendant Killed In Crash Were To Be Married</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Azores Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flight attendant Yvette Murray and pilot
Leon Daugherty often worked together and boarded a chartered jet
with plans of building a life together.
   Wednesday, they died together.
   Ms. Murray, 26, of Marietta, and Daugherty, 41, of Nashville,
Tenn., were planning to be married May 20, according to Ms. Murray's
father, Tom Murray of Atlanta.
   But their Boeing 707 crashed into a mountain in the Azores on
Wednesday, killing all 144 aboard.
   Both worked for Independent Air Corp. of Smyrna, Tenn. The
charter plane, bearing 137 Italian tourists and an American crew of
seven, was flying from Bergamo, Italy, to the Dominican Republic,
and would have continued without passengers to Jamaica.
   Murray said his daughter was undaunted about flying despite
recent crashes and maintenance problems in the airline industry.
   ``She loved flying, it was a big thing for her,'' he said.
``Because she was going to be married, she didn't think they'd let
her continue flying.
   ``She probably would have been out of this thing in a month or
so.''
   The couple had planned to live in Acworth, near Atlanta.
Daugherty had bought a house there, Murray said.
   ``He also bought her a horse two weeks ago. He was so kind to
her,'' Murray said.
   ``She was a very nice, sweet girl,'' said the pilot's mother,
Robbie Daugherty of Nashville. ``We were close.''
   Mrs. Daugherty said her son had worked as a pilot for several air
freight companies before he joined Independent Air. He owned his own
plane, and flew helicopters in the Tennessee National Guard.
   ``He called me Sunday from Jamaica and asked me to tell the Guard
he couldn't fly because of his job,'' Mrs. Daugherty said.
   Ms. Murray grew up in Tampa, Fla., and had worked as a waitress
and a cellular phone saleswoman before becoming a flight attendant,
her father said.
   ``She was a beautiful little girl,'' Murray said.
</TEXT>
