<FIRST>r a PM-MorristownDeath     02-09 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Morristown Death,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Autopsy Shows Black Man Died From Drug Use, Not Police Brutality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRISTOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black man who died in police custody
was the victim of drug use and not police brutality, as some
activists have claimed, officials said.
   Despite the autopsy finding, about 55 demonstrators marched
outside Town Hall for an ninth straight night Wednesday to protest
what they alleged to be brutality against 22-year-old John ``Tony''
Jackson.
   ``It's the same answers that they had before,'' said Frank
Osborne, Jackson's uncle and leader of the nightly marches.
``They've diverted the traffic, that wasn't the issue. We have to go
further.''
   The ``death, in my opinion, was caused by cardiac arrhythmia,
brought on by cocaine use,'' Morris County Medical Examiner Dr.
Ernest E. Tucker said. ``As far as police brutality is concerned, I
couldn't find any evidence of police brutality. ...
   ``I am calling this a homicide on the grounds that whoever
supplied the drugs is responsible for his death,'' he said.
   County Prosecutor Lee Trumbull said his office and local police
will investigate the case as a homicide.
   ``In terms of police brutality ... that case has ended,''
Trumbull said. `We now have a homicide investigation under way.
   ``Unequivocally, the Morristown Police Department or any
individual member is not a suspect,'' he said. ``I would like to see
the community as vigorous in attempting to identify the source of
the drugs that killed Tony Jackson as they've been in protesting.''
   David Manahan, mayor of this affluent township about 30 miles
west of New York, welcomed the findings. But the mayor, who has
asked U.S. Justice Department mediators to look at the case,
criticized Trumbull for not talking with leaders in the black
community before releasing the medical examiner's report at a news
conference.
   ``The main problem here has been one of trust and mistrust, and I
think an opportunity was lost in the press conference,'' he said.
   Cardiac arrhythmia, as described by Tucker, occurs when a
person's heart quivers and cannot pump sufficient quantities of
blood. The person faints and loses consciousness because blood
cannot reach the brain.
   Traces of cocaine, heroin, quinine and codeine were found in
Jackson's blood and urine. Tucker said the drugs were taken in the
hour before death.
   Jackson had puncture marks on both arms but Tucker said he did
not know if they were from medical efforts to revive Jackson or from
the victim's own drug injections.
   The autopsy also showed Jackson had a laceration above the right
eyebrow and a bruise on the scalp, but Tucker said they caused no
damage to the skull or brain and did not contribute to his death.
   Jackson also had a history of bronchial asthma but that did not
play any rose in his death, Tucker said.
   Jackson died Jan. 28 after he ran away from police who tried to
arrest him on a traffic warrant. Police caught him after he bumped
into an officer in the low-income housing project where he lived.
   Afterward, Jackson complained of shortness of breath, police
said. Witnesses said he cried out for help and collapsed soon after.
Police took him to Morristown Memorial Hospital, where he was
pronounced dead.
</TEXT>
