<HEAD>Stocks Up Slightly, Dollar Edges Lower in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index, edging up
only slightly, set a record high for the fifth consecutive trading
day today, while the dollar declined marginally against the Japanese
yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 32,078.43 after a
13.31-point, or 0.04 percent, gain from its previous record closing
of 32,065.12 on Wednesday.
   The index had gained 178.64 points in early trading but
institutional and foreign investors, major buyers in the morning,
started taking profits in the afternoon, dealers said.
   Electricals, including Sony and Toshiba, were among the gainers
in active trading. First section volume was estimated at 1.6 billion
shares.
   The dollar closed at 129.39 yen, down 0.11 yen from Wednesday's
close of 129.50 yen. After opening at 129.40 yen, the currency
stayed in a tight range of 129.35-129.43 yen.
   Market players remained on the sidelines ahead of President
Bush's budget address to Congress Thursday night, dealers said.
