<FIRST>u i PM-Kabul-Mood     02-09 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kabul-Mood,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Encircled Afghan Capital Calm _ At Least On The Surface</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a courtyard where only enormous
wooden and rusting beams keep the walls from collapsing, the
money-changers ply their trade.
   In this sensitive and openly tolerated black market, the value of
currency can change with a small gesture of the hand or inflection
of the voice.
   Today there is no sign of panic. The U.S. dollar is changing
hands for 210 afghanis, compared to 238 a week ago when Soviet
soldiers were still seen in full force.
   Now the Soviets are all but gone, and the money-changers say
there's a feeling their departure will lead to peace and that the
perenially warring Afghans will settle down to their traditional way
of handling things _ by making a deal.
   Whether that's a realistic attitude remains to be seen, but the
Red Army's departure is having a buoyant effect.
   ``We didn't need them here,'' said one money-changer, Mohammad
Yahir. ``We have problems, but we can solve them ourselves, God
willing. I think it will be OK.''
   One by one, Soviet bases around this city of 2 million people
have been handed over to Afghan government forces.
   Several hundred Soviet soldiers are still hanging on to guard the
Kabul airport, but they are to leave by next week.
   The rest of the thousands of Red Army troops who were around the
capital three weeks ago are home or on their way, either in convoys
heading up the snowy Salang Highway to the Soviet border or on huge
military transport planes.
   Moslem guerrillas have launched few rocket attacks on Kabul, and
the government shelling of guerrilla hideouts in the mountains has
tapered off.
   On the surface at least, Kabul is calm.
   The markets bustle with women clad in traditional chadris, the
all-enveloping veil that cascades in pleats from a skullcap, with a
coarse mesh panel over the eyes.
   Children slide down the icy hills and fly kites in the street.
   Smoke-belching buses and horn-blaring taxis jam the narrow
streets.
   Carts filled with fresh bananas and oranges from neighboring
Pakistan and pomegranates and apples from other parts of Afghanistan
mask for a few seconds the stench of impoverished humanity.
   On Chicken Street, the main venue for foreigners and the wealthy,
merchants sell everything from centuries-old carpets and antique
muskets to Swiss watches and German beer.
   ``Goods are still coming in. There is plenty of food and other
goods. All you need is the money to pay,'' said a merchant who
identified himself only as Tamoor.
   The Soviet armored personnel carriers that a few days ago stood
at the end of Chicken Street are gone. In their place are Afghan
soldiers, clutching a Soviet-designed Kalashnikov rifle in one hand
and prayer beads in the other.
   Few signs remain of Moscow's nine-year military intervention
except for the Volga and Moskvich cars, fur hats, vodka and Russian
caviar _ which has nearly tripled in price since the final Soviet
withdrawal started in early January.
   Afghans openly voice their hostility toward Soviets and look upon
foreigners with suspicion.
   ``Where are you from?'' Qurban Ali asked a group of Westerners.
   ``England,'' one of them answered.
   ``Forgive me,'' Ali said, motioning the group inside his carpet
shop. ``I thought you were Russian.''
   For the city's 350,000 poor people, things are not so comfortable.
   A Soviet airlift and attacks on guerrillas blocking the Salang
Highway have eased shortages of flour, but lines persist at the
shacks where bread is sold. The poorest people survive on diets of
bread, rice and tea.
   Heating oil and fuel are even scarcer, making a bitter winter
even harder.
   A liter of gasoline sells on the black market for 175 to 500
afghanis ($3.20 to $9.10 at the official exchange rate), compared to
30 afghanis (55 cents at the official rate) for the scarce and
tightly rationed government supplies.
   ``I had to walk seven kilometers (four miles) to work today,''
said a government interpreter. ``It's best to live near the trolley
lines. They run on electricity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
