<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay     02-09 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Provisional Government Investigating Stroessner Finances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new government of coup leader Gen.
Andres Rodriguez is investigating allegations of financial
irregularities involving public funds controlled by deposed
President Alfredo Stroessner.
   Stroessner, ruler of this landlocked South American country since
1954, was ousted from power Friday in a coup engineered by
Rodriguez. About 50 people died in the takeover, and Stroessner was
sent in exile Sunday to Brazil.
   Charges of corruption under Stroesser were widespread. Opposition
politicians, once persecuted and now allowed to speak freely, have
called for the creation of a commission to recover funds misspent
under the old regime.
   Attorney Pedro Abilio Rolon filed a suit Monday charging three
former government ministers and Stroessner's long-time personal
secretary, Mario Abdo Benitez, of using public funds and accepting
bribes to obtain mansions, apartments and autos. Rolon sought an
embargo on their local bank accounts.
   That action was followed Tuesday by Gen. Juan Antonio Caceres,
former minister of public works, who alleged that Stroessner
personally controlled at least two accounts funded by public money.
   On Wednesday, the Central Bank announced it was going to
``control withdrawals'' from accounts ``of some government
institutions.''
   Caceres noted Stroessner, 76, had signature power over funds
exceeding $4 million _ revenues from highway tolls and gasoline
taxes.
   Caceres said he didn't know what Stroessner used the money for,
but that in general, the funds were not available for use by his
ministry.
   A Paraguayan businessman with close contacts in the banking
industry said government officials loyal to Stroessner wrote and
hurriedly tried to cash checks written on government accounts
immediately following his ouster.
   Aldo Zuccolillo, publisher of the newspaper ABC Color, which was
closed by Stroessner but hopes to reopen this month, said the
Central Bank measure was ``good, intelligent.''
   ``This was taxpayers' money being administered as though it were
a personal checking account,'' Zuccolillo said, adding, ``There must
be dozens more accounts like this linked to other government
ministries in state-run companies.''
   The Central Bank said the reason for the measure, which could
cause delays in the payment of some government checks, was ``to
obtain better control and greater clarification of the destination,
and correct application, of public funds.''
   Luis Ortiz, secretary to new Economy Minister Enzo de Bernardi,
said the bank would review ``all checks written by government
officials who no are longer government officials.'' De Bernardi is
in charge of the bank.
   In a separate development, he told reporters Paraguay's foreign
debt amounts to $2 billion, and there don't appear to be funds to
keep making payments. The last payment was made in December, he said.
   ``The Treasury needs funds and if we do not find them, we'll have
to talk with our creditors,'' he said.
   Foreign Minister Luis Maria Argana declined to blame Stroessner.
   ``He was a great president for many years,'' said Argana, who
under Stroessner served as president of the Supreme Court.
``Unfortunately, during the last two years, he was surrounded by a
group of totally irresponsible, greedy politicians totally lacking
in patriotism.''
</TEXT>
