<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Piro     02-09 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Piro,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Society Dance Teacher Dead at 68</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank ``Killer Joe'' Piro, the dancer who taught
high society everything from the cha-cha to the hully-gully, has
died of kidney disease at age 68.
   Piro, who got his nickname because he easily outlasted partners
on the dance floor, died Tuesday at a hospital in Manhattan.
   For decades, the short, sinewy dancer performed on stage and
television, taught at his Manhattan studio and made nightly rounds
of parties and clubs. Always a step ahead of fashion, Piro taught
the mambo, the cha-cha and the merengue, then the twist, the frug,
the frog and the watusi.
   His students included the Duke and Duchess of Windsor and Luci
Baines Johnson, daughter of President Lyndon Johnson, not to mention
other dancers such as Dame Margot Fonteyn and Ray Bolger.
   Piro was born in East Harlem, the son of an Italian tailor. He
said he took up dancing at a neighborhood social club to meet girls.
   He dropped out of school after eighth grade, working at
construction jobs and plastics designing. Meanwhile, he kept winning
Harlem dance contests, including the 1942 National Jitterbug
Championship at the Harvest Moon Ball.
   After serving in the Coast Guard during World War II, Piro
entered and won dance contests at the Palladium so often, he said,
they offered him $15 a week to teach dancing _ and stop competing.
   He is survived by his wife, Lucienne; a daughter, a stepson and
two sisters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
