<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-Asylum     02-09 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Asylum,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Allows Former Somoza Officers To Leave After Nearly 10 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After nearly a decade of political
asylum in the Venezuelan Embassy, two former high-ranking officers
in the army of the ousted Somoza regime were permitted to leave and
flew to Guatemala.
   Col. Carlos O. Gutierrez and Capt. Mario Guerra Palacios arrived
in Guatemala City Wednesday night aboard a commercial flight from
Managua. They were greeted by a Venezuelan diplomat and taken to a
nearby hotel.
   Diplomatic sources in Guatemala told The Associated Press the
pair would remain in Guatemala a few days and that they planned to
seek political asylum in the United States. The sources spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The two fled to the Venezuelan Embassy in July 1979, the same
month the leftist Sandinista National Liberation Front took power
after a popular uprising ousted President Anastasio Somoza.
   Gutierrez, 62, and Guerra, 42, were members of the now-disbanded
National Guard, as the army was known under Somoza.
   Known as ``The Ranger'' because of his U.S. military training,
Gutierrez was one of Somoza's trusted officers. He had suffered two
heart attacks in confinement, and said in a 1986 interview that the
only way out was if the United States ``comes in and wipes these
Communists out.
   ``Either that, or we will end up dying here,'' he had said.
   Guerra kept himself busy by studying radio and television repair,
and completed a correspondence course in electronics in 1986.
   In Managua, the opposition newspaper La Prensa on Wednesday
quoted unidentified sources as saying the Foreign Ministry gave the
two a one-year ``exit permit'' instead of the customary safe-conduct
pass.
   Repeated telephone calls to the Foreign Ministry and the
Venezuelan Embassy in Managua went unanswered. Reporters were kept
away from several Venezuelan diplomats gathered at Managua's Cesar
Augusto Sandino International Airport before the pair left.
   Allowing the officers to leave was seen as a gesture of goodwill
toward the United States by the Sandinista government, which is
trying to cope with a rapidly deteriorating economy. Inflation
reached 20,000 percent in 1988.
   The government has blamed economic problems on eight years of war
with the U.S.-backed Contra rebels; Hurricane Joan, which struck the
Atlantic coast last October; and a U.S. trade embargo since 1985.
   President Daniel Ortega is scheduled to attend a summit of
Central American presidents next week in El Salvador. The meeting,
postponed many times, was called under a regional peace plan signed
by Ortega and the presidents of El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala,
Costa Rica in August 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
