<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-09 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great Lakes Get Strong Winds, Heavy Snow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow and strong winds buffeted states along the Great Lakes
today, causing whiteouts and traffic accidents as drifts up to 10
feet deep piled up. Snow fell in California and Utah.
   The Great Lakes storm left more than a foot of snow in parts of
northern Michigan on Wednesday night and drifts 6 to 10 feet deep.
Snow advisories were in effect today in much of the state.
   In northeast Ohio, blowing, drifting snow made snow removal
difficult if not impossible. Blowing snow caused whiteouts and many
traffic accidents in the area, which was under a winter storm
warning.
   Snow squalls developed over western New York, and up to 6 inches
of snow was forecast.
   A snow advisory was issued for northwest Pennsylvania.
   Snow began falling Wednesday night in the northern mountains of
Southern California, and rain fell along the coast. A winter storm
warning was in effect for mountains from the San Bernardino Range
northward and in the Owens Valley. Snow advisories were posted for
the Antelope Valley, northern foothills and valleys above 1,500
feet, the northern Sierra Nevada and the Lake Tahoe Basin.
   Snow also fell in St. George and Cedar City, Utah. A winter storm
warning was in effect for the mountains of southern Utah and a
winter storm watch was issued for mountains to the north tonight and
Friday.
   Today's forecast called for widespread rain across much of
central and Southern California; snow in the Southern California
mountains and much of Nevada; lake-effect snow along the eastern
shores of lakes Erie and Ontario and across eastern upper and
northern lower Michigan; and gusty winds from eastern Wyoming to the
upper Great Lakes and much of New England.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 20s and 30s in much of
the nation; in the teens in southern Idaho and from the upper
Mississippi Valley to the Great Lakes and New England; in the 40s
and 50s from the Pacific Coast to the southern Rockies, western and
southern Texas, the lower Mississippi Valley and the southern
Atlantic Coast; and in the 60s and 70s in southern Arizona and
central and southern Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 22
degrees below zero in Craig, Colo., to 74 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 30 fair; Boston 22 windy; Buffalo 7 windy;
Charleston, S.C., 40 fair; Cincinnati 7 fair; Cleveland 8 snow;
Detroit 5 fair; Miami 69 fair; New York 25 windy; Philadelphia 22
windy; Pittsburgh 7 snow; Portland, Maine, 20 windy; Washington 24
wind.
   _Central: Bismarck 5 fair; Chicago 2 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 29
fair; Denver -1 fair; Des Moines -6 fair; Indianapolis 4 fair;
Kansas City 0 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul -6 fair; Nashville 15 fair;
New Orleans 40 fair; St. Louis 6 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 27 cloudy; Anchorage 30 snow; Las Vegas 35
cloudy; Los Angeles 50 showers; Phoenix 55 cloudy; Salt Lake City 4
hazy; San Diego 56 partly cloudy; San Francisco 41 foggy; Seattle 33
fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 10 snow; Toronto 9 windy.
</TEXT>
