<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 0714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     02-09 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Moslem Amal Appear In Control Of South Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fresh from victory over their rivals in the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, the militiamen of the Shiite Moslem Amal
appear to control south Lebanon.
   The country's south is divided into strips:
   First, there is the Israeli-controlled security zone along the
border, then an area patrolled by the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon,
then the Amal zone running up to Sidon, 35 miles north of the
Israeli border.
   Leaders of Amal say their control over south Lebanon means they
can also control attacks on Israeli soldiers in the security zone
Israel proclaimed near its border in south Lebanon. But they would
not strike at targets in Israel.
   ``No one is allowed to hold weapons or wear military clothes in
south Lebanon except Amal,'' said Ali Kreiss, the local Amal
political chief. ``Amal is responsible for the security of everyone
in south Lebanon.''
   The U.N. peacekeepers, numbering 5,800, have been in Lebanon
since a 1978 Israeli invasion. Israel set up its security zone in
1985.
   Kreiss said Amal's responsibility for security in south Lebanon
was laid out in agreements signed over the last three months with
the Hezbollah, or Party of God, and the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Before the agreements, hundreds were killed in fighting with the
PLO for control of Palestinian refugee camps, and with Hezbollah for
mastery of south Lebanon and Beirut's Shiite southern suburbs.
   The agreement means Amal has rid itself of ``direction from
outside, from other countries,'' Kreiss said, indirectly sneering at
Hezbollah dependence on Iran. He claimed Syrian backing for Amal did
not represent influence but ``relations.''
   Kreiss said four longstanding Amal tenets were included in the
agreement: All Lebanon must remain unified, Amal must have charge of
the south's security, no attacks may be carried out on U.N. forces,
and no foreigners may be kidnapped.
   To underscore the last point, Amal security chief Mohammed Harkus
had his men take Western journalists on a tour of Tyre, including
ancient Roman ruins.
   Led by a jeep with wailing siren, a convoy of four cars pushed
through snarled traffic.
   A small measure of Amal's control was that the siren persuaded
drivers to give way. Militias most often fire automatic rifles in
the air to clear traffic.
   Along the roads, Amal checkpoints monitored traffic and the
militia's green symbol was plastered on walls, along with posters of
the late Amal leader of south Lebanon, Daoud Daoud, who was killed
in last September's Amal-Hezbollah fighting.
   In Tyre, a city of 50,000 10 miles north of Israel's border,
people appear less grim than when Hezbollah's power was on the rise
and one cafe advertised live music. The Tehran-backed hard-liners
had banned music, ordered booze off store shelves, and papered walls
with posters of Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   A stop for coffee by the journalists, at an outdoor cafe, drew
curious Lebanese unaccustomed to seeing foreigners in anarchic south
Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
