<FIRST>r a PM-MultipleKillings     02-09 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Multiple Killings,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Cites Love-Hate Relationship Between Suspect And Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLARKSVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of murdering 14 family
members in a 1987 Christmastime rampage had a ``love-hate
relationship'' with one of his daughters that might explain some of
the killings, a prosecutor said.
   R. Gene Simmons, 48, should be sentenced to death for strangling
and shooting his relatives, prosecutor John Bynum said in his
opening statements Wednesday.
   Bynum said the prosecution would present a note written by
Simmons that authorities found in a bank safe deposit box.
   ``It will show you and indicate to you a motive as to why Mr.
Simmons killed some of these people,'' specifically his oldest
daughter, Sheila; her husband and 6-year-old daughter, Sylvia; and
Simmons' wife, Becky, 46, said Bynum.
   ``It will describe a love-hate relationship with this daughter,''
Bynum told the jury. Relatives say Simmons fathered Sylvia.
   The defense attorney, Robert E. ``Doc'' Irwin, told the jury to
forget past publicity about the case.
   ``I want to ask you to be the most careful and most courageous
jury that ever sat in this county, perhaps in this state, in behalf
of the defendant,'' Irwin said.
   Bynum described how investigators found the bodies of Simmons'
wife, seven children, two of their spouses and four grandchildren at
the Simmons house north of Dover, 25 miles southeast of Clarksville.
   They found five bodies in the house on Dec. 28, 1987, and the
next day found seven bodies in a grave and the bodies of two babies
in the trunks of cars.
   Authorities found the bodies after arresting Simmons for a
40-minute shooting spree that left two dead and four wounded in
Russellville.
   Simmons has been convicted and sentenced to death for the two
Russellville murders. He has asked to be executed as soon as
possible, but an opponent of capital punishment has appealed the
sentence.
   Bynum said ballistics tests showed that a pistol Simmons handed
over to former Russellville Police Chief Herb Johnston upon his
arrest was the same one used to kill five relatives.
   Irwin told the jury there was no evidence to link Simmons with
the pistol before he handed it over and no evidence on Simmons'
whereabouts during the period when the deaths occurred.
   ``He would have to be around those people to kill them,'' the
attorney said.
   About 100 spectators crowded into the courtroom at the Johnson
County Courthouse, where the trial was moved from Russellville
because of publicity about the case.
   A dozen relatives of the victims sat on two benches in the front
of the courtroom. Several wept as Bynum told the jury the names of
those slain and how they died.
</TEXT>
