<FIRST>r a PM-HudsonSuit     02-09 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hudson Suit,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hudson Thought He was Cured of AIDS, Attorney Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock Hudson never told his homosexual lover
that he had AIDS because the actor thought he had been cured of the
fatal disease, an attorney for Hudson's estate said.
   ``I don't think he believed he had the AIDS virus in his blood
anymore,'' attorney Robert Mills said during closing arguments
Wednesday in an $11 million lawsuit filed by Marc Christian,
Hudson's former lover, against the actor's estate.
   Mills rebutted claims by Christian that Hudson had deliberately
hid his illness from his lover, saying, ``You don't tell someone you
have something that you don't believe you have.''
   Christian, 35, an aspiring musician who lived with Hudson in the
last two years of his life, contends he is entitled to compensation
for the ``enhanced fear'' he suffered when he found out that his
lover had AIDS.
   But Mills said that Hudson, who had been undergoing treatment in
France with an anti-AIDs drug, was told by a doctor there that he
was ``free of AIDS'' shortly before a final bout with the disease
that killed him.
   The attorney also argued that Christian lied when he said he had
sex with Hudson about 160 times between 1983 and 1985. Mills said it
would have been impossible for Christian not to have contracted the
disease under those circumstances, and suggested the tryst between
the two men ended long before Hudson was diagnosed as having AIDS.
   He said Christian has tested negative repeatedly in tests for
exposure to the AIDS virus.
   Earlier, Christian's lawyer, Harold Rhoden, told jurors that when
Hudson and Christian became lovers in 1983, ``This was a different
world as far as AIDS was concerned'' and Christian had no fears.
   ``If they had met today, there might be an argument that he
should have known better,'' Rhoden said in his final argument to the
jury. ``But they met in 1982. All the world knew was that homosexual
men were dying in New York and San Francisco. All there was was
speculation about what this thing was that was killing gay men.
There was talk of gay cancer.''
   In 1983, when the men became lovers, Rhoden said, ``There was no
reason to use a condom. There was no reason for Marc Christian to
believe he could get AIDS from Hudson.''
   Hudson, who played the leading man to such actresses as Doris
Day, Elizabeth Taylor and Linda Evans in movies and TV, died on Oct.
5, 1985, a few months after his battle with AIDS became public.
   Christian claims that he wasn't told about Hudson's disease until
the public announcement that the star was dying.
</TEXT>
