<FIRST>r a PM-SniperTrial     02-09 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sniper Trial,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sniper Trial Goes To Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors began considering 29 charges
including attempted murder, burglary and arson against a man accused
in a series of sniper attacks.
   The jury asked Superior Court Judge Dominic F. Cresto to explain
which of approximately 75 exhibits, including a gun, bullet
fragments and casings allegedly used in the snipings, related to
each of the various charges against suspect Peter T. Trepanier.
   Before retiring to a downtown hotel Wednesday evening, the jury
also asked Cresto to repeat the definition of ``assault with intent
to commit murder.''
   Trepanier, 25, is charged with six counts of assault with intent
to commit murder and six counts of conspiracy to commit murder in
connection with nighttime sniper attacks in northern Rhode Island
between Dec. 8, 1986, and Jan. 8, 1987.
   He also is charged with seven counts of conspiracy to commit
burglary, seven counts of burglary and three of first-degree arson
in connection with a string of housebreaks and fires in the late
spring of 1987.
   He faces a maximum penalty of life in prison if convicted on the
arson charges.
   In his closing argument, defense lawyer John J. Hardiman said the
prosecution had produced no evidence linking Trepanier to the
shootings. He said Trepanier confessed to a friend because he was a
``jokester, a prankster'' and wanted to get attention.
   Prosecutor Eva Marie Mancuso said Trepanier had committed the
sniper attacks in a reckless manner, and ``reckless is intent to
murder.''
   ``Who picked up the rifle each and every time and looked in the
scope and pulled the trigger and watched the people fall?'' Mancuso
asked the jurors.
   Russell Ducharme II, a high school classmate, faces virtually the
same list of charges and will be tried later.
</TEXT>
