<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-09 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower In London, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in European trading early today
amid uncertainty over the U.S. government's ability to reduce the
nation's budget deficit, traders said. Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said the dollar fell sharply in the first hour of
trading, and its slide triggered further dollar-selling. But they
predicted the currency would soon recover.
   President Bush is to present his fiscal 1990 budget proposals to
Congress later today.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.11 Japanese yen to a closing 129.39 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 128.68 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8605 West German marks, down from 1.8720
   _1.5821 Swiss francs, down from 1.5916
   _6.3335 French francs, down from 6.3725
   _2.0999 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1140
   _1,356.50 Italian lire, down from 1,364.25
   _1.1825 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1847
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7536, compared with
$1.7423 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $394.25 a troy ounce, up
from $390.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $394.10.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $394, up from $390.85 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid of $395.58,
compared with $395.07 a week ago. Financial markets in Hong Kong
have been closed for the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.94 a troy
ounce, up from $5.88 bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
