<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 0733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Karajan     02-09 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Karajan,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famed Conductor Asks For Reprieve From Contract Due To Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Famed conductor Herbert von Karajan has asked for a
reprieve from his contract with the Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra
because of failing health, officials said today.
   The 80-year-old conductor wrote Berlin culture authorities that
he is unable to keep up with the pace demanded by his contract and
wants to rest at his home near Salzburg, Austria.
   ``He needs to reduce his workload and has submitted the
recommendations of three doctors to that effect,'' said Ludwig von
Pufendorf, Berlin secretary for cultural affairs.
   Pufendorf said Karajan's request was ``nothing dramatic'' because
the Austrian conductor has been ill for years.
   But with the letter, Karajan conceded for the first time that his
ability to conduct has been affected by a stroke, failing vision,
circulatory problems and at least five operations he has undergone
in the last 12 years.
   Pufendorf said Karajan's obligations with the Berlin Symphony had
been reduced to 6 concerts per year from 12 as earlier was required.
   Karajan has conducted the Berlin Philharmonic since 1954 and
holds the honorary title of lifetime director.
   He is also lifetime director of Vienna's Friends of Music Society
and has regularly conducted the Vienna State Opera and Salzburg and
Lucerne music festivals.
   Karajan underwent a nine-hour operation in 1976 and had surgery
again in 1979. He has been visibly hindered since a 1983 operation
on his spinal column and two later operations to remove tumors.
   He has required a supporting chair behind the conducting pulpit
for more than a year and is reported by orchestra members to be so
far-sighted that he cannot read music anymore and conducts from
memory. He also suffers from a hearing problem.
   Karajan asked in the letter to Berlin cultural affairs senator
Volker Hassemer for a break from his concert duties, noting he
continues to suffer circulatory problems as a result of the stroke
and influenza contracted last year.
   ``Karajan's health is not what it used to be,'' Hassemer said.
   ``His life is a heroic exertion against illness and pain,'' a
Vienna music critic commented.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
