<DOCNO> AP890209-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 0737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TaxCharges     02-09 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Charges,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Asher Edelman's Brother Indicted In Alleged Tax Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York financier and a Florida businessman
have been indicted for allegedly faking more than $38 billion in
trades in U.S. government securities in a massive tax fraud scheme.
   ``There were no real transactions. It was all pieces of paper
going back and forth,'' U.S. Attorney Benito Romano said Wednesday.
``It was an entirely fictitious operation.''
   Romano said the case, which allegedly involved $511 million in
illegal tax writeoffs, was at least as large as any previous case of
its type.
   Jon Edelman, 43, of Rye, N.Y., and Bernhard F. Manko, 48, of
Lighthouse Point, Fla., were charged with conspiracy to defraud the
Internal Revenue Service and numerous counts of making false
statements to the IRS or aiding others to do so.
   Edelman, the brother of prominent takeover strategist Asher
Edelman, issued a statement calling the charges ``unfounded, unfair
and unjust.'' ``I am confident that I will be completely vindicated
by the jury that will hear my case,'' he said.
   Manko's lawyer, Pamela Rogers Chepiga, said she hadn't yet
reviewed the indictment but ``based on what has come to our
attention during this long investigation, we believe Mr. Manko will
be entirely vindicated.''
   The investors were unwitting participants in the scheme and
aren't under investigation, Romano said, although ``they may have to
undergo civil audits'' to determine whether they owe back taxes.
   The investors include billionaire John Kluge, the chairman of
Metromedia Co.
   Kevin O'Brien, an attorney for Kluge, confirmed his client and
Kluge's wife, Patricia, had invested in two Edelman-Manko
partnerships. He said IRS audits of the partnerships ``have been
going on for years'' and that a settlement with all the partners to
cover back taxes was being implemented.
   Among other investors listed in the indictment was a Perry Ellis.
Prosecutors would not confirm if it was the late fashion designer,
and calls to a spokesman for Ellis's company were not returned.
   Asher Edelman was not implicated in the alleged scheme. Through a
spokeswoman, Maureen Connelly, he issued a statement: ``This is a
distressing and difficult time for our family. I will do everything
in my power to assist my brother because I do not believe he would
engage in any unlawful activity.''
   Jon Edelman and Manko were accused of creating more than $38
billion in ``pre-arranged, rigged and fraudulent'' transactions in
government securities to generate losses for investors in numerous
limited partnerships, which the investors could write off against
their taxes. The scheme involved at least 15 partnerships between
1982 and 1986, the indictment charges.
   Both Manko and Edelman were charged with conspiracy, which
carries a maximum penalty of five years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
   Manko was charged with 24 false statement counts and Edelman was
charged with 25 similar counts, each of which carries up to three
years in prison and a $5,000 fine.
   The pair also was accused of creating false trading and financing
confirmations, causing the distribution of fraudulent sales
literature and misleading lawyers who prepared offering materials
and signed tax opinion letters for some of the limited partnerships.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
