<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 0739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru   02-09 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0468,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Asks Workers Not To Strike While Negotiations Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with Walesa appealing to workers not to strike,
opposition-government talks resume, details, minor editing. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal miners at Poland's largest power plant
suspended a three-day strike today and Lech Walesa appealed to
workers not to strike while he tries to negotiate Solidarity's
reinstatement.
   ``Give a chance to the round table,'' The chairman of the free
trade union movement said in an interview on state radio just hours
after the miners ended the stoppage that had threatened to shut down
the Belchatow plant's generators.
   ``Lech Walesa is appealing for a chance for the round table. We
have been waiting for so many years, we can wait a few days more,''
he said.
   Walesa had dispatched an envoy to help settle the dispute.
   He joined a working group on trade union issues that began talks
today as part of historic ``round table'' talks between the
opposition and government that opened Monday and are expected to
last up to six weeks.
   ``Belchatow is just another proof that we should reach agreement
on the most important things as soon as possible, and restore the
organization called Solidarity,'' Walesa said in the radio interview.
   The decision to suspend the strike at Belchatow until Feb. 28
followed a visit to the mine 90 miles southwest of Warsaw by an
envoy for Walesa and management's agreement to provide most of the
pay raise sought by strikers, state radio reported.
   The strike had reduced coal supplies at Belchatow to about two
days' reserves. The strip mine at the complex fuels the plant's
generators, which produce one-fifth of Poland's electricity.
   State radio said management raised pay by $41 a month, compared
to the $59 monthly raise sought by the 4,000 strikers. On average,
workers at the plant earn $145 monthly.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban had on Wednesday had accused
Walesa's envoy, Aloyzy Pietrzyk, of encouraging the strike at a
rally attended by thousands of workers rather than trying to ease it.
   ``I must express decisive anxiety for the sense of the round
table talks and chances for agreement. Agreement is not possible
under strike pressure,'' Urban said.
   Today's working group was co-chaired by Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a top
Solidarity adviser, Romuald Sosnowski, deputy chairman of the
official trade union alliance OPZZ and Aleksander Kwasniewski,
minister of sports and tourism.
   Solidarity hopes the negotiations will culminate in the
restoration of its legal status after a seven-year ban. The
government seeks to persuade its leaders to join parliament as a
minority party.
   The Polish economy, beset by a $39 billion foreign debt, is in
ruins.
   There are chronic shortages of basic goods and supplies,
inflation was at 60 percent last year, and the declining value of
real wages has produced increased worker unrest, including 39
strikes last month.
   Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszcak first proposed the
negotiations in August during the country's worst labor unrest since
the authorities crushed Solidarity in a December 1981 military
crackdown. The only independent labor movement ever allowed in the
Soviet bloc was outlawed the following year.
   The government has sought the promise of a two-year strike
moratorium in return for reinstatement of Solidarity. But Walesa,
while acknowledging that strikes don't help the economy, insists
that workers have the right to strike over poor pay and working
conditions.
   He has repeatedly warned Communist authorities of the potential
of further unrest if economic and politial reforms are not
implemented quickly.
   State television said 4,000 of the 12,500 workers at the
Belchatow plant were on strike. The Solidarity Information Service
in Warsaw put the number at 8,000.
   Signs of labor tension appeared elsewhere in the country today.
Workers at the coke department of the Nowa Huta steel mill near
Krakow have been refusing since Feb. 1 to work overtime, Solidarity
spokesmen reported. Last year, riot police broke up a strike at the
plant, Poland's largest steel mill.
   Walesa was planning to travel to Krakow later today to talk with
workers from Nowa Huta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
