<FIRST>r a PM-BaseballBat     02-09 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baseball Bat,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harvard MBA Hired Thug to Attack Lawyer, Prosecutor Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Harvard MBA accused of bilking her employer of
$44,000 in moving expenses hired a thug to break her lawyer's leg
with a baseball bat because she didn't like his handling of the
case, prosecutors charged.
   Marsha L. Allen, 36, of South Orange, N.J., pleaded innocent
Wednesday to assault and conspiracy charges in the attack. She was
jailed on $100,000 bail.
   Ms. Allen is accused of paying $500 to a hit man to attack her
lawyer, O.T. Wells in 1987. The assault on the street put Wells in
the hospital for four days with a broken shin and caused a mistrial
in the larceny case.
   A second mistrial was declared Tuesday when her new lawyer, C.
Vernon Mason, learned of the attack and withdrew from the case.
   Ms. Allen, a Harvard Business School graduate, was charged with
grand larceny and forgery for billing Equitable Life Assurance Co.
for $44,000 in moving expenses that had already been paid by her
previous employer, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph.
   On the eve of jury selection in the case, she complained about
the quality of Wells' legal representation, but the judge proceeded
with the trial. Prosecutors had nearly rested their case when the
bat attack occurred.
   Authorities refused to say whether the attacker had been caught
or whether he had become a witness against Ms. Allen.
   If convicted in the larceny case, she could receive up to 2 1@3
to seven years in prison. The assault and conspiracy charges carry a
maximum of five to 15 years.
   Wells, 57, said Wednesday he was shocked to hear of Ms. Allen's
indictment. ``As a defense lawyer,'' he said, ``I'm outraged.''
</TEXT>
