<FIRST>r a PM-CookerExplosion     02-09 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cooker Explosion,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Killed In Plant Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A giant pressure cooker used for curing
parts at an aerospace plant exploded and blew its 14,000-pound lid
through the roof, killing a worker, authorities said.
   Three other people in the Kaiser Space Products building escaped
injury in the explosion Wednesday, said Kaiser President Bill Sidney.
   The victim, Robert Renkemeyer, 66, of Pensacola, Fla., was
standing near the hydroclave, a steam-driven kettle, when it blew
up, Sidney said.
   Renkemeyer, an equipment consultant, was a representative of the
company that built the device.
   ``It was the first time we ran it (the hydroclave) at full
pressure,'' Sidney said.
   The lid landed in a parking lot 50 or 60 feet away, Fire
Department spokesman Charlie Stimmel said. Two walls of the building
also were blown out.
   The plant supplies rocket nozzles to NASA, the Air Force and
private satellite operations.
</TEXT>
