<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Roman Catholic Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman firing from a
motorcycle shot to death a Roman Catholic pedestrian today, police
said, near a central Belfast square notorious for sectarian killings.
   Two helmeted men rode up to 33-year-old Tony Fusco in a street
off Smithfield Square, and one of them fired several shots from
close range, said police Sgt. Michael Glover.
   Fusco lived in the Falls, a Catholic district in west Belfast,
and police found a motorbike apparently abandoned by the assailants
in the adjoining Shankill, a Protestant district.
   Fusco had no connection with the security forces and his killing
bore the hallmarks of a sectarian attack, Glover said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility.
   On Jan. 18, two masked gunmen killed a Roman Catholic worker in a
store in Smithfield Market near the Protestant and Catholic enclaves
of west Belfast.
   More than 2,700 people have been killed in nearly 20 years of
political and sectarian violence in the British-ruled province.
   The Irish Republican Army is fighting to end British rule and
unite the province with the Irish Republic.
