<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 0941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-Cambodia     02-09 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Cambodia,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Resistance Leaders Offer Peace Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian resistance leaders today called for the
reconciliation of the warring factions of Cambodia in a peace plan
they said would keep the Khmer Rouge from returning to power.
   A Cambodian resistance official said he hoped the infamous Khmer
Rouge leader, Pol Pot, would have no part in a future Cambodian
government.
   Under the proposal, 2,000 United Nations personnel would
supervise the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops, who have occupied
Cambodia since they invaded the Southeast Asian country in 1978.
   Troops from the United Nations Peacekeeping Force also would be
stationed in Cambodia after the Vietnamese left to keep the Khmer
Rouge from monopolizing power, prevent a civil war and protect
Cambodia from the possibility of another Vietnamese invasion.
   The leaders also called for establishment of a provisional
government during the withdrawal that would include the three
resistance factions and the Vietnamese-backed government.
   An army made up of 10,000 men from each Cambodian faction also
would be formed. Any group with more than 10,000 men would be forced
to demoblize them. General elections would follow.
   The plan was presented by Khieu Samphan, acting head of the Khmer
Rouge and vice president of the resistance coalition; Prince Norodom
Ranariddh, son of resistance leader and former Cambodian king Prince
Norodom Sihanouk; and Son Soubert, son of guerrilla leader Son Sann.
They appeared at a packed news conference in Sihanouk's residence in
Beijing.
   Sihanouk, who is in Beijing, did not take part.
   ``We do not want a bad peace in Cambodia, we do not want to be
another Lebanon,'' said Ranariddh. ``Without national
reconciliation, we have no hope in our country.''
   Khieu Samphan said the proposal differed from an earlier plan put
forward by Sihanouk in that it attempted to address Vietnamese
concerns about a return to power of the Khmer Rouge after Vietnam
withdraws its troops.
   Vietnam also rejected the earlier plan because it said the
proposal would result in civil war in Cambodia.
   ``Under the new plan, those obstacles have been removed,'' said
Khieu Samphan. ``Now let us see if Vietnam really has the intention
of pursuing a political settlement.''
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 and toppled the
pro-Chinese Khmer Rouge, who killed hundreds of thousands of people
in a three-year reign.
   But faced with a worsening economy and pressure from its backer,
the Soviet Union, Vietnam says it will withdraw its troops from
Cambodia by September, provided the four warring parties can arrive
at a political settlement.
   Hanoi says 50,000 troops remain in Cambodia. American officials
put the number much higher.
   China also has given in to Soviet pressure to talk to the
Vietnamese.
   Last month in Beijing, in their first negotiations since 1979,
China and Vietnam agreed that China, the major backer of the
resistance coalition, would cut its aid to the guerrilla factions as
Vietnamese forces returned home.
   Last week, the Chinese and Soviet foreign ministers discussed the
Cambodian conflict for the second time in two months.
   They agreed that Vietnam's withdrawal must be supervised by an
international agency but failed to agree on the nature of the
supervision or on the make-up of a coalition government during the
Vietnamese withdrawal. They also set May 15-18 as the dates for the
first Sino-Soviet summit in 30 years.
   Tosay's proposal will be discussed during a second round of
informal peace talks with Vietnam in Jakarta, Indonesia, beginning
Feb. 19.
   The first round was held last summer.
   Ranariddh said today he opposed the return to power of Pol Pot,
whose measures to establish radical agrarian communism resulted in
massive killings.
   ``If I had to vote for Mr. Pol Pot, it would of course be
`nyet,''' he said. ``But we feel the Cambodian people should be
allowed to decide.''
   He denied charges that the resistance coalition was delaying
peace in Cambodia. ``How could we as victims be obstacles to
peace?'' he asked.
</TEXT>
