<FIRST>r a PM-NavyDeath     02-09 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy Death,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Of Navy Recruit Who Died Files $20 Million Claim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a Navy recruit who panicked
and drowned during rescue training has filed a $20 million claim
against the Navy.
   The death in March of Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis., led to
charges against instructors and reform of training practices at the
Navy Rescue Swimmer School here.
   The claim accuses the Navy of negligence in allowing Mirecki back
into the class after he had been diagnosed as having a phobia about
being held under water. It also charges the Navy of intentionally
inflicting emotional distress on the family by first reporting that
Mirecki's death was an accident.
   The family, dissatisfied with the initial report, got help from
congressmen in getting an investigation that led to charges.
   Ross Goodman, an attorney for Mirecki's family, said the claim
was sent Wednesday to the commander of the Naval Air Station in
Pensacola. He said the Navy has six months to respond. If it does
not respond, the family can file a lawsuit, he said.
   Cmdr. Dennis Hessler said the claim would be forwarded to the
Navy legal services office on the base. He would not comment further.
   Witnesses said Mirecki, who had a phobia about being held under
water, was dragged back in despite his pleas to quit the training. A
pathologist concluded that he was literally scared to death,
suffering heart failure and drowning.
   An instructor was convicted by court-martial of negligent
homicide. Four other instructors received administrative punishments
of fines or demotions. The officer in charge was acquitted of
dereliction of duty.
   As a result of the case, instructors are no longer allowed to
come into physical contact with students and must immediately cease
drilling trainees who panic, ask to quit or show signs of excessive
fatigue, the Navy said.
</TEXT>
