<FIRST>r a PM-TaintedMeat     02-09 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tainted Meat,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Says Company Sold Meat Mixed With Pet Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSH LEMIEUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company sold state agencies more
than $300,000 worth of meat mixed with pet food, beef lungs, chicken
necks and other illegal additives, Missouri's attorney general
charges in a lawsuit.
   ``When you read through this, it is frankly a modern-day horror
story,'' William Webster said of the suit seeking $800,000 in
damages from West Meat Co. of St. Louis. The suit was filed
Wednesday in state court.
   West Meat has had contracts with more than 25 state facilities,
including hospitals, prisons, the Highway Patrol Academy and the
Missouri School for the Blind.
   Webster said he had no reports of health problems related to the
allegedly tainted meat. He said the state stopped using the meat in
October and forced West Meat to pick up more than 60,000 pounds
already shipped.
   ``Between February 1986 and October 1988, the state paid West
Meat Co. more than $300,000 for meat products we believe may well
have been adulterated,'' Webster said.
   The suit said the company added pet food, spoiled meat, beef
blood, suet, beef lungs, chicken necks, kidneys, adrenal and
salivary glands, and deer and chicken meat to ground beef, pork
sausage and Polish sausage.
   ``The federal government does not allow any of these elements to
be mixed with the meat products shipped to the state,'' Webster
said. ``And the state contract is specific in its requirement for
ground beef to be 80 percent lean and 20 percent fat, with nothing
added.''
   A lawyer for the company, John Kilo, had no immediate comment
today.
   The suit charges the company, its president, Joseph A. West, and
a plant manager with fraud, violations of merchandising laws and
breach of contract.
   ``We're not alleging health and safety problems, although I'm
sure that's why the (U.S. Department of Agriculture) has these
standards,'' Webster said.
   Webster said the suit would not stop USDA from taking legal
action against the company.
</TEXT>
