<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SymphonyFunds     02-09 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Symphony Funds,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Affirmative Action Promise Releases State Money For Symphony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF HOLYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators freed $1.25 million for the
ailing Detroit Symphony Orchestra after it pledged to try to hire
more black musicians.
   The 100-member orchestra has only one black musician, even though
its home city is two-thirds black, and until recently hasn't tried
to recruit more, its chairman, Robert S. Miller Jr., said at a
legislative hearing Wednesday.
   Miller said he made no specific promise to hire a black musician
but that he hoped the orchestra would hire one before the end of the
year.
   Last year, the Legislature appropriated $2.5 million to help the
financially struggling orchestra. The orchestra got half the money
immediately, but lawmakers reserved the rest until they reviewed its
efforts to hire minorities and solve its financial problems.
   On Wednesday, an appropriations subcommittee freed the rest of
the money on a unanimous vote.
   ``I'm convinced major change has taken place and will continue to
take place in the orchestra,'' said Rep. Morris Hood, who sharply
criticized the orchestra's record on hiring blacks in a meeting last
week.
   Miller said that the orchestra would be ``out of business''
without the money.
   ``One is we can't afford to lose this money. Secondly, if we were
to be denied this money, the reason would be we didn't live up to
affirmative action goals,'' he said. ``I couldn't go to any
corporation or individual and say, `Please keep us in business, the
state just cut off our water because we're racist.'''
   Miller said symphony executives were developing a five-year plan
to take care of the money problems.
   But hiring more blacks could be more difficult because there are
relatively few black classical musicians, the symphony has only
about a half-dozen openings each year and it uses a blind audition
in which musicians are screened from the judges when they play, he
said.
   As many as 100 musicians apply for each opening in the symphony
and only one to three are black, Miller said. Musicians earn about
$50,000 a year.
   ``This is the big leagues and every kid on the sandlot wants to
play in the major leagues and Detroit is one of those,'' he said.
``In the music world, this is a high-paying, glamorous job.''
</TEXT>
