<HEAD>Tensions Eased Following Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrest and indictment of a male go-go dancer
in a string of 24 rapes over five years has eased tension in the
victimized neighborhoods, a community leader says.
   ``The heat is off,'' said Irving Chudner, president of the West
Park Community Council, which held a training session in November on
how to fend off a rapist.
   Ronnie Shelton, 27, was indicted Tuesday on 152 counts, including
rape, kidnapping, burglary, robbery, assault and grand theft. James
O'Meara, an assistant county prosecutor, said it was the biggest
