<FIRST>r a PM-ChildrenBurned 1stLd-Writethru a0487 02-09 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children Burned, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0487,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Say Father Apparently Set Himself and Two Children
on Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with separate burning incident elsewhere
in Mississippi, and recast to clarify sequence of events in Flowood incident.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLOWOOD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman had an amiable conversation with
her ex-husband shortly before he apparently locked himself and their
two children in his truck, doused everyone with gasoline and set a
fire, police said.
   Benny Bilbrew, 29, and his children, Benny Carl, 6, and Fecia, 5,
were dead by the time rescuers arrived.
   Elsewhere in Mississippi, a Grenada teen-ager was in critical
condition today after her boyfriend poured gasoline on her head and
set her on fire, police said.
   In the Flowood fire, investigators believe the children may have
been dead before Bilbrew set the blaze Wednesday in the parking lot
of the hospital where his former wife worked, said George McKay, an
arson investigator for the Rankin County sheriff's department. All
three bodies were burned beyond recognition.
   Bilbrew's ex-wife, Connie, a cafeteria worker at the Woman's
Hospital, told authorities he called her 1{ hours before the bodies
were found.
   ``There was nothing indicating what was ahead,'' said police Lt.
Johnny Watkins. ``He was not violent on the phone and there was
nothing out of the ordinary.''
   However, Watkins said Mrs. Bilbrew told police the couple
divorced about two years ago but lived together for about a year
until they split up again a few weeks ago.
   There were no witnesses to the setting of the fire, but McKay
said he thought the children ``had met their demise before they ever
came to this parking lot.''
   ``I don't know anybody's children who wouldn't scream and holler
... if someone was rendering these children helpless. Someone would
have heard them scream. There are people in this parking lot all the
time and on the road,'' he said.
   McKay said hospital personnel noticed the fire only after the
explosion of some shotgun shells in the locked, burning truck. He
said no gun was found in the truck, although a knife was recovered.
He also said no gasoline container was recovered.
   Mrs. Bilbrew was inside the hospital when the fire occurred, and
Watkins said she had to be sedated after being informed of the
deaths. He said she wouldn't be questioned at length until Friday at
the earliest.
   Watkins said the woman had custody of the children, but they had
been visiting their father, a self-employed concrete worker, since
Monday because an ice storm had closed schools this week.
   In the Grenada incident, a 17-year-old whose name was not
released was in critical but stable condition at a Memphis, Tenn.,
hospital, with burns from the waist up, said said Grenada police
Capt. Joe E. Durr.
   The girl and her boyfriend ``had argued the night before and he
drove to her house shortly before noon Wednesday to collect clothing
and other items,'' Durr said. ``It was then that he allegedly poured
the gas on her and lit it.''
   Morrell Sykes, 21, of Duck Hill, was freed on $10,000 bail after
being charged with aggravated assault.
</TEXT>
