<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-UNForces     02-09 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-UN Forces,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Demands Removal of U.N. Commander for Nazi Comparison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0541 to avoid duplication of DataStream reference
number.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel today demanded the removal of a Norwegian
U.N. commander who compared the expulsion of nearly 80 people from
Israeli-controlled territory in south Lebanon to steps Nazis took in
World War II.
   Lt. Col. J.E. Karlsen, commander of the Norwegian battalion in
the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon, or UNIFIL, made the comparison
last week in a private meeting with Israeli officials.
   He was protesting the expulsions of 79 Lebanese from the Israeli
security zone, which he said were carried out by Israeli-backed
Christian forces and Lebanese working for the Israeli Shin Bet
security service. His remark was leaked to the press, and Israel's
Foreign Ministry complained at the time.
   However, the ministry now wants him removed because he was quoted
by a newspaper as saying his comparison succeeded in drawing
attention to the expulsions, a Ministry spokesman said on condition
of anonymity.
   ``In light of the fact that the battalion commander is repeatedly
uttering his despicable opinions, Israel expects the UNIFIL command
to draw the proper conclusions regarding the officer,'' a Foreign
Ministry statement said.
   The dispute over Karlsen, 43, began Thursday when Israeli and
U.N. officers met to discuss the expulsions.
   ``In World War II, my fellow countrymen sacrificed their lives in
the struggle against the Nazis, who were trying to expel Jews from
Norway. Nowadays, you behave in south Lebanon exactly as the Nazis
did,'' newspapers later quoted him as saying at the meeting.
   After Nazi forces invaded Norway in 1940, they expelled people
from much of the north to create a military zone. They burned homes
and other buildings.
   Israel set up the 6-to-10-mile deep security zone north of its
border in 1985 when it withdrew the bulk of its forces from Lebanon,
ending a three-year occupation that followed Israel's 1982 invasion.
   The zone is patrolled by Israeli soldiers and the South Lebanon
Army, an Israeli-backed militia largely made up of Lebanese
Christians. Most of the population of the area is Shiite Moslem.
</TEXT>
