<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Tezuka     02-09 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Tezuka,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cartoonist Osamu Tezuka Dead at 60</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Osamu Tezuka, one of Japan's leading cartoonists and
animators, died of stomach cancer Thursday. He was 60.
   Tezuka, a medical doctor from Osaka, published his first cartoon
in 1946 while he was a medical student at Osaka University.
   His masterpiece _ ``Tetsuwan Atom,'' or ``Astroboy'' _ swept the
nation when it was publshed in a magazine starting in 1951. The
cartoon was shown on Japanese TV in the 1960s and the 1980s. It also
was shown in the United States.
   Tezuka's cartoons and films, often dealt with medical ethics,
life and science, said Akiko Fukumura, spokeswoman for Tezuka
Productions.
   His works won many prizes during his 40-year career. Among them
were two experimental films, ``Jumping,'' a winner of the
International Animation Festival in Zagreb, Yugoslavia in 1984, and
``Broken-down Film,'' which won the 1985 International Film Festival
in Hiroshima.
   Tezuka is survived by his wife, Etsuko, and three children. A
private funeral will be held Sunday, with a a public memorial at a
later date.
</TEXT>
