<FIRST>r i AM-HirohitoFuneral     02-09 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito Funeral,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hirohito's Funeral Rites to Last 13 Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's funeral rites Feb. 24 will last
more than 13 hours, the palace said Thursday.
   Palace officials released a final draft of the funeral day
schedule, beginning with an early morning religious ceremony at the
palace and finishing with another at 8:50 p.m. at the imperial
mausoleum, 28 miles outside Tokyo.
   The estimated 10,000 guests,including dignitaries from 134
nations, will begin assembling hours before the start of the
67-minute state funeral, scheduled to begin just before noon in the
Shinjuku Imperial Gardens in central Tokyo, the officials said.
   The day has been designated a public holiday.
   After one minute of silence, Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, the
leaders of the two houses of Parliament and Supreme Court Chief
Justice Koichi Yaguchi will address the funeral gathering.
   Foreign heads of state or government or their representatives
will then line up to pay last respects to Hirohito.
   Hirohito, who died of intestinal cancer Jan. 7 at age 87, served
as the high priest of Japan's Shinto religion, and four of the five
scheduled rites will be religious in nature.
   Controversy has been growing regarding governmental funding of
the funeral. Leftist opposition leaders, academics and citizen
groups have charged that the government is violating a
constitutional separation of church and state.
   But palace officials, in unveiling funeral preparations, said
most funeral guests would not be involved directly in religious
ceremonies or would be allowed to decide for themselves if they
wanted to take part.
   The Sojoden-no-gi, the main Shinto funeral rite lasting 47
minutes, is to proceed in a sanctuary adorned with sacred trees and
a Shinto archway just before the state funeral starts.
   Imperial family members will attend, while the mourners,
including the prime minister and other government leaders, will
observe the ceremony from two tents facing the sanctuary.
   The state funeral will be followed by a 95-minute procession to
the western Tokyo suburb of Hachioji and a Shinto entombment
ceremony extending until 8:20 p.m.
   ``The state funeral ends when the procession reaches its
destination. ... From there on it's up to participants to decide for
themselves if they will continue to take part,'' one official said.
</TEXT>
