<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     02-09 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seoul Urges North Korea to Continue Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A delegate to parliamentary talks with
North Korea on Thursday urged the communist nation to retract its
decision to call off a meeting between the two nations because of
joint U.S.-South Korean military exercises.
   ``Along with all people who yearn for fruitful results of the
dialogue, we feel very much regretful (about the North Korean
decision),'' said Rep. Chae Mun-shick, a former National Assembly
speaker.
   He called on North Korea to continue the talks ``in the interest
of national harmony and unification.''
   Chae heads a South Korean delegation to parliamentary talks with
North Korea. The talks cover a non-aggression pact and other
measures aimed at easing tension between the nations.
   Delegations of lawmakers from both sides have met seven times to
prepare for a joint meeting of their full legislatures. Another
round of talks was to be held Friday.
   North Korea announced Wednesday that the Friday meeting must be
postponed until after the joint ``Team Spirit'' training exercises
are over.
   Chae said the joint exercises are defensive and have been
conducted annually since 1976.
   ``In fact, our side has informed North Korea in advance of the
exercises and even invited them to observe the open and defensive
nature of the training,'' he said.
   He said North Korea also conducts joint military exercises with
the Soviet Union.
   Chae noted the North Korean radio broacast came only 30 minutes
after the breakdown of another set of talks between the nations
aimed at preparing the first meeting of their prime ministers.
   ``This all gives me the impression that they had a pre-planned
scenario to embarrass our side and dump responsibility on us,'' he
said.
   The military exercises have been conducted in various parts of
South Korea since 1976 to train the joint command system of the two
countries in the event of an invasion. North Korea invaded South
Korea in 1950, starting a three-year war.
   This year's ``Team Spirit'' exercises began last week with about
200,000 troops taking part. The maneuvers usually last about two
months.
   Wednesday's talks bogged down over North Korea's insistence the
exercises be halted. The two sides are scheduled to meet again March
2.
</TEXT>
