<FIRST>r a AM-Molest     02-09 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Molest,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Known for Adopting Third-World Children Charged with Sexual
Abuse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Theadore cq in 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ANGELES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer who adopted at least 16
children, mostly from Asia and Central America, has been charged
with sexual abuse amid indications of ``wanton sexual activity'' at
his home, a prosecutor said.
   A 12-year-old blind girl from Guatemala told investigators she
was molested repeatedly by Theadore E. Ripley, 46; his adopted son,
Kori Ripley, 30, a former reserve sheriff's deputy; and at least one
juvenile in the home, according to documents filed in Clallam County
Superior Court.
   Police are also investigating claims of sexual abuse by several
children in the Ripley household, which once was praised in a
nationwide broadcast by author and minister Norman Vincent Peale,
the documents said.
   In the documents, county Prosecutor David H. Bruneau wrote that
``such disclosures by multiple victims and multiple abusers show a
pattern of wanton sexual activity within that residence, and
certainly tend to corroborate the continuing disclosures by the
victim of the sexual abuse of her.''
   The elder Ripley will plead innocent when he is arraigned Friday
on a charge of second-degree statutory rape, said his attorney,
David Johnson. The charge carries a maximum penalty of 10 years in
prison and a $20,000 fine.
   ``Ted adamantly denies the charges. We're hoping for a speedy
resolution of the case and we're confident that ultimately the truth
will come out,'' Johnson said.
   Ripley remained free on personal recognizance but was barred by
court order from trying to visit the girl.
   Denise Thomas, social work supervisor in the local Child
Protective Services office, said the girl had been declared a ward
of the state and placed in a foster home, but three minor children
remain with the Ripleys.
   State officials have begun an investigation of the household,
including a review of the license for Adoption Advocates
International, an adoption agency at the Ripley home.
   Last month Kori Ripley pleaded innocent to a charge of sexual
assault in 1984 on the Guatemalan girl, who had been living with
Ripley and his wife, Merrily, since infancy. Trial was set for March
17.
   Mrs. Ripley, who runs the adoption agency, has not been charged
in the latest case and is not mentioned in any of the associated
court papers.
   In July a juvenile boy living in the Ripley home was convited of
assaulting the same girl and was sentenced to 22 weeks in a juvenile
institution. It was that case that led to the charges against Kori
and Theadore Ripley, Bruneau said.
   Peale praised the Ripleys in a nationwide broadcast for adopting
children from other countries and bringing them to the United
States, according to newspaper accounts which said there were 18
children in the household in February 1980.
</TEXT>
