<DOCNO> AP890209-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-EuropeTrade     02-09 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Europe Trade,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Sales to Europe May Reach Level of Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales by Americans to 12 West European
countries will reach the level of imports by the end of this year if
present trends continue, a Commerce Department official said
Thursday.
   ``That's not a prediction, it's a projection,'' Franklin J.
Vargo, deputy assistant secretary for Europe, told reporters.
   He told the House Small Business Committee that U.S. exports to
the European Economic Community rose more than 25 percent last year
while U.S. imports rose 5 percent, changes which cut the U.S. trade
deficit with the community to $13 billion from $24 billion in 1987.
   Another year of those trends and the deficit will disappear, he
said.
   He pointed out that U.S. companies and their affiliates sold more
than $600 billion worth of goods to the 12 countries last year,
three times as much as to Canada and four times as much as to Japan.
For many years after World War II, U.S. exports to western Europe
exceeded imports. In recent years, that trend has reversed.
   The 12 countries in the community are Britain, West Germany,
France, Italy, Denmark, Ireland, Belgium, Holland, Luxembourg,
Spain, Portugal and Greece. They are now trying to turn their
association into a single market, almost as integrated as the United
States, by the end of 1992. Some Americans see that movement as a
threat of a ``Fortress Europe'' which would keep out American goods.
   ``On balance 1992 should benefit the United States,'' Vargo told
the committee.
   He said faster growth should furnish a better market for U.S.
goods. But he said there are many problems remaining, especially in
the common standards being set by the 12 governments for imported
products and the possibility that tests of U.S. products to see that
they meet those standards will be required on European soil.
   Frank S. Swain, the Small Business Administration's chief counsel
for advocacy, urged American companies to set up a subsidiary in one
of the 12 countries.
   ``The consensus is that the EEC single internal market will
materialize, if not by 1992, then shortly thereafter,'' he said in
testimony for the committee.
   ``Establishing a subsidiary in the EEC would be the safest
option, although it also could be the costliest choice initially,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890209-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Reform Bjt   02-09 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Reform, Bjt,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>`New Class' Sabotaging Gorbachev's Reforms, Article Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``new class'' of Communist Party and government
bureaucrats is sabotaging President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms,
and the Soviet leadership is unable to combat it, a daring magazine
article says.
   Direct criticism of Gorbachev's reform program has remained
largely off limits, despite his policy of greater openness in
society. But Sergei Y. Andreyev's article in the Leningrad monthly
Neva is one of the harshest and most detailed attacks yet on the
communist system and Gorbachev's policies.
   The party general secretary _ the post Gorbachev holds along with
the presidency _ remains ``an inaccessible and exemplary figure''
and his attempt to make the system democratic still leaves the
people politically powerless, Andreyev wrote.
   ``All decisions of the upper powers are carried out only to the
extent that they are advantageous to the new class,'' Andreyev said
in the 28-page essay in the January issue of the literary and
political magazine.
   He said the new class is a ``production and managerial
apparatus'' of 14 million party bureaucrats, government ministers
and managers.
   Gorbachev himself has launched a war on bureaucrats who interfere
in day-to-day decisions about production and has tried to transfer
some of their power to local officials and factory managers. He
often blames bureaucrats for the slow pace of reform.
   But Andreyev said Gorbachev hasn't gone far enough and that the
new class controls the government and party.
   ``Both the Soviet (government) and party organs have turned out
to be subordinate to its interests,'' he said, adding that the model
government of the people has been replaced by the ``dictate of the
new class.''
   Andreyev, 34, is a biologist and plant director who said he
represents a new political club called ``Alternative.'' He mocks the
party's claim of popular support and uses ``gensec'' in referring to
the general secretary. The abbreviation may be used in colloquial
speech but isn't seen in the state-run press.
   Andreyev's use of the term ``new class'' appeared to be a
reference to Milovan Djilas' book ``The New Class,'' which
criticized the Communist system. The Yugoslav politican and writer,
who broke with Yugoslavia's leadership, said in the 1957 book that
the Communist system had produced a new class of privileged leaders
instead of a classless society.
   The new class, Andreyev wrote, is largely responsible for the
lack of major improvements in the Soviet economy and for impediments
to democracy that have arisen since Gorbachev came to power in March
1985 and the next month launched his program of reforms known as
``perestroika.''
   ``We must admit that the economy is in a crisis. ... For the
years since the memorable April plenum of the Communist Party
Central Committee, the economy didn't get on track. ... The crisis,
in this way, is deepening,'' Andreyev said.
   He said politicians no longer tell the producers what to do, but
that ``new class'' uses party bodies to give orders to the society.
   Perestroika is moving slowly not because of some mysterious
forces, but because of ``well-organized sabotage,'' he wrote.
   Some Soviets have written letters to the editor claiming factory
managers and others are sabotaging Gorbachev's reforms by
withholding food and consumer goods from store shelves.
   The 57-year-old Kremlin chief has admitted perestroika is not
moving as quickly as he had hoped, but reaffirmed his commitment to
reform and said the people support his program.
   Andreyev, however, said the current leadership is partly to blame
for economic woes because it hasn't kept its promise to let
unprofitable businesses go bankrupt.
   ``The good promises made from high rostrums hang in the air and
are far from fostering the strengthening of faith in the possibility
of perestroika,'' he said.
   The article also criticized Gorbachev's political overhaul under
which a new, more powerful legislature and presidency are to be
created this year. Andreyev said the offices of Communist Party
general secretary and president _ or head of the legislature _
should not be held by the same man, as Gorbachev proposes, because
the lawmakers are supposed to check the work of the top political
figure.
   Despite the party's claim that it serves the people and is in the
``vanguard of society,'' the general population ``practically never
had access to the real levers of power and doesn't have it now,
either,'' he said.
   On the world scene, the Soviet brand of socialism has a
``demoralizing influence'' and is perceived as ``capable of leading
only to collapse,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
