<FIRST>r w AM-CapitalGains 1stLd-Writethru a0584 02-09 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Gains, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS byline spelling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tax-Writer Says No to Bush's Capital-Gains Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the
House Ways and Means Committee, on Thursday promised all-out
opposition to President Bush's proposal to reduce the tax on capital
gains.
   ``I'm not about to tell the wage earners in Chicago that they
should pay a higher tax than stockbrokers,'' Rostenkowski said in a
speech to the National Press Club.
   ``I personally will strongly resist any efforts to undo (the
1986) tax reform, including the return to a preferential tax rate
for capital gains,'' Rostenkowski said.
   He spoke eight hours before Bush was delivering a package of
budget recommendations that was expected to include a call for lower
taxes on capital gains, which are profits from the sale of stocks,
real estate and other assets.
   There is strong support in Congress, principally among
Republicans but even among some Democratic liberals, for taxing
capital gains at a lower rate than applies to wages and other
income. Capital gains and most other income now are taxed at rates
of either 15 percent, 28 percent or 33 percent.
   Seventy percent of capital gains are taken by people with incomes
above $100,000 a year.
   Rostenkowski has emphasized on other occasions that restoring a
preference for capital gains would threaten the landmark 1986 tax
overhaul, which was characterized by a significant cut in tax rates
for most Americans and a reduction or elimination of several
deductions and credits.
   Rostenkowski sounded another familiar theme at the press club:
Despite Bush's campaign pledges, any realistic plan for reducing the
budget deficit must include tax increases, he said.
   ``If President Bush is willing to put all spending and revenues
on the table, he will find a Congress willing to make the tough
choices that real deficit reduction requires,'' he said.
   The veteran lawmaker said that then-President Reagan had also
made a no-tax pledge but that during his eight years in office,
``Reagan raised more taxes than any peacetime president.'' Reagan
signed more than a dozen tax increases.
   Rostenkowski said the 1990 budget left by Reagan was based on
highly optimistic projections on how the economy will perform.
   ``Does anyone really believe that real growth will be 3.2 percent
this year? Or inflation at 3.8 percent? Or short-term interest rates
at 6.3 percent?'' Rostenkowski asked. ``Those are the numbers in the
last Reagan budget.
   ``I hope I don't see them in President Bush's budget,'' he said.
``I don't want to raise taxes, but I won't participate in a sham.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
