<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael J. Fox received 5,000 threatening
letters from a woman who was upset he got married, a district
attorney investigator said Thursday.
   Tina Marie Ledbetter, 26, was arrested in Westlake Village last
week but was released after posting $100,000 bail, said the
investigator, Gary Schram. Ledbetter faces a possible charge of
making terrorist threats, officials said.
   Fox, 27, who won two Emmys for his portrayal of the insufferable
conservative son of liberal parents on the NBC series ``Family
Ties,'' married his former co-star on the show, actress Tracy
Pollan, last July. They are expecting their first child.
   Fox began receiving unsigned letters last February and they
continued after his marriage, said Al Albergate, spokesman for the
Los Angeles County district attorney's office.
   ``The letters threatened the lives of Fox, his wife and their
yet-to-be-born child,'' Albergate said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Academy Award-winning actress Patricia
Neal will be on hand when her first film in seven years has its
premiere in her hometown April 28.
   ``An Unremarkable Life,'' also starring Shelley Winters, will
open at Knoxville's Tennessee Theater and will serve as a
fund-raiser for the Patricia Neal Rehabilitation Center for stroke
victims, the Knoxville Journal reported Wednesday. Winters, herself
a two-time Oscar winner, also plans to attend.
   ``I hadn't done a film in, I guess, seven years,'' the
63-year-old actress told the Journal in a telephone interview from
her New York apartment. ``This role came up. I liked it, but we
couldn't come to terms financially. Then they came back with a
better offer and I grabbed it. It's a fabulous part.''
   In the film, directed by Amin Q. Chaudri, Neal and Winters play
sisters who share a house. When Neal's character falls in love, her
sister has trouble adapting to the prospects of being alone.
   Neal won an Oscar for her performance in ``Hud'' in 1963 before
suffering a series of strokes in the 1960s. She recovered and went
on to receive an Oscar nomination in 1968 for her role in ``The
Subject Was Roses.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As ``The Six Million Dollar Man,'' actor Lee
Majors was equipped with bionic legs that enabled him to run at
amazing speeds. In an upcoming CBS series pilot, he will travel by
bus.
   Majors, who recently completed the second ``The Bionic Couple''
TV movie with Lindsay Wagner for NBC, hopes to return to the weekly
lineup this fall with ``Travelin','' said Barney Rosenzweig, head of
television for Weintraub Entertainment.
   Majors will play a man who wanders around the country by bus. The
role of his female companion is currently being cast, Rosenzweig
said.
   Series production begins Feb. 28 in Philadelphia. Janet
Herrington of the city's film office said scenes will be shot in
historic areas of the city and near the Art Museum.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's Supreme Court has denied a
motion that could have meant a reduction in the prison sentence of
singer Johnny Paycheck, convicted in a 1985 barroom shooting.
   Without comment, the court on Wednesday rejected a motion that
sought to prohibit Paycheck's sentencing under an Ohio law that sets
mandatory prison terms for certain felonies.
   Although Paycheck was sentenced to a term of seven to 9{ years
Monday in Highland County Common Pleas Court, lawyers said granting
of the motion could have made the singer eligible for a reduced
sentence.
   Paycheck, 50, will not be eligible for parole for more than 5{
years as a result of the December 1985 shooting in a Hillsboro
tavern.
   Paycheck, whose real name is Donnie Lytle, is being held in the
Highland County jail pending transfer to the state prison system
next week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer can rest assured that New
Orleans tow truck drivers know their job. After all, they impounded
his car.
   While the governor was in meetings Wednesday at the World Trade
Center complex in the city's business district, parking officials
towed his car, which was parked in a taxi zone.
   Roemer had arrived from Baton Rouge by helicopter and was whisked
downtown in his family's black-and-gray vehicle driven by aides,
said spokeswoman Sidney Coffee. The car was impounded at about 1
p.m., but the governor's staff had it back before he left two hours
later.
   ``They towed it off, we offered to pay for it, and they wouldn't
let us pay,'' Coffee said. ``It was really kind of funny.''
</TEXT>
