<SECOND>PM-Commissioner Plea,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highway Commissioner Pleads Guilty To Extortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former state highway commissioner today
pleaded guilty to extorting a $127,000 payoff from a construction
company.
   Sam Waggoner, 67, of Newton, also pleaded guilty to filing false
federal income tax returns. A highway commissioner for 21 years
until he resigned Dec. 31, Waggoner could receive up to 29 years in
prison and $550,000 in fines.
   No sentencing date was set.
   Prosecutors said the former commissioner of Mississippi's central
highway district has agreed to testify in other white-collar crime
cases.
   A related FBI investigation of purchasing practices has resulted
in corruption charges against 57 county supervisors in 26 counties.
   Fifty-two have been convicted or have pleaded guilty, and the
Legislature overhauled county purchasing practices to lessen the
potential for graft.
   Waggoner pleaded guilty to accepting cash from Freddy Rogers of
Freddy Rogers Construction Inc. of Morton and underreporting his
income by $190,500 in 1984-86.
   On Wednesday, a judge sentenced former Southern District Highway
Commissioner Bob Joiner to six years in prison for extortion and
fined the 59-year-old Waynesboro man $100,000 for tax evasion.
   The third member of the state Highway Commission, Northern
District Commissioner Zack Stewart, hasn't be charged with any crime.

