<FIRST>r a AM-WGAAwards     02-09 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WGA Awards,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writer's Guild Announces Nominees For Screenplay Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Box office hits ``Big'' and ``Who
Framed Roger Rabbit'' were among 10 screenplays nominated Thursday
by the Writer's Guild of America for outstanding achievement in 1988.
   The awards, to be presented March 20, are divided into two
categories _ original screenplays and screenplays adapted from
another medium.
   Nominated for best original screenplay were ``Big'' by Gary Ross
and Anne Spielberg; ``Bull Durham'' by Ron Shelton; ``Working Girl''
by Kevin Wade; ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' screenplay by John Cleese,
story by Cleese and Charles Crichton; and ``Rain Man,'' screenplay
by Ronald Bass and Barry Morrow, story by Morrow.
   The nominees for best screenplay adapted from another medium were
``Dangerous Liaisons'' by Christopher Hampton; ``The Unbearable
Lightness of Being'' by Jean-Claude Carriere and Philip Kaufman;
``The Accidental Tourist'' by Frank Galati and Lawrence Kasdan;
``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' by Jeffrey Price and Peter Seaman; and
``Gorillas in the Mist: The Adventure of Dian Fossey'' screenplay by
Anna Hamilton Phelan, story by Ms. Phelan and Tab Murphy.
   During the last 40 years, nominees and winners for the WGA awards
have closely matched the Oscar nominees and winners. Out of 80
awards given by the two groups from 1947 through 1987, 60 were
identical.
   All 10,000 members of the WGA were eligible to vote for the
nominations from among more than 200 screenplays. All guild members
now vote on winners.
</TEXT>
