<SECOND>AM-People-Busey,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publicist Says Actor Improving, Eager To Get Back To Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Gary Busey is making good progress and
is eager to get to work on a film that was put on hold until he has
recovered from a near-fatal motorcycle crash, his publicist said.
   ``Hopefully he will be able to go back to work and get back in
the saddle soon,'' Carla Schalman said Wednesday.
   Busey, 44, underwent brain surgery after the Dec. 4 crash in
Culver City. He was thrown from the bike and struck his head against
a curb. He was not wearing a helmet and has actively campaigned
against proposals to make helmets for motorcycle riders mandatory.
   Ms. Schalman said an independent feature film, ``Howling at the
Moon,'' was put on hold when Busey was injured. The movie describes
the last day in the life of frontier lawyer John Wesley Harding.
Busey was cast to play the lead, Ms. Schalman said.
   Busey, who was initially treated at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center,
was transferred to a private facility for rehabilitation therapy.
The name of the facility has been withheld to afford Busey some
privacy, Ms. Schalman said.
   She said the actor was deluged with cards, letters and gifts
shortly after the crash, but she was unsure if he had responded to
them.
   ``The main focus has been on physical therapy, getting better and
back in the swing,'' she said. ``He's making really good progress.
He seems excited about that progress. He's been talking on the phone
and taking exercises.''
   Ms. Schalman said she didn't know when he would be released.
   She said she had not talked to Busey to see if he had changed his
mind about the helmet law. ``The helmet law hasn't come up yet. His
concern, his doctors' main concern and everyone's main concern has
been getting him back well and recovered.''
   Busey gained fame after performing the title role in the 1978
movie, ``The Buddy Holly Story.'' His other film credits include
``Lethal Weapon,'' ``A Star is Born,'' ``Carny'' and ``The Bear.''
</TEXT>
