<DOCNO> AP890209-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AzoresCrash-Families     02-09 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Azores Crash-Families,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends, Relatives Call Crew Members Dedicated, Enthusiastic</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Azores Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot and first officer of the Boeing
707 that crashed in the Azores, killing all 144 people on board,
were described by friends and family Thursday as enthusiastic,
dedicated aviators.
   ``He just loved motion,'' said Craig Abington, a pilot and major
with the Tennessee Army National Guard who had known pilot Leon
Daugherty since 1975.
   ``Most of his efforts were invested in the flying business. He
really loved it,'' he said.
   In all, seven crew members, all American, and 137 Italian
tourists died when an Independent Air Corp. charter jet slammed into
a mountain Wednesday in the Azores Islands. The plane, en route from
Italy to the Dominican Republic, was approaching landing for a
refueling stop.
   Daugherty, 41, of Nashville, was engaged to one of the four
flight attendants who died, 26-year-old Yvette Murray of Marietta,
Ga.
   Also killed were first officer Sam Adcock, 36, of Nashville;
flight engineer Jorge Gonzalez, 34, of Rex, Ga.; and flight
attendants Sabrina Cromarty of Atlanta; Helen Ziegler, 56, of Warner
Robins, Ga.; and Angela Urban, 24, of West Palm Beach, Fla.
   John Matthews, a pilot and friend of Adcock's for five years,
said he was ``real easy to get along with. He was very professional
and loved to fly.''
   Daugherty had logged about 8,000 hours in the air and had worked
for Smyrna-based Independent for about two years after stints in the
Navy and Army, said Maj. Hooper Penuel, the Tennessee guard's public
affairs director. Daugherty joined the guard in 1974.
   Abington said Daugherty was still active with the guard.
   ``He just loved airplanes and helicopters and cars and
motorcycles,'' he said. ``You can't just use an adjective here or
there for a person like that.''
   Two of the Georgians killed in the crash, Gonzalez and Mrs.
Ziegler, were last-minute replacements, called in after regularly
scheduled employees were unable to make the flight.
   Gonzalez, 34, was the sole support for his mother, wife, sister
and son, all of whom are natives of Colombia.
   Mrs. Zeigler, 56, a flight attendant, had made the same flight
many times before, said her husband, Kenneth, himself a former pilot
for Independent Air.
   ``When she left, I said to her, `Helen, you shouldn't have to go
out again. It's just not right,''' said Ziegler. ``But she would
never turn down a flight. That wasn't even supposed to be her
flight. They said they needed her and she went.''
   ``This is so final. We had been married for 35 years,'' he said.
``You just don't find people like that anymore. She was a very
strong person. She kept our whole family together.''
   E.H. Raney of Shelbyville said his 27-year-old daughter, Shan
Raney, was the Independent flight attendant who was supposed to have
made the fatal trip. ``She had gotten the flu and couldn't go to
work,'' Raney said. ``But she's terribly upset because she lost a
lot of friends on the plane.''
   Ms. Murray's father, Tom Murray of Atlanta, said his daughter
loved to fly and was not afraid, despite recent reports of crashes
and maintenance problems in the airline industry. Flying ``was a big
thing for her,'' Murray.
   ``Because she was going to be married, she didn't think they'd
let her continue flying,'' he added. ``She probably would have been
out of this thing in a month or so.''
</TEXT>
