<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     02-09 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Round Up 175 Palestinians in Hebron Soccer Stadium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers rounded up about 175 Palestinians in
the West Bank on Thursday and forced them to sit blindfolded and
bound for up to 16 hours in a soccer stadium, Arab and Israeli
witnesses said.
   Riots erupted outside the Megiddo Prison for a second straight
day after Arab reports circulated that a second Palestinian had died
of wounds sustained in a riot there Wednesday, Israel radio reported.
   Police said an Israeli settler killed when his car went up in
flames in the West Bank on Wednesday appeared to be the victim of a
terror attack, but an investigation was continuing.
   ``It is reasonable it was terrorist,'' West Bank police commander
Haim Malcha said on Israel radio. ``Even though the results are
preliminary, it seems unreasonable there was any other cause.''
   Israel radio said laboratory tests determined the car was not hit
by a gasoline-filled bottle or firebomb because no glass fragments
were found.
   But the tests uncovered a large quantity of flammable liquid in
the driver's seat, the radio said. It said police suspected the car
was either hit with a flaming plastic bottle or that gasoline was
thrown at it.
   The settler, Albert Jerassi, 38, was the 16th Israeli to die
since the Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories began
Dec. 8, 1987. At least 379 Palestinians have died, most from Israeli
gunfire.
   Arab reports said 17-year-old Nidal Zuhdi Deeb died after being
shot by troops trying to quell Wednesday's disturbance at Megiddo
Prison in northern Israel. The army said it was checking the report.
   The radio said Thursday's riot was quickly subdued by prison
guards and there were no casualties.
   In the West Bank and Gaza Strip, troops shot and wounded nine
Palestinians, including a 9-year-old girl and a 10-year-old boy from
Gaza's Mughazi refugee camp, Arab doctors said. Both were struck in
the head with rubber-coated steel bullets, they said.
   The army did not confirm any of the shootings.
   Troops with lists of suspects began rounding up Palestinians
overnight in the West Bank city of Hebron, detaining about 175 in a
soccer stadium where they were forced to sit cross-legged on the
ground until 2:30 p.m. Thursday, Arab witnesses and an Israeli
photographer said.
   Many were in their pajamas and had their hands tied behind their
backs. Some were blindfolded.
   The Palestinians apparently were suspected of planning an action
against Israeli authorities in Hebron, Israeli sources said.
   Arab witnesses said the detainees were given water but no food.
One of the Palestinians was slapped twice by a soldier, they said.
   Dozens of the detainees were later moved from the soccer field,
apparently to detention centers for questioning, the witnesses said.
The rest were sent home.
   Also Thursday, the army sealed three Palestinian homes and
demolished a fourth belonging to Palestinians accused of attacks on
Israelis.
   One of the residences sealed belonged to Said Dadu, who allegedly
threw explosives at the home of Trade and Industry Minister Ariel
Sharon in the Arab quarter of the walled Old City.
</TEXT>
