<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     02-09 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hezbollah Pulls Out of Southern Lebanese Villages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JBAA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian-backed Moslem militiamen on Thursday
pulled out of captured villages in the south under terms of a peace
accord that ended their nine-month fight with Syrian-allied forces.
   The fundamentalist fighters of Hezbollah, or Party of God, took
refuge in hideouts in mountains near Israel's security zone. But
there was no immediate move by their Shiite rivals, the Amal
militia, to take over the villages of Jbaa and Ein Bouswar.
   Some angry villagers said they want both militias to stay out.
   Ahmad Raad, a member of Jbaa's municipal government, walked out
of his bomb-scarred house and shouted: ``We don't want militiamen
any more: Neither Amal nor Hezbollah.
   Fatima Qobeissie, a housewife, yelled: ``The militias have ruined
our village! We don't want them back!
   ``Three rockets hit our house, but luckily we were hiding in a
bomb shelter,'' she said. ``Who's going to compensate us for our
losses?''
   The withdrawal was part of a peace treaty reached last month
under supervision of Syria and Iran.
   The pullout came 39 days after the radical Hezbollah seized Jbaa
and Ein Bouswar in an assault on Amal last month. Amal recaptured
most of the mountainous region in a string of counter-offensives but
failed to dislodge Hezbollah from the mountaintop villages near
Sidon.
   Hezbollah official Saeed Mattout said in Jbaa that his forces
withdrew before dawn to bases on Mount Safi near the western end of
the security zone.
   Israel set up the buffer zone, which runs up to 10 miles deep
into neighboring Lebanon, when it withdrew most of its occupation
army from south Lebanon in 1985.
   Mattout said Hezbollah may maintain bases on Mount Safi under the
Damascus agreement.
   Jamal Qalqas, an Amal representative, toured the two villages
after Hezbollah militiamen withdrew and called on civilians who
evacuated the area during the fighting to return home.
   At least 173 people were killed in the fighting that broke out in
south Beirut Dec. 31 and spread to the Shiite-dominated south. It
was the latest eruption in a power struggle for control of Lebanon's
1 million Shiites, the country's biggest sect.
   Hezbollah advocates creating an Iranian-style Islamic republic in
Lebanon.
   The more secular and nationalist Amal favors a multisect
government in Lebanon in which Moslems would hold an equal share of
power with traditionally dominant Christians.
   In the Chouf mountains southeast of Beirut on Thursday, gunmen
shot and killed a senior aide of Walid Jumblatt, a Druse Moslem
military leader, police said.
   Anwar Fatayeri, political bureau member of Jumblatt's Progressive
Socialist Party, was gunned down in an ambush on a road nine miles
from Beirut. No one claimed responsibility.
</TEXT>
