<FIRST>u a AM-RoamingTerrorist Bjt-2takes   02-09 1061</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Roaming Terrorist, Bjt - 2 takes,1084</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accused Terrorist Found Tools To Kill In K marts, Art Stores</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese man who allegedly came within two
days of blowing up a Manhattan building avoided suspicion by buying
ingredients for his deadly bombs on a monthlong terrorist shopping
spree to art supply, sporting goods and discount stores in 11
states, documents reveal.
   Yu Kikumura, reputedly a member of the Japanese Red Army who
received terrorist training in Lebanon's Bekka Valley, entered the
United States illegally last March 8 and then made his zigzag,
7,000-mile trek in a used Mazda.
   Court papers show he stayed at motels, bed and breakfast rooms
and campgrounds, his travels apparently financed in part by money
drawn from a Swiss bank account.
   ``He didn't tell jokes, he didn't laugh, in fact, he looked like
a guy with a lot of problems, with a lot of troubles on his mind,''
Carmen Brown, whose Huntington, W.Va., campground was one of the
many places Kikumura stayed during his trip, said in a telephone
interview with The Associated Press.
   His odyssey ended at a New Jersey Turnpike reststop on April 12,
two days before officials said he intended to bomb a Navy recruiting
center housed in a Veterans Administration building in retaliation
for the 1986 U.S. bombing of Libya.
   New Jersey State Trooper Robert Cieplensky said he noticed
Kikumura acting erratically. As Kikumura drove off, Cieplensky
stopped him and found in the back seat a package containing three
bombs _ hollowed-out fire extinguishers filled with gunpowder, lead
shot and with switchs and triggers. He also found a map which
authorities later said showed possible other targets, including
three New York City college campuses.
   ``I would hope that at some point he would have made another
mistake,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney John Lacey, who helped
prosecute the case. ``But based on his experience and background, I
have very little doubt that he would have succeeded in killing
people with those bombs.''
   On Tuesday, Kikumura, claiming the allegations against him were
fabricated, was sentenced to 30 years in prison for explosives and
weapons charges and carrying false documents, including a
passport.Kikumura's attorney, civil rights lawyer William Kunstler,
said an appeal was planned.
   Investigators used receipts found in Kikumura's car to piece
together his movements in the month before his arrest. His travels
took him to roadside motels through America's heartland, across its
colonial byways and into the Bible Belt. The documents show he spent
time in Massachusetts, New York, New Jersey, Ohio, Michigan,
Illinois, Missouri, Tennessee, Kentucky, West Virginia and
Pennsylvania.
   Along the way, he bought items such as gas cans, a diet scale,
flash bulbs, electrical wire and tape, cements, epoxy glue and fire
extinguishers.
   ``The materials he bought to make the bombs are most always used
for legitimate purposes,'' Lacey said. ``And when he traveled around
to buy the different materials, it decreased the risk of somebody
piecing together what he was doing.''
   Kikumura's favorite store was K mart, authorities said.
   ``Turn Mr. Kikumura loose near a K mart and a sporting goods
store and in a matter of hours, literally, he can make what was
found in his car today,'' U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. said
during Kikumura's sentencing hearing this week.
   Alito made a rare appearance in court to present the evidence
against Kikumura, who had a record for explosives charges and is
reputedly a member of the notorious Japanese Red Army, a radical
leftist group formed in the 1960s to promote world revolution.
   On May 1, 1986, Kikumura had been arrested at Amsterdam's
Schiphol airport with two pounds of TNT and several bomb detonators.
He spent four months in jail after the courts found that authorities
had conducted an illegal search at the airport.
   His whereabouts over the next few months are sketchy. But from
August 1986 until his arrival at New York's John F. Kennedy
International Airport last March 8, he used a stolen and altered
passport to travel through Italy, France and Switzerland,
authorities said.
   Prosecutors also said an informant has provided evidence that
Kikumura spent some time at a terrorist training camp in Lebanon's
Bekka Valley.
   Two days after his arrival in the United States, Kikumura was
sent by a roommate service to the Manhattan apartment of Chris
Brande.
   ``He was quiet and polite,'' Brande, an accountant, told the AP.
``Looking back now I can see a few strange things, like he said he
was a tourist but I never saw a camera.
   ``He didn't look like a terrorist type, whatever that type is. He
just seemed like a nice guy.''
   Kikumura bought a used Mazda 626 at Central Motors in the Bronx
within a week of his arrival in the United States, and he set out on
his tour.
   On March 16, he was in Gloucester, Mass. He traveled west on
March 22 on Interstate 80 through New Jersey and Pennsylvania and
stayed overnight at the Williams House bed and breakfast in Avon
Lake, Ohio. The next night he stayed at Barnicks Bed and Breakfast
in Diamondsdale, Mich.
   The Harrison Hotel in Chicago was his home the night of March 24.
Two days later, he was in Mark Twain's hometown of Hannibal, Mo. He
also stayed March 28 in the Biltmore Hotel in Union City, Tenn., and
on March 29 at Clardy's Guest House in Murfreesboro, Tenn.
   It didn't make his first known bomb-parts purchase, until March
30, when he stopped in an art supply store in Nashville, Tenn., to
buy two cans of aluminum powder.
   The next day he went to K mart in Lexington, Ky., and in two
visits bought gas cans, a diet scale, coffee-maker accessories, a
special glue, contact cement, electrical wire and electrical tape.
   On April 1, he arrived at the Browns' campground.
   Mrs. Brown said she and her husband, Herbert, noticed bruises on
Kikumura's hands and a split lip. Prosecutors theorize he may have
been injured by a slight blast when mixing the highly combustable
powder used in the bombs.
   While in Huntington, Kikumura went to an electronics store and
bought a toggle switch, circuit tester, phone jacks, phone plugs and
wire.
   He left for New York on April 3 and stopped at Smiley's Motel in
Hurricane, W.Va., on his way back to Manhattan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
