<FIRST>r i AM-NATO-Summit     02-09 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO-Summit,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Summit Expected in May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and the leaders of the 15
other NATO nations probably will hold a summit in Brussels in May, a
source in the Western alliance said Thursday.
   No final decision has been made on a date or place for the
anticipated summit but the source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said ``May is most likely.''
   Bush has been expected to have an early meeting with other
leaders of the North Atlantic Treaty Organizations to discuss
pressing NATO issues and mark the alliance's 40th anniversary.
   On a trip through Western Europe, Secretary of State James A.
Baker III will meet in the Belgian capital Feb. 16 with the NATO
secretary-general, Manfred Woerner of West Germany, and
representatives of the member nations, officials said.
   A specific date for the summit probably will be set soon after
Baker's trip, the source said, adding: ``We don't have a signal from
Washington that it's going to be in May,'' but ``we're putting
together ... possible dates that it could be.''
   There has been speculation the summit would take place in London
in early June, when foreign ministers of the NATO countries are
scheduled to meet, but the source said some NATO delegations prefer
alliance headquarters in Brussels as a site, especially because of
the anniversary year.
   The gathering comes at a time when the West must respond to
dramatic changes in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev of the Soviet Union has captured
public attention, particularly in Europe, with promises to reduce
Soviet troop strength and military spending.
   His pledges appear have reduced the public perception of the
threat from the East, causing concern in NATO about continued
support for defense spending.
</TEXT>
