<FIRST>r a AM-People-Powell     02-09 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Powell,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Powell Steadily Improving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lewis F. Powell Jr., a retired Supreme
Court justice, is steadily improving from his bout with pneumonia,
but doctors have not determined when he can leave the hospital, a
spokeswoman said Thursday.
   Powell, 81, is being treated with antibiotics after developing
pneumonia Tuesday.
   ``He's been resting. He's real alert, and he looked great,'' said
Cindy Hamilton, a spokeswoman at Baptist Medical Center.
   Powell also has been exercising by walking in the hospital
corridors.
   The justice, who spent 15 years on the Supreme Court, was in
Jacksonville as a member of a panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals. He complained of dizziness Monday and was taken by
ambulance to the hospital, where he was admitted for an acute
respiratory infection.
   Powell retired from the nation's highest court June 26, 1987,
citing concerns about his health as one reason. He had suffered from
prostate cancer.
