<FIRST>r i AM-ArmsSeizure     02-09 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Seizure,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arms May Have Been Headed for Bolivia, Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVONA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 170 tons of arms confiscated from a
Danish freighter might have been destined for rebel movements in
Bolivia and Colombia, the Italian news agency ANSA said Thursday.
   Police boarded the Jenstar on Wednesday and seized 5,217 cases of
Czechoslovak rifles, pistols, submachine guns and amunition valued
at about $8.8 million, the agency said.
   Tiziana Parenti, the investigating magistrate assigned to the
case, told ANSA the shipment was believed to be part of a larger
plot to arm revolutionary movements in Bolivia and Colombia.
   The magistrate said the operation may involve shipments worth up
to $29.4 million.
   The agency said police found two manifests on the ship: one was
for Italian authorities and it listed the cargo as machine parts;
the other listed the arms and destinations in South American, ANSA
said.
   The boat brought the cargo from Hamburg, West Germany, to Savona,
where it was to be loaded on another ship and sent to it final
destinations, according to the agency.
   Police arrested six Danish crew members aboard the ship, ANSA
said. Another five suspects _ four Belgians and an Italian _ were
arrested at the Genoa airport, according to the agency. The charges
included illegal transportation of military arms, munitions and
equipment, ANSA said.
