<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FemaleBishop Bjt   02-09 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Female Bishop, Bjt,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consecration Of Female Bishop Won't End Controversy Over Women Of
the Cloth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Episcopal Church is mustering full pomp and
ceremony to install Barbara Harris as the first woman bishop in a
2,000-year Christian line dating to the apostles.
   The worldwide attention expected for Saturday's events goes far
beyond anything the Episcopal Church usually confronts and reflects
a debate that has simmered within church ranks and now threatens to
spill over into Christianity at large.
   Some 8,300 tickets have already been distributed for the
consecration. Demand has forced church officials to move the
ceremony from St. Paul's Cathedral in Boston to the cavernous Hynes
Convention Center, which has room for spectators, a chorus of 130,
television cameras and a large contingent of journalists.
   Though no one is announcing any last-minute effort to block the
appointment, a good many of the attendees can be expected to hold
their breath when the ritual requires presiding Bishop Edmund
Browning to intone: ``If any of you know any reason why we should
not proceed, let it now be made known.''
   The 58-year-old former head of a left-wing religious publishing
company has been a subject of some controversy within the church
since Sept. 24, when the Episcopal Diocese of Boston elected her
suffragan, or assistant bishop.
   Women have been priests in the Episcopal Church since 1976. But
becoming an bishop is a question of much higher magnitude. Harris
would become the first woman to reach that height in any of the
three major branches of Christianity _ Roman Catholicism, Eastern
Orthodoxy and Anglicanism _ that trace bishops in a direct line back
to the Apostles of Jesus.
   After the election last September, debate quickly ensued across
the country among 118 church committees responsible for confirming
the election.
   A traditionalist faction of the Episcopal Church, led by the
Evangelical and Catholic Mission in Austin, Texas, rallied in
opposition to Harris' elevation. Now, prelates and observers on both
sides of the issue are concerned that the stakes may be even larger
than the unity of the Episcopal Church, which is a branch of
worldwide Anglicanism.
   The Roman Catholic, Eastern Orthodox and Anglican churches have
been involved for more than a decade in discussions over easing
their centuries-old differences. ``And they have made great
progress,'' said James Solheim, a spokesman for the Boston Episcopal
diocese. ``For Roman Catholics, the idea of a woman standing at the
altar representing Christ is totally unacceptable.''
   Pope John Paul II in December issued what Solheim called
``ominous noises'' about the impending consecration of Harris. The
pope warned of ``painful and deplorable consequences'' of the
Episcopal Church going forward with the consecration of a female
bishop. ``The constant line of tradition, common to all the
churches, cannot be so easily interupted,'' he said.
   ``This has great ecumenical consequences,'' said Bishop Donald
Davies of the Evangelical and Catholic Mission in Austin.
   A female bishop might be acceptable if all of Christianity
approved in an official way, he said. ``But we're a small church. In
taking the leadership in this, we just denigrate the progress we've
made in having communion throughout the world.''
   Barbara Clementine Harris this week was the calm at the center of
the storm, recovering from a head cold on a church retreat. She
could not be reached for comment because she has no access to a
telephone at the retreat, Solheim said.
   Some of the opposition to her elevation stemmed from her
decidedly leftist political views which she conveyed in the
publication, The Witness, issued by the Episcopal Church Publishing
Co. in Philadelphia, where she has been an Episcopal priest since
1980.
   The periodical has published articles supporting homosexual
rights and the Nicaraguan Sandinista government and criticizing the
church for failing to fully bring women into church leadership.
   The Rev. Jerome Politzer, president of the traditionalist Prayer
Book Society in America, described Harris as ``pro-Marxist. Her
writings are snide and sarcastic. She is unfit to be a bishop.''
   Some also have questioned Harris' qualifications because of her
lack of a college degree and full seminary training.
   A black woman and a veteran of the civil rights marches of the
1960s, Harris has been outspoken for civil rights and feminism and
she is unapologetic about her views.
   But at a recent news conference in Boston, Harris sought to ease
concerns by saying her work for the Boston diocese would focus on
sacramental and pastoral duties rather than involvement in political
affairs.
</TEXT>
