<SECOND>AM-Irish,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunman Kills Roman Catholic Pedestrian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman firing from a
motorcycle shot and killed a Roman Catholic pedestrian Thursday near
Smithfield Market, a central Belfast square known for sectarian
slayings, police said.
   The Ulster Volunteer Force, an outlawed Protestant group, claimed
responsibility in a telephone call to the British Broadcasting Corp.
   Two helmeted men on a motorcycle rode up to Tony Fusco in a
street off the square, and the motorcycle's passenger fired several
shots from close range, said police Sgt. Michael Glover.
   Fusco, 33, lived in the Falls, a Catholic district in west
Belfast. Police found a motorcycle apparently abandoned by the
assailants in the adjoining Shankill, a Protestant district.
   The Ulster Volunteer Force said Fusco was a member of the mainly
Catholic Irish Republican Army. The outlawed IRA's legal political
wing, Sinn Fein, denied it. Glover said Fusco had no connection with
the security forces.
   Two masked gunmen shot and killed a Catholic worker Jan. 18 in a
store in Smithfield Market, which is situated near the Protestant
and Catholic areas of west Belfast several hundred yards north of
City Hall.
   More than 2,700 people have been killed in nearly 20 years of
political and sectarian violence in the British-ruled province.
