<FIRST>r w AM-MarielCubans     02-09 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mariel Cubans,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Cubans Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight Mariel Cubans ordered deported by special
federal review panels were flown back to their homeland Thursday,
the Justice Department said.
   The Cubans were being flown aboard a government plane from
Birmingham, Ala., to an airport outside Havana, said Joe Krovisky, a
Justice Department spokesman.
   The eight are among 33 who have been ordered deported since
December, when Justice Department panels began reviewing the cases
of 400 Cubans who entered this country illegally during the
so-called Mariel Flotilla of 1980.
   Another 400 or 500 Cubans will be placed on the review list once
they finish serving prison terms.
   Many convicts and mentally ill people were among the 125,000
people who came from Cuba during the Mariel Flotilla.
   The repatriation review boards were set up last year in the wake
of riots by Cuban detainees held at federal prisons in Atlana and
Oakdale, La.
   A total of 23 Cubans have been sent back to Cuba since the review
process resumed in December.
   Repatriation efforts were begin briefly in 1984 but suspended at
the insistence of Cuban President Fidel Castro.
   Krovisky said the Justice Department planned to make flights
every two weeks as each review panel, sitting for that period,
completes its work.
   Three parole and two repatriation panels are schedule to convene
every two weeks, the department said.
</TEXT>
