<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Nepal-Religion     02-09 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Nepal-Religion,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Hindus Convicted for Converting to Christianity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Hindus were found guilty of
converting to Christianity, and they were sentenced to one year in
prison by a court in Nepal, the world's only Hindu kingdom, it was
reported Thursday.
   The constitution declares that Nepal is a Hindu state, and
Nepalese law bans converting from Hinduism to any other religion.
   The sentence was announced Wednesday by the district court at
Bhadrapur, 190 miles southeast of Katmandu, according to the
Nepalese news agency RSS.
   Christian sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said about
200 Nepalese are awaiting trial on charges of converting from
Hinduism.
   In October, police arrested two foreigners from the London-based
Christian organization Operation Mobilization. They are to stand
trial Feb. 28 on charges of ``preaching Christianity and causing
disturbances to Hinduism.'' If convicted, they could face up to six
years in prison.
   The two, David McBride, 33, of Columbia, Pa., and Mervyn Budd,
26, of London, Ontario, Canada, were being held at Phidim, 150 miles
east of Katmandu.
