<FIRST>r w AM-VAHospitals     02-09 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-VA Hospitals,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospitals Very Short of Supplies, Nurse Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY B. DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supplies are so short in Veterans
Administration hospitals that nurses are scrounging thee little
souvenir bars of soap and shampoo bottles from hotels to bring to VA
patients, a nurse told Congress on Thursday.
   Supply accounts are frequently raided to pay salaries and avoid
layoffs, an outside medical administrator told the House Veterans
Affairs Committee.
   Claudette Morissey, a nurse at the Brooklyn, N.Y., veterans
hospital and prsident of the Nurses Organization of the Veterans
Administration, said in testimony submitted to the hearing, ``At one
VA hospital in the south, nurses were frustrated by the refusal of
(the) prosthetics (department) to supply wheel chair cushions for
patients on the long term care unit.
   ``The nurses obtained a $25 donation, went to the local
upholstery store and purchased a large foam mattress, and with an
electric knife borrowed from the mother of one of the nurses, cut
the foam to make wheel chair cushions for their patients.''
   She did not identify the hospital, nor the hospital in other
anecdotes:
   ``Nurses in one hospital brought in souvenir hotel soaps and
shampoos for the patients, and in another, brought and cut large
bars of soap in small pieces for patients to use.''
   At her own hospital, she said, ``We cannot properly monitor
diabetic patients when there are no lancets to do finger sticks, no
Chem Sticks for blood samples and no insulin syringes to use to give
insulin if it is needed. This is the situation I have faced over the
past month at my facility and I thank God there has been no crisis
because of it.''
   A Soviet report last week of hospital patients getting AIDS from
unsterilized needles ``is a startling reminded to us in this country
that mistakes can happen when the system starts to cut corners and
workers perform daily under inordinate pressure as we do in the
VA,'' she said.
   At congressional hearings last September, VA officials said they
faced a $600 million to $1 billion shortfall in their $10.54 billion
budget for medical care in the current fiscal year.
   Edward Derwinski, President Bush's nominee for head of the VA and
secretary of veterans affairs when the VA becomes a cabinet
department next month, said Tuesday he had met with Budget Director
Richard Darman.
   Declining to say if he thought a supplemental appropriation is
needed for the current fiscal year, Derwinski said the meeting with
Darman ``didn't result in any figure changes, but I hope it'll
increase his sensitivity.''
   L. Thompson Bowles, vice president for medical affairs at the
George Washington University Medical Center, a member of a VA
advisory committee and a consulting surgeon to two VA hospitals,
said, ``By moving funds from other accounts, the Department of
Medicine and Surgery was able to remain near the congressionally
mandated 194,720 employment level,''
   Kenneth I. Shine, dean of the University of California at Los
Angeles Medical School, told the committee that next year's medical
budget should be $12.42 billion, a 14 percent, or $1.48 billion,
increase over this year's total, instead of the $186 million
increase proposed in President Reagan's budget. Four veterans
organizations have endorsed a similar amount for next year.
</TEXT>
