<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages     02-09 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Cleric Hopes Hostages Will Be Released `Shortly'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spiritual leader of the group believed
holding most of the American hostages in Lebanon said he hopes their
ordeal will end ``shortly,'' according to a letter released Thursday.
   Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah wrote to Peggy Say, sister of
American hostage Terry Anderson, ``I hope your human suffering will
end shortly and I promise to do all my best to help you.''
   Anderson, 41, of Lorain, Ohio, was kidnapped March 16, 1985,
while serving as chief Middle East correspondent for the The
Associated Press.
   He is the longest-held hostage in Lebanon among 15 Westerners,
including nine Americans, three Britons, one Irishman, one Italian
and a Belgian.
   Fadlallah, 53, is the spiritual leader of the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God. It is made up of Shiite Moslem
fundamentalists and is believed to be an umbrella group for
underground factions that have claimed the abduction of most
Westerners missing since 1985.
   Mrs. Say, who is in Damascus to meet with Syrian officials
cooperating in the effort to obtain the hostages' freedom, gave
reporters here a copy of the message she received recently.
   Fadlallah's letter, dated Dec. 31, said, ``We hope the
governments involved will take into account the humanitarian aspect
of the hostages issue and the grief of their relatives.
   ``We, as religious people, will strive hard to solve this tragic
problem with respect for the good ties which link us to the American
people.''
   Syrian officials said they would arrange a meeting between Mrs.
Say and Fadlallah, now in Iran, if he transits Damascus on his way
back to Lebanon.
   ``We would like to emphasize that regardless of the rulers'
interests, our relations with other peoples should be friendly and
based on good faith,'' Fadlallah said in his letter.
   The religious leader, who has disavowed any responsibility for
the kidnappings, wrote in response to letters from Mrs. Say, the
Journalists' Committee to Free Terry Anderson and other humanitarian
and media groups in the United States.
</TEXT>
