<FIRST>r p AM-Democrats     02-09 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown Says He's Committed to South's Importance to Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incoming Democratic Party chairman Ronald H.
Brown, moving swiftly to calm dissenters to his election, told
Southern party officials Thursday he is ``absolutely committed'' to
the region's importance.
   ``The South is crucial to the future of the Democratic Party,''
Brown told a meeting of the Southern Caucus of the Democratic
National Committee.
   On the eve of his unopposed election to the chairmanship, Brown
preached unity and the importance of reaching out to all elements of
the party.
   Many southerners opposed his election because of past ties to
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and Jesse Jackson.
   ``I say let's give him a chance,'' said John Baker, chairman of
the Alabama Democratic Party, who once threatened to boycott the
national party if Brown became chairman.
   ``A lot of Democrats feel excluded, feel rejected,'' said Baker.
``They feel there's no room in the party for them because they are
moderate or conservative in philosophy.''
   The Alabama chairman said it would be ``helpful, first of all, if
he'd (Brown) acknowledge that we've got that problem.''
   A 47-year-old partner in one of the capital's largest and most
politically active law firms, Patton, Boggs and Blow, Brown will be
the first black to head a major political party.
   He will succeed Paul G. Kirk Jr., whose election four years ago
was opposed by many southerners concerned about his service as a top
aide to Kennedy.
   But Kirk ended his term with high marks for unifying the party
and many of the Democrats who had opposed him in 1985 pleaded with
him to seek re-election. But Kirk turned them down and is returning
to his law practice.
   Brown made the rounds of regional caucuses and also spoke to the
Association of State Democratic Chairs.
   He told the state party leaders, ``We've got a difficult job
ahead, we've got tough adversaries. ...They don't care much about
truth or about decency.''
   Addressing the concerns of Southerners, Brown said, ``I don't
want to be chairman of a party that writes off any region of the
country.''
</TEXT>
