<FIRST>r i AM-India-Fires     02-09 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Fires,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire in TV Studio Kills 36, Injured Famous Actor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire broke out during taping at a
television studio in the south, killing at least 36 people and
injuring one of India's best-known actors and at least 54 other
people, news reports said Thursday.
   The fire on Wednesday destroyed the studio near Bangalore, 1,100
miles south of New Delhi, United News of India said.
   The studio was filled with actors and technicians making a
television show at the time. The injured included Sanjay Khan, a
well-known actor and director, who received burns over 60 percent of
his body, the news agency said.
   There was no word on the cause of the fire.
   In Bombay on Thursday, a large fire swept through the Sahar
international airport, disrupting flight schedules for more than six
hours, officials said.
   No casualties were reported in that blaze, which began in some
duty-free shops in the airport terminal building, a senior airport
official said on condition of anonymity. The entire airport was
evacuated, officials said.
   There was no word on what started the fire.
   At least 20 firefighters fought the fire for six hours, news
agencies said. There was no immediate report on damages.
   Flights could not land until the fire was brought under control
because safety regulations require that firefighters be on standby
for all landings in case of emergencies.
