<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LonesomeDove     02-09 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lonesome Dove,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Lonesome Dove' Ranks 14th on All-Time Miniseries List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS' ``Lonesome Dove'' wound up 14th on the list
of all-time highest-rated network miniseries.
   CBS estimated, based on figures from the A.C. Nielsen Co., that
about 40 million viewers tuned in each night of the four-night
Western epic that revived network television, at least for the week.
   CBS Entertainment President Kim LeMasters got a tip of the hat _
literally _ from competitors at an industry luncheon here Thursday.
Brandon Tartikoff of NBC and Brandon Stoddard of ABC presented
LeMasters with a cowboy hat at the annual International Radio and
Television Society newsmakers luncheon at the Waldorf Astoria.
   ``Lonesome Dove'' had an average, four-night rating of 26.1 and a
39 share, far above the below-30 shares that network had guaranteed
to advertisers, delighting the third-place network and contributing
to combined three-network shares that soared into the 80s on some
nights. The season-to-date average for the three networks had been
68.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with televisions.
The share is a percentage of sets in use.
   The top three network miniseries remain ``Roots,'' ``The Thorn
Birds'' and ``Winds of War,'' all of which aired on ABC.
   ``Lonesome Dove'' became CBS' third-highest-rated miniseries
behind ``Master of the Game,'' which ranks 11th on the all-time-high
list, and ``Scruples,'' at 13th. The list does not include two-part
movies.
</TEXT>
