<FIRST>r w AM-BRF-JointExercise 190   02-09 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-Joint Exercise, 190</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Exercise Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 troops from the United States,
Britain, Canada and Australia will join forces in California next
month for a rare joint training exercise, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   The exercise, codenamed ``Caltrop Force,'' will bring ``ground,
air and amphibious forces ... to Fort Hunter-Liggett, Calif.,'' the
Pentagon said.
   ``The central California maneuver area will allow the units to
operate against an imaginary foe, under the control of a U.S.
brigade headquarters from Fort Ord, Calif. The exercise will be
staged from March 15 to April 1.''
   While U.S. armed forces frequently exercise with units from each
of the four countries, it is unusual for all four nations to
schedule a joint exercise, according to the Pentagon.
   Britain, Canada and Australia plan to send a battalion of about
500 men each, the Pentagon added. They will be joined by a U.S. Army
battalion, as well as by small Marine Corps, National Guard and Army
Reserve units.
   An Australian Navy ship, the Tobruk, also will participate along
with American helicopter units, the Pentagon said.
</TEXT>
