<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1626EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HelicopterFlak Bjt   02-09 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helicopter Flak, Bjt,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighbors of Children's Hospital Critical of Helicopter Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helicopters serving one of the few Midwest
hospitals to perform heart transplants on children are drawing flak
from neighbors who say the aircraft are overused and pose a
potential safety hazard.
   However, a hospital official countered Thursday that Children's
Memorial Hospital has taken great pains to keep the helicopters'
disturbance to a minimum since it began using them a couple of years
ago.
   Herbert Malkind, planning committee chairman of the Park West
Community Association, said the hospital has failed to obey zoning
laws and an agreement with community groups to use the helicopters
only for emergencies, trips longer than 40 miles and for its own
staff.
   Malkind testified Wednesday before a hearing officer gathering
material on the hospital's application to be certified as a
pediatric heart transplant center by the Illinois Health Facilities
Planning Authority.
   ``The helistop is controversial in Lincoln Park from the
standpoint of safety concerns and noise problems,'' Malkind said of
the surrounding affluent North Side neighborhood.
   ``We think it's a very good hospital, we really do,'' Frank
Giarrizzo, a Lincoln Park resident who also attended the hearing,
said Thursday. ``We just say, `Live up to the agreements, follow the
laws.'''
   The suggestion that Children's has violated its agreements or the
law is ``totally untrue,'' said Edward Horner, president of the
Children's Memorial Foundation and a representative of the hospital
at the hearing.
   Because donor hearts remain viable for just four hours outside
the body, they must be flown into Children's, requiring more
helicopter flights, he said.
   However, he said the hospital goes out of its way to keep
helicopter use to a minimum and noted that the total number of
helicopter landings and takeoffs actually dropped last year compared
to 1987, from 201 to 195.
   There is no restriction on the number of helicopter flights
allowed, Horner said.
   Children's has performed five heart transplants since its first
one last May. ``Our estimate is we do not believe more than 12 of
these (transplants) could or would be done a year, based on the
difficulty of getting donor hearts,'' Horner added.
   He said quarterly reports on helicopter use, distributed to
community groups, clearly reflect the hospital's proper use of the
vehicles.
   ``We took extraordinary efforts to involve the community'' when
the helicopter service began, he said Thursday. Sound testing
equipment was placed in homes and businesses and community hearings
were held to address safety and noise, said Horner.
   He said he believes only a few people are complaining, and that
they are not representative of most of the neighborhood.
   Giarrizzo said area residents do not oppose certification for
Children's, but believe the hospital should be required to tighten
up its use of helicopters before it is granted official status as a
transplant center.
   In addition to the many homes around the hospital, a school and a
church are right across the street, Giarrizzo said.
   Safety concerns center on the hospital's use of twin-engine
helicopters, which carry more fuel than the single-engine
helicopters Children's originally agreed to use and could presumably
cause greater damage in the event of a crash, he said.
   The hospital's bid for certification ``has very little to do with
helicopters,'' said Horner.
   ``It has a whole lot to do with the societal obligation of
Children's, which transcends Lincoln Park. It's a societal
obligation that an institution of this ilk must fulfill.''
   Children's cardiology service treats about 4,000 young people a
year, about 10 percent of whom require heart surgery of some sort,
making the hospital one of the largest of its kind in the country,
Horner said.
   The board of the planning authority is to act on Children's
application for certification at its March 2 meeting, said authority
executive secretary Ray Passeri.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
