<FIRST>r p AM-Jackson-Mayor     02-09 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson-Mayor,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Won't Run for DC Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson flatly denied Thursday any
interest in running for mayor of the District of Columbia and said
he would never move to unseat Mayor Marion S. Barry Jr.
   ``I've expressed no interest in the job,'' Jackson said after
leading an anti-drug rally at a city high school. ``Under no
condition would I run against Marion Barry.''
   Asked later if he would run if Barry decided not to seek
reelection in 1990, Jackson said, ``I have expressed no desire to be
mayor.''
   Instead, Jackson said he plans to continue taking his anti-drug
message to school children around the country and press the Bush
administration on its promise to make fighting drugs a top priority.
   Jackson, who owns a home here, has been mentioned as a possible
mayoral candidate since December, when Barry's repeated visits to
the hotel room of a drug suspect triggered the worst political
crisis in Barry's 10 years as mayor.
   Recent polls show Barry's popularity has dropped and remains low
since a federal grand jury began probing his ties to the drug
suspect, former city employee Charles Lewis.
   Barry has not yet said publicly if he will seek another term.
   Speculation over Jackson's possible candidacy grew after he said
in early January he was worried about Barry's health. The mayor also
said that the two had a ``moving, tearful'' prayer session after
Jackson telephoned him from Africa.
   Jackson also refused to comment when asked Thursday whether he
was still concerned about Barry's health and personal habits.
   During his speech, Jackson made no mention of Barry's troubles,
and characterized his formal civil rights ally as a close personal
friend.
   Barry, who arrived for the rally about 15 minutes late, was
greeted with a mixture of cheers and catcalls from the 1,000
students in the school's auditorium. By contrast, Jackson received a
standing ovation.
</TEXT>
