<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 2002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Angola     02-09 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNITA Envoy Seeking More U.S. Weapons, Raises Doubts About Cuban
Pullout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An envoy for the rebels fighting the Angolan
government said Thursday he is seeking additional U.S. anti-aircraft
and anti-tank missiles to combat a predicted offensive by
Cuban-backed troops.
   Tony da Costa Fernandes, who holds the rank of brigadier general
in the Union for the Total Independence of Angola, also urged the
United States to improve the monitoring of Cuban troop pullout from
Angola against any attempts by Cuba to cheat.
   Fernandes said at a news conference that he was ``satisfied with
the meetings'' he has had with U.S. officials about his
organization's requests.
   But he also criticized parts of the U.S.-sponsored agreement
signed last December that calls for the pullout of all Cuban troops
from Angola and grants independence to neighboring Namibia from
South African rule.
   ``There are flaws in the agreement that are not of our liking,''
he said.
   Fernandes urged the United States to use ``sophisticated means''
to monitor the troop withdrawal, claiming that Cuba had sent in
fresh troops to replace some of the 3,000 who were pulled out under
the agreement last month.
   He said there were no accurate figures for Cuban troops, who have
been helping the Marxist Angolan government since it gained
independence from Portugal in 1975. Troop estimates from a variety
of sources have ranged from between 50,000 and 60,000.
   Under the agreement, Cuba has promised to provide accurate
figures by April 1, once the 90-member U.N. observer group is in
place. The commander of the force, Brazilian Gen. Pericles Ferreira
Gomes, says his 10-nation group will rely on Angolan and Cuban
figures during the withdrawal.
   But Fernandes said that could lead to cheating. He said the
27-month pullout timetable means Cuban troops will remain in Angola
one year after Namibian independence, giving Cuba a chance to send
some of the troops to its ally Namibia.
   Based on troop movements and weapon stockpiling, Fernandes
predicted that Cuban-backed Angolan troops would launch two or three
offensives against UNITA in southern Angola between May and July,
before the Aug. 1 deadline for the Cubans to move northward of the
15th parallel.
   He said UNITA needs long-range artillery pieces, anti-aircraft
and anti-tank missiles. The United States already provides UNITA
with shoulder-fired Stinger anti-aircraft missiles and TOW anti-tank
missiles as part of a covert aid package estimated at $15 million
annually.
   Fernandes said UNITA needs more arms because the Soviets recently
delivered to Angola 12 Cuban-flown MiG-25 fighter jets and some
Mi-35 helicopter gunships.
   A U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, says
Fernandes met with several people in the State Department but she
declined to elaborate. ``We provide appropriate and adequate
assistance to UNITA,'' she said, but said policy bans discussion of
covert aid.
   Much of UNITA's arsenal, which is mostly of Soviet origin, was
brought in through South African-controlled territory. But this has
stopped under terms of the tripartite agreement, along with the $80
million South African annual aid package, he said.
   In a separate interview, Fernandes said UNITA had ``increased the
capability of all airfields'' to accommodate long-range aircraft,
indicating that these bases would be used to resupply the
organization now that its land lines have been blocked.
   He also said UNITA has a two-to-three year stock of military
equipment it received through South Africa and from three African
countries which he declined to name.
   Despite reports to the contrary, UNITA enjoys ``moral and
diplomatic support'' from about 15 other African states, he added.
   At the news conference, Fernandes said he had asked the United
States to send a signal to several African nations, such as Senegal
and Kenya, of support for a dialogue between UNITA and the Angolan
government.
   Such a signal would spur these governments to put pressure on
Angola to negotiate a cease-fire and power-sharing agreement with
the rebels, he said.
   UNITA will not accept a government offer for clemency because
``we are not criminals,'' Fernandes said, preferring to increase its
military struggle to place additional pressure on the government to
negotiate.
</TEXT>
