<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-ChildCare     02-09 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Child Care,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Score Bush Child Care Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Child care experts Thursday criticized
President Bush's proposed $1,000 child care tax credit as being too
low and insufficient to address the range of problems faced by most
parents.
   ``It's really irrelevant to the child care needs of the United
States,'' said Edward F. Zigler, director of the Bush Center in
Child Development and Social Policy at Yale University.
   Zigler, speaking as the House Labor and Education Committee
opened a series of hearings on child care, called the proposal ``a
non-solution.''
   ``And the amount of money is too low. In an era where child care
costs $3,000 and $4,000 a year, $1,000 doesn't do much for that,''
said W. Norton Grubb, a professor of education at the University of
California at Berkeley.
   The committee estimates full-time child care costs at an average
$3,000 annually per child. That means a family with two children, in
which both parents work at minimum wage, spends more than half its
income for child care.
   Zigler, a strong proponent of school-based day-care, said the
Bush proposal doesn't address the obstacles faced by single-working
mothers or move to eliminate the ``two-tier'' care system he said is
developing between low-income families and others who can afford
private care.
   Grubb said Bush's failure to include a system of regulation in
the proposal would result in poor families spending the money for
other needs.
   ``The money in that proposal is not restricted to child care.
Most of the funds in that proposal, if enacted, would not go for
child care. They would go for food, housing, utilities, clothing and
other necessities like that,'' said Grubb.
   Deborah Phillips, a University of Virginia professor of
psychology, told the panel the proposal doesn't address the quality
of day care. She said quality should not be sacrificed because
government policy frames it ``as a luxury issue in child care.''
   Meanwhile, Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon, ranking Republican on the
Finance Committee, said he will introduce a bill to expand existing
child care tax credits for families with incomes under $25,000 and
assist states in improving current programs.
   Packwood's proposal would provide a maximum tax credit of $960
for one child and $1,920 for two or more children. The credit would
be fully refundable and could be made available through payroll
withholdings.
   Current law provides for tax savings of $720 for one child and
$1,440 for two or more children and it is not refundable.
</TEXT>
