<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     02-09 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buy More Grain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought another 600,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, the Agriculture
Department said Thursday.
   Christopher E. Goldthwait, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said the wheat was part
of an authorization of more than 2 million tons under the Export
Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Goldthwait said the wheat is for shipment in March. Counting some
left over from a previous EEP arrangement and 2 million tons
authorized Jan. 25, the Soviets have more than 1.4 million tons
still available under the program.
   With the latest sale, the Soviet Union has bought about 2.6
million tons of wheat for delivery in the sixth year of a long-term
supply agreement, which was extended last fall to run through Dec.
31, 1990.
   A metric tons is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. The 600,000 tons are equal to about 22 million bushels
worth around $90 million at recent U.S. farm prices.
   The EEP arrangement lets private exporters sell wheat and other
designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in
order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free
government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or
subsidies.
   Sales for delivery in the sixth year of the agreement also
included about 10.2 million tons of corn, along with 450,000 tons of
soybeans, 1.4 million tons of soybean meal, and 508,900 tons of
grain sorghum.
   Goldthwait said the 600,000 tons of wheat were sold by Ferruzzi,
USA Inc., 100,000 tons; Continental Grain Co.a, 250,000; Louis
Dreyfus Corp., 200,000; and Central States Enterprises Inc., 50,000.
   The companies will get subsidy of $23.01 per ton, or about 63
cents per bushel under the EEP arrangement.
</TEXT>
