<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 2011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Dukakis-Finances     02-09 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dukakis-Finances,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaign Has Yet to Report Final Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' presidential campaign has not
yet filed federal reports covering more than $3.1 million in
expenses incurred during the final month of last year's race for the
White House, aides to the Massachusetts governor said Thursday.
   Jack Corrigan, a former campaign aide to Dukakis who now works in
the governor's office, said expenses were not reported because the
money went out in the form of vouchers that allowed staffers to
withdraw cash, and the campaign's accountants were awaiting the
documents needed to report what the money bought.
   Because of the pace of events in the closing weeks of the
campaign, not all of the paperwork has made its way through,
Corrigan said.
   ``The events of the last month are not reflected,'' he said in a
telephone interview from Boston.
   According to the report filed Feb. 2 at the FEC, Dukakis had more
than $3.9 million on hand with nearly $1.3 million in unpaid debts,
indicating that the campaign had a surplus of some $2.6 million.
   However, Corrigan said the report did not include more than $3.1
million in vouchers that were paid but not listed because the
supporting documents were not yet available. Figured with the money
owed to the campaign and the cash on hand, the campaign should wind
up within $3,500 of being broke, he said.
   The 1984 presidential campaign of Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, was
fined by the Federal Election Commission for failing to report
expenses in a timely manner during that campaign, according to FEC
records.
   An attorney for the Dukakis campaign, Carol Darr, said she would
look into the current matter and ``we will correct it immediately''
if anything is wrong. ``We have been extremely careful all along,''
she said.
   Following an audit of the Glenn campaign, the election commission
charged it with violating the law for failing to report $312,495 in
expenses in a timely manner. Last year, the Glenn campaign agreed to
pay a $30,000 fine, a relatively large sum to be levied by the FEC,
but that also included penalties for other related violations.
   Although the commission has told campaigns that using bank drafts
is an acceptable practice, it has warned them against taking too
long to report the expenses.
   ``Draft transactions are reported in the period in which the
draft is paid by the bank,'' the commission said in a manual
provided for presidential campaigns.
   Ms. Darr said she was not familiar with the commisison ruling in
the Glenn case or the warning in the manual on bank drafts.
   ``Stuff like this is very technical,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
