<FIRST>r a AM-TeenBurned     02-09 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Burned,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-ager In Criticial Condition After Burning Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRENADA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school senior was in critical
condition Thursday, the day after police said her distraught
boyfriend poured gasoline over her head and set her on fire.
   ``She is burned pretty badly from the waist up,'' said police
Capt. Joe E. Durr.
   Morrell Sykes, 21, of Duck Hill was free on $10,000 bond after
being charged with aggravated assault.
   Sykes and the 17-year-old girl, ``argued the night before and he
drove to her house shortly before noon Wednesday to collect clothing
and other items,'' Durr said. ``It was then that he allegedly poured
the gas on her and lit it.''
   The teen-ager, whose name was not released, remained in critical
condition Thursday afternoon in the burn unit at the Presley Trauma
Center in Memphis, said hospital spokeswoman Dorise Madison.
   Sykes turned himself in Wednesday afternoon, Durr said. He said
Sykes' hands were burned and he was treated at a Grenada hospital.
   Durr said officers were able to talk with the girl at the Grenada
Lake Medical Center before she was flown by helicopter to the
Memphis hospital.
   The incident in Grenada occurred shortly before an incident in
Jackson, about 100 miles to the south, in which a man apparently
locked himself and his two children in a pickup, poured gasoline
over their bodies and set them on fire. All three died.
</TEXT>
