<FIRST>r w AM-Arabs-Jews 1stLd-Writethru a0578 02-09 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arabs-Jews, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0578,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3 grafs new material for 3rd graf pvs, B'nai B'rith</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arab Group Campaigns Against B'nai B'rith Letter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Arab Americans announced a campaign
Thursday against a leading Jewish human rights group over a letter
alleging that Arabs on college campuses are ``poisoning the minds of
our young.''
   The American Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee accused B'nai
B'rith International of sending ``hate literature'' to its members
in a fund-raising letter designed to combat anti-Semitic propaganda
and cult influence on Jewish college students.
   B'nai B'rith issued a statement questioning why the Arab
organization was continuing its campaign ``after B'nai B'rith has
publicly admitted that it was in error in using a phrase that may be
considered offensive.''
   ``The ADC is apparently anxious to keep the matter alive and
festering in order to score cheap points and damage the relationship
between Jews and Arabs in the United States,'' said the statement.
   The Jewish organization said that the letter, composed by an
outside mailing house, was a mistake and that unmailed copies had
been withdrawn two weeks ago. The organization has apologized
privately to the Arab group but has rejected demands that it reveal
how many such letters were sent, saying only that it was not a mass
mailing.
   The letter was signed by Seymour Reich, who serves as president
of B'nai B'rith International and who was chosen last month as head
of the Conference of Presidents of Major Jewish Organizations.
   The American-Arab committee has asked Reich to tell all the
original recipients that he dissociates himself from the first
letter, and B'nai B'rith spokesman Art Shulman said Thursday Reich
had done so. Reich's new letter says the views stated in the
previous one ``do not reflect our views. The incident was an
unfortunate mistake,'' Shulman quoted the second letter as saying.
   Nonetheless, the Arab group has asked the Internal Revenue
Service to examine the tax exempt status of B'nai B'rith, which is
based on the organization's description of itself as an educational
institution, said committee spokesman Faris Bouhafa. A similar
request has gone to the Postal Service, which grants such
institutions preferred rates, he said.
   ``Every day we are subjected to a deluge of anti-Semitic
propaganda'' on college campuses, the original letter said. ``This
is a deliberate and well-organized campaign to undermine the basic
beliefs and values of our young people _ our children and
grandchildren,'' it said.
   ``The Arab presence on the college campus is poisoning the minds
of our young people,'' the letter said.
   ``While cults and cultists are lurking around every corner, B'nai
B'rith'' is ``there to battle against the very real threats to
Judaism.''
   Bouhafa said his organization objects to the letter's association
of Arabs with cultists and to ``the association of legitimate
political activity on the part of Arab Americans with
anti-Semitism.''
   The committee has asked 575 civil rights and religious
organizations to sign an open protest letter to Reich.
   ``For an organization known for its anti-discrimination efforts,
it is dismaying to see discrimination against another ethnic
group,'' said a letter to Reich from the Women's Division of the
United Methodist Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
