<FIRST>u i AM-Italy-AzoresCrash     02-09 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Azores Crash,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italy Mourns 137 Dead In Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Azores Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUSSELL STEVENS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and family Thursday mourned the 137 Italians
killed when a chartered jet hit a mountain in the Azores.
   Pope John Paul II sent ``sentiments of ... spiritual closeness''
to relatives of the victims.
   The Boeing 707, chartered from an American company, was bound
from Bergamo, Italy, to the Dominican Republic and crashed on the
approach for a refueling stop. All 144 people aboard were killed,
including the crew of seven Americans.
   Mayor Paolo Pillitteri of Milan, home of many victims, expressed
``condolences for the tragic deaths of my fellow citizens'' and
established an agency to help families and friends.
   In Trento, vendors at an outdoor market placed flowers and
newspaper accounts of the crash in the place normally occupied by
Ottilia and Bruna Baratto, sisters who were killed in the crash, the
news agency ANSA reported.
   Francesca Falcini of Milan mourned her sister Cristiana, who
substituted for her because Francesca's work kept her home, the
agency said.
   Many people blamed the charter company, Independent Air Corp.,
and airline deregulation in the United States.
   Mayor Pillitteri said the crash ``once again reveals the problem
of security of flights so essential in our society.''
   A member of Parliament's transport committee, Pino Lucchesi, said
the ``tragedy is a reflection of the consequences the excessive
deregulation of airline traffic can bring.''
   Erica Mattei said her daughter Andrea, a tour operator on the
flight, had expressed worry about the soundness of the aircraft, on
which she had flown to the Dominican Republic twice before, ANSA
reported.
   A Milan television reporter, Paola Ferrari, said she flew on the
plane late last year and there was condensation inside, some baggage
was wet at the end of the flight and the oxygen masks popped out
when it landed.
   ``I had wanted ... to protest to the agency that organized the
vacation (and) write an open letter to the newspapers, but then work
commitments absorbed me and today I am here crying about not having
done it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
