<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1752EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     02-09 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detainee's Hunger Strike Spreads, Lawyers Start Solidarity Fast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday it
will not let a hunger strike by 300 black inmates change its policy
of imprisonment without trial.
   The hunger strike is perhaps the strongest challenge to the
policy of detention without trial since President P.W. Botha
declared a national state of emergency in June 1986.
   Meanwhile, a U.N. report released in Geneva charged the
government with ``state terrorism'' against the black majority. The
138-page report said that children continue to be victims of torture
and other inhuman treatment.
   The report said news accounts of the problem are being distorted
by censorship and other media restrictions as well as by official
South African propaganda.
   Leliel Mikuin Balanda of Zaire, who headed the group that drew up
the report, told reporters Thursday that the situation in South
Africa was getting ``worse and worse.''
   In another development, two members of Inkatha, a powerful Zulu
political group, were sentenced Wednesday to hang for the murders of
seven teen-agers in 1987, one of the worst incidents during a
two-year power struggle in Natal Province.
   Emmanuel Khanyile, 34, and Wilfred Phewa, 31, were convicted and
sentenced in Durban Supreme Court.
   The youths were forced into a minibus on March 16, 1987, taken to
a cemetery, then beaten with hammers and stabbed, according to
testimony. The killers allegedly suspected the youths were
supporters of the United Democratic Front, an anti-apartheid
coalition that has been feuding with Inkatha.
   Also Thursday, a bomb exploded in a moving police van, slightly
injuring two white officers and a schoolboy walking nearby, police
said. There was no claim of responsibility.
   More than 40 civil rights lawyers pledged to fast 48 hours until
noon Saturday in support of the hunger strikers' demands to be freed
or tried.
   The lawyers said seven detainees had been hospitalized after
going 18 days without food.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok rejected a request by some of
the lawyers to meet them Thursday at Johannesburg's Diepkloof
Prison, where the strike began Jan. 23.
   He said the government ``cannot allow itself to be blackmailed by
way of hunger strikes.''
   Vlok indicated the government might reevaluate its stance ``if
some of the hunger strikers near death.
   ``We will look at it again when we are standing at the
crossroads,'' Vlok said.
   Civil rights workers said 105 detainees at St. Albans Prison in
Port Elizabeth _ many of them held since 1986 _ joined the hunger
strike Monday. About 170 detainees at Diepkloof are fasting, as are
detainees in the port city of Durban and in Witbank, a mining town
near Pretoria, the lawyers said.
   An estimated 30,000 people have been detained without charge for
varying periods during the state of emergency. Vlok, at a news
briefing Thursday in Cape Town, said fewer than 1,000 people remain
in detention.
   Vlok said of the detainees, ``No one is being held without good
reason.'' He said the government chose not to charge the detainees
because of the difficulty obtaining convictions.
   The Human Rights Commission, formed by anti-apartheid activists
last year, said Vlok will be responsible ``should even one of the
detainees die.''
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
