<FIRST>r a AM-NorenService     02-09 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noren Service,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Who Committed Suicide Is Eulogized As A `Good Judge'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WOODSTOCK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. William A. O'Neill and more than 100
judges gathered Thursday to honor Richard C. Noren, the Superior
Court judge who killed himself after withdrawing his bid for a
second term on the bench.
   Noren was eulogized as a renaissance man, a good judge and a
considerate friend who spent his last hours writing thank-you notes
to those who had supported him in his highly public battle for
reappointment.
   Noren, 47, withdrew from consideration for a second eight-year
term last week after appearing twice before the General Assembly's
Judiciary Committee, which questioned him about his 1986 drunken
driving arrest, his drinking habits and his truthfulness.
   Three days later, he poisoned himself with car exhaust fumes in a
barn near the Woodstock farmhouse in rural northeast Connecticut
where he had lived since his youth.
   A crowd of about 900, including more than 100 judges and scores
of attorneys and court officials, applauded when Harry S. Gaucher
Jr., a friend and attorney, began his eulogy by saying, ``Richard
Carl Noren was a good judge.''
   Noren had requested such a eulogy in his emotional second
appearance before the Judiciary Committee, saying, ``I have often
said, not entirely facetiously, that I should like to have on my
tombstone the epitaph, `He was a good judge.'''
   The state Supreme Court and Appellate Court canceled sessions so
judges could attend the service at a conference center, and most of
the state's 139 Superior Court judges also cleared their schedules
to attend.
   ``Dick was as close to portraying the renaissance man as anyone I
have known,'' said Noren's college roommate, Henry Greene, now a
District of Columbia Superior Court judge. ``He was a historian, a
raconteur, an antiques expert.''
   Noren, a graduate of Harvard College and George Washington
University Law School, was clerk of Superior Court in Windham from
1971 to 1980 before being named a judge. His first term would have
expired Friday.
   There was a sentiment among many of those in attendance that
Noren's death reflected the amount of stress judges feel from the
state's reappointment process, said Chief Court Administrator Aaron
Ment.
   ``What's happened is that we now have a procedure that is similar
to trying to negotiate a minefield,'' said Ment. Some judges feel
that ``the integrity of the system _ the independence of the
judiciary _ is being eroded.''
</TEXT>
