<FIRST>u w AM-Flight103 2ndLd-Writethru a0690 02-09 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0690,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Official Says No Double Standard In Air Terror Warnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, The posted, to clarify that the threat, not the
notice, was a hoax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department's top terrorism expert
said Thursday that officials were wrong to post notices of threats
against American flights on embassy bulletin boards without also
telling the traveling public.
   The posted notice relayed rumors of a threat against Pan Am
flights from Frankfort, West Germany to the United States and
appeared days before a bomb exploded on Pan Am flight 103 over
Scotland Dec. 21. All 259 people on board were killed. The threat
was later determined to be a hoax.
   ``It is not our policy to alert government officials and not the
general public to such a threat,'' L. Paul Bremer, the State
Department's ambassador-at-large for counterterrorism, told the
House Foreign Affairs Committee. ``There is, and can be, no double
standard.''
   Bremer, appearing at the second congressional hearing of the day
on efforts to tighten aviation security, called the threat to
Frankfurt-U.S. flights a ``gruesome coincidence.''
   The notice ``should not have been posted,'' he said. Officials
have acknowledged that the warning was posted in the Moscow embassy
and possibly other missions as well.
   Bremer said officials at the Moscow embassy have said they found
the policy on warnings ``not as clear as we thought it was.'' He
said if a threat is specific and serious, authorities recommend
cancellation of the flight. Otherwise, a public travel advisory is
issued.
   Relatives of people killed in the unsolved explosion told the
earlier hearing that Congress should speed federal efforts to
tighten security against terrorist airplane attacks.
   Federal aviation and anti-terrorism officials defended the
government's policy of not publicizing bomb threats against
airlines, saying U.S. airlines and airports receive an average of
three threats a day.
   Relatives of those killed in the Pan Am crash said the government
must do more in notifying passengers about terrorist threats and in
installing sophisticated equipment to detect explosives and weapons.
   ``I bring no particular expertise to this committee other than
possibly sadness, grief and tears,'' said a steady-voiced Robert P.
Berrell, an automobile dealer from Fargo, N.D., whose 20-year-old
son, Steven, a student at Syracuse University, was among those
killed in the crash.
   An additional 11 victims were killed in Lockerbie, Scotland, when
flaming debris from the Boeing 747 plummeted to earth.
   ``When threats as specific as this are received, interested
passengers must be notified,'' Berrell told members of the House
Science, Space and Technology's transportation subcommittee.
</TEXT>
