<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0608 02-09 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0608,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede WARSAW</HEAD>
<HEAD>Miners End Strike; Walesa Asks Workers to Give Talks a Chance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Walsa in Krakow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity founder Lech Walesa interceded
to end a strike at Poland's largest power complex Thursday and asked
restive workers to give his negotiations with the government a
chance.
   At a rally in a Roman Catholic church for employees of the huge
Nova Huta steel mill, Walesa spent more than an hour explaining the
talks with communist authorities through which Solidarity hopes to
become legal again.
   He urged workers to put aside local grievances long enough for
the negotiations, which began Monday in Warsaw, to bear fruit.
Strikes crippled the Nova Huta mill last spring and summer.
   A strike of coal miners at the Belchatow power complex 90 miles
southwest of Warsaw, which supplies one-fifth of Poland's
electricity, was ended with the help of a mediator sent by Walesa,
but other labor tension continued.
   The Solidarity Information Service said workers in the Nowa Huta
coke department were refusing overtime, and the official news agency
PAP said the same was true of ambulance staffs in Poznan province,
western Poland.
   PAP said about 460 workers at a machine plant near Czestochowa
started a strike Thursday for higher pay, cuts in administrative
staff and better working conditions.
   Government delegates and representatives of the opposition met
for seven hours Thursday in a working group on trade union issues
and expressed optimism that technical details for restoring
Solidarity's legal status could be worked out.
   Among major questions remaining are whether a ``social contract''
can be made on economic and political reforms, and the form of new
parliamentary elections. Authorities have made agreement on those
topics, being negotiated by other working groups, a condition for
legalizing the union.
   Janusz Onyszkiewicz, national spokesman for Solidarity, told
reporters the union wants a separate law making it legal again and
expressed satisfaction with the prospects.
   ``It's not formal approval'' so far, ``but it's optimistic
because the authorities asked for technical details,'' he said. ``So
they treat (our position) as a serious thing and will consider it as
such.''
   Alexander Kwasniewski, a government minister who took part in the
meeting, said the discussion now revolves around how the
legalization would occur.
   Walesa founded Solidarity in Gdansk, where he still works as a
shipyard electrician, during the labor turmoil of 1980 and the
government initially accepted it as the first independent trade
union in the Soviet bloc. It was suppressed after the declaration of
martial law in December 1981, however, and later outlawed.
   After attending the first part of Thursday's negotiations in
Warsaw, Walesa left for the evening Mass and rally in Nowa Huta, on
the outskirts of Krakow in southern Poland.
   He is making a two-day tour of the southern region to reassure
skeptical workers about the negotiations with the government.
   Speaking to a crowd of about 3,000 people after Mass in the
Mistrzejowice church, which was lined with Solidarity banners, he
declared:
   ``I don't believe in the government, but there is a possiblity
for pluralism. As Lech Walesa I must do everything, or take every
opportunity peacefully, to build a better Poland.''
   The union leader, who won the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, has
apologized to audiences lately for ``too elegant'' by wearing a suit
and tie to the negotiations. He appeared at the rally in a sportcoat
and jeans.
   When members of the audience shouted out grievances against the
steel mill management and behavior of local authorities, Walesa
appeared impatient.
   ``Each one of us has grievances and reasons to strike, and we
have to get out of this,'' he said. ``If there is a chance at the
round table, we have to take it.''
   Solidarity can address specific problems when it is allowed to
function legally, he said.
   Walesa's initial appeal, in an interview with state radio, was
broadcast as the working group on unions began its meeting.
   He called the Belchatow strike ``another proof that we should
reach agreement on the most important things as soon as possible and
restore the organization called Solidarity.''
   Wildcat strikes could be avoided if an organized union spoke for
the workers, he said, and told Solidarity's supporters: ``Lech
Walesa is appealing for a chance for the round table. We have been
waiting for so many years, we can wait a few days more.''
   The unprecedented talks, first proposed during severe labor
unrest in August and expected to last up to six weeks, are intended
to create a national consensus for solving Poland's severe economic,
social and political problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
