<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay     02-09 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Officials of Stroessner Regime Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEDRO SERVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said they arrested two of
deposed President Alfredo Stroessner's government ministers Thursday
and caught the former central bank president trying to flee with a
large amount of cash.
   No charges were specified, but the detentions appeared to be
connected with alleged financial irregularities under Gen.
Stroessner, who ruled for nearly 35 years and was overthrown last
week. Stroessner is in exile in Brazil.
   Cesar Romeo Acosta, 75-year-old former head of the central bank,
was arrested while trying cross the border to Argentina and confined
to a police hospital, the authorities reported. They said said he
was carrying $20,000, many traveler's checks and 12,000 West German
marks.
   Police also reported the detentions of Adan Godoy Gimenez, former
minister of public health, and Carlos Ortiz Ramirez, who was
Stroessner's education minister.
   Officials in the provisional government of Gen. Andres Rodriguez,
a longtime associate of Stroessner who ousted him Feb. 3, have been
saying all week that officials of the former regime apparently
enriched themselves with public funds.
   Central bank officials said Wednesday they would examine checks
written by some ``government officials who are no longer government
officials.''
   With the dictator gone, exiles are returning from neighboring
Brazil and Argentina and such opposition politicians as Domingo
Laino are interviewed on television.
   Rodriguez, who has called elections for May 1, is receiving
dissident factions of the ruling Colorado Party.
   ``It seems like a dream to see Laino on television,'' said
journalist Fernando Cazenave. ``It seems like a fantasy to hear
leaders of the Popular Colorado Movement were received by the
president of the republic. All this has never happened in this
country.''
   Leaders of the dissident Popular Colorado Movement, including
Miguel Angel Gonzalez Casabianca and Mario Mallorquin, were exiled
in 1960. After they were allowed back in 1983, police agents on
motorscooters followed them everywhere.
   Opposition leaders hardly ever appeared on television while
Stroessner was in power. The general's son Gustavo owned one of the
two stations in Asuncion and his good friend Nicolas Bo owned the
other.
   Stroessner closed the largest newspaper, ABC Color, in March 1984
and called publisher Aldo Zuccolillo ``an enemy of the government.''
Soon after the coup, Zuccolillo was featured in a story in the the
Colorado Party paper.
   Critics say only the faces have changed and the system of
Colorado Party rule under a military president remains the same. But
Rodriguez has appointed a capable Cabinet, set an election date and
made overtures to the Roman Catholic Church, which Stroessner
alienated.
   U.S. Ambassador Timothy Towell spent an hour Thursday with
Foreign Minister Luis Maria Argana, then told reporters: ``We've
heard the words. We hear the commitments. Now is the time to see how
they implement them.
   ``We will be judging the quality of our relationship on the
degree in which they move forward in all these areas.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
