<SECOND>BC-Wright Text, 1st add,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 9 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: homeless tonight.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   They have no place of their own to eat or sleep, to take a bath
or wash their clothes. Their children have no place to study or play.
   No, these are not just derelicts or ne'er-do-wells or social
misfits. They represent many families of the working poor who have
low-paying jobs and work each day, but simply cannot pay for the
inflated price of housing
   America can do better than that. We must do better!
   Of course, we cannot expect to vanquish all these evils
immediately, but if we have the will we can make significant
progress against all three deficits this year.
   We in the Congress, and surely all Americans everywhere, are
anxious to help our new president fulfill his promise of a ``kinder,
gentler America.'' I want very much to help George Bush qualify to
be known as ``the education president.''
   We in Congress are eager to help him attain the goals he has
expressed of wider access for all Americans to Head Start services,
to safe and wholesome child day care in an age when both parents
must work, to affordable housing and to a cleaner environment.
   By working hard together, we must drive the scourge of drugs from
our streets and our schools as Mr. Bush pledged in his inaugural
speech. Congress made significant progress last year in this truly
bipartisan goal. We developed a good battle plan for the war against
drugs. But when it came to paying for the war, the government ran
out of money. Right now we're financing not a war, but a skirmish.
   That's not good enough. Our society can afford to pay for
vigorous anti-drug efforts. Truth is, we can't afford not to. That's
our first line of defense.
   That, and the education of our children _ more vital to our
national security than Star Wars.
   Since 1980, the federal investment in education has actually
declined by 12 percent. Is it any wonder that American students _
better fed and surely just as smart _ do worse in mathematics and
language, and geography, and science, than students do in most other
industrial nations?
   That's not good enough. We can do better than that. And we will.
</TEXT>
