<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-09 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold And Wet In California, Great Lakes Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A shot of cold arctic air flowing across the Great Lakes created
snow in parts of New York and Michigan on Thursday and a low
pressure system off California swept rain through the valleys and
snow on the mountains.
   Temperatures warmed over portions of the Plains and the South
remained mild.
   In California, snow fell over the northern mountains, the
Antelope Valley and the Owens Valley in Southern California, where a
winter storm warning was in effect Thursday. Twelve inches of snow
were dumped on Olancha, Calif.
   Strong winds, gusting to nearly 60 mph overnight, were
diminishing over the San Joaquin Valley.
   Snow also fell over portions of Utah, some of it in areas that
usually do not receive much snow. Four inches of new snow were
recorded at Santa Clara, in southern Utah.
   Over the Great Lakes, cold arctic air moving across the lakes'
warmer waters created lake-effect snow. Snowfall over western New
York on Thursday morning included 5 to 6 inches at Batavia, and 5
inches at Sodus.
   Temperatures were warming Thursday over portions of the Plains,
with readings in the 20s and 30s from the central and northern
Plains, across the middle Mississippi Valley and the Tennessee
Valley, to the middle Atlantic Coast.
   Readings remained in the single digits and teens over much of the
upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes, and much of New England.
Strong winds combined with the cold temperatures over New England
and created wind chill readings between 20 and 30 degrees below zero.
   But temperatures were in the 60s and 70s through the Florida
peninsula.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 5
degrees below zero at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 78 degrees
at Homestead Air Force Base and Key West, Fla.
   The low in the nation Thursday morning was 30 degrees below zero
at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   Friday's forecast called for rain along much of the southern and
central Pacific Coast, with snow over mountainous areas, as well as
over the Great Basin and western portions of the central Rockies;
lake-effect snow through upper Michigan and much of the lower Great
Lakes region; and snow scattered over northern New England.
   High temperatures were forecast in the teens and the 20s through
much of the central Rockies, southern Idaho, and from much of the
northern Plains across the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes
and the upper Ohio Valley to New England; in the 30s and 40s from
the northern half of the Pacific Coast across the Great Basin, the
northern Rockies; the central Plains and Oklahoma, much of the
middle Mississippi Valley and Arkansas, the lower Ohio Valley, the
central and southern Appalachians to the middle Atlantic Coast and
much of the Carolinas; in the 50s and 60s from the central and
southern California Coast across the southern Plateau, the southern
Rockies, Texas, the Gulf Coast region and much of Florida to the
Georgia and South Carolina coast; and in the 70s in the Florida Keys.
</TEXT>
