<DOCNO> AP890209-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Budget-Analysis 1stLd-Writethru a0607 02-09 0877</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Analysis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's First Budget: Collision Between Campaign Rhetoric and Reality</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES top 21 grafs with material from budget briefing; PICKS
UP 19th graf pvs bgng, `During the'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new president's first budget is always a
collision between campaign rhetoric and reality, and the budget
George Bush put forward Thursday could spell a quick end to his
honeymoon with Congress.
   Bush the campaigner wanted to be the education president, stop
the drug scourge, house the homeless and clean up the environment.
   And he promised that all the good things he wanted for the
American people could be accomplished without raising taxes.
   The critics charged that Bush would fail. Either the promises
would go unfulfilled or the president would end up increasing taxes.
   But in a melody with a familiar refrain, Bush came up up with a
way out of his quandary. He said he will raise more revenue by
cutting taxes. Strains of ``That Old Black Magic'' by Ronald Reagan.
   The tax Bush has in mind is the capital gains levy, which taxes
the profits earned from the sale of assets, such as stocks.
   The Bush budget projects a $5 billion increase in revenues for
the 1990 fiscal year, which begins next Oct. 1, through enactment of
the cut in the capital gains tax.
   Bush's capital gains tax helps the new president achieve a
projected 1990 deficit of $91.1 billion, slightly bettering the
$92.5 billion deficit Reagan put forward one month ago in his final
spending blueprint.
   That is accomplished through the $5 billion projected revenue
gain from the cut in the capital gains tax and $2.6 billion in
reductions Bush proposed making in Reagan's 1990 military spending
request.
   Currently the profits on sales of assets are counted just like
other income, which means for high-income people a top tax rate of
either 28 percent or 33 percent.
   Bush wants to cut the capital gains rate in 1990 to 15 percent
for assets held one year or longer and projects the change would
increase revenues by $5 billion as people sold assets to take
advantage of the lower rate.
   But that revenue estimate comes with a big catch, many economists
believe. It will lower government revenues for other years.
   David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources Inc., a Lexington,
Mass., economic consulting firm, said that much of the revenue would
be lost in the current year, thus ballooning the size of the 1989
deficit, which is already projected to soar to $161 billion.
   ``I guarantee that you would lose about the same amount of
revenue in 1989 that you will gain in 1990,'' Wyss said. ``If you
know that the capital gains rate is going down on Jan. 1, you won't
be selling a lot of stock at a profit in June.''
   Democrats on Capitol Hill have another complaint. They say the
capital gains tax cut, which was one of Bush's campaign promises, is
nothing but the old Republican ``trickle down'' theory to benefit
the rich. They contend that 85 percent of all capital gains are
earned by the wealthiest 5 percent of Americans.
   They aimed their fire at the proposal in barbed remarks stripped
of the bipartisan good feeling which surrounded Bush's inaugural
address.
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman James Sasser, D-Tenn., said that
at a time of huge budget deficits it was ``simply unacceptable to be
considering tax breaks for the very wealthiest segment of the
American population.''
   The capital gains tax wasn't the only target drawing fire.
Critics complained that in many other areas the amount of money Bush
is proposing to spend is minuscule when compared with the magnitude
of the problem.
   Even before Bush's joint address, his aides were busy lowering
expectations, contending that in a time of tight budgets it was
tough to fund new initiatives.
   Bush's budget director, Richard Darman, told reporters at a
briefing on the budget that the president had at least made a start
toward fulfulling his pledge for a ``kinder, gentler'' nation.
   ``Is it as kind and gentle as everyone would like to be
immediately, I think probably not. But we can't do absolutely
everything at once,'' Darman told reporters. ``We will not be
claiming to have solved all problems.''
   During the campaign, Bush said the deficit problem would simply
melt by 1993 or 1994 if Congress would enact his ``flexible
freeze,'' whereby the overall rise in government spending is held to
the increase in inflation each year. Some programs could climb
faster than the inflation rate but only if other areas were pruned
back.
   But the pruning is likely to be as difficult for Bush as it was
for Reagan.
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said
Thursday he was upset that Bush had decided to leave in his budget a
proposal also in Reagan's final budget to curb Medicare spending by
$5 billion next year by trimming payments to doctors and hospitals.
   Such a cut, Bentsen said, ``leads to very serious problems
because you have a lot of hospitals losing money on Medicare now and
a lot of hospitals closing, particularly rural hospitals.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITORS: Martin Crutsinger has covered economics for The</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press since 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
