<FIRST>u w AM-Budget-Agriculture     02-09 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Agriculture,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Calls for $2 Billion Cuts in Farm Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush called on lawmakers Thursday
night to ``reform'' farm payment programs by reducing them by $2
billion next fiscal year, and the Democratic chairmen of both
agriculture committees quickly said he was cutting too hard.
   Bush's overall fiscal blueprint for Department of Agriculture
programs appeared similar to what an outgoing President Reagan
proposed a month ago, but some lawmakers expressed puzzlement over
the fine print.
   Rep. Virginia Smith, R-Neb., said the spending assumptions on
which Bush based his outline were at sharp odds with Reagan's and
that ``we will have much negotiating to do with the
administration.'' She said farmers facing more drought could not
take deeper cuts.
   ``Ultimately, Mother Nature and the U.S. Congress will have the
last word,'' the Appropriations Committee lawmaker said.
   Reagan also had proposed $2 billion in cuts in payments by the
government-owned Commodity Credit Corp. next year. But he sought to
soften the blow for farmers by making $900 million of those payments
this fiscal year.
   The Commodity Credit Corp. provides income-support payments to
cotton, rice, wheat and feed grains producers as well as
price-support loans that guard farmers against market slumps by
making the government the buyer of last resort.
   Farm payments ballooned to more than $26 billion in 1986 but
currently are costing taxpayers less than half of that as the farm
economy continues to rebound from its doldrums of the early and
mid-1980s.
   Bush's budget book said that ``provisions of current law were
designed during the height of the farm crisis.''
   ``It is now time to reform our farm programs and not wait until
the current farm bill expires nearly two years hence,'' it said. It
added that Bush has called on Agriculture Secretary Clayton K.
Yeutter to ``work with the Congress to develop a specific set of
initiatives designed to reduce federal farm expenditures by $2
billion in 1990.''
   It reviewed an array of possible means of cutting the
expenditures, ranging from a speeded up lowering of target prices
used to calculate income-support payments to reducing the number of
acres eligible for payments.
   On Capitol Hill, Rep. E. (Kika) de la Garza, D-Texas, chairman of
the House Agriculture Committee, issued a statement, saying he would
``make every effort possible to work harmoniously with my fellow
Texan, President Bush.''
   ``However, as it is currently proposed, the administration's 1990
budget still makes unreasonable demands upon agriculture which has
already given $30 billion in cuts from proposed budgets over the
last eight years.''
   ``We in agriculture are prepared to make a fair contribution, but
this administration is asking us to take cuts which represent
considerably more than our fair share of the budget-balancing
burden,'' de la Garza said.
   ``I would remind everyone that if we cut out the entire amount
proposed for agricultural spending, it would still make only an
almost infinitesimal impact on the total budget situation,'' he
added.
   Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.,
said the farm cuts envisioned would be double the automatic cuts
prescribed if Congress failed to reduce the deficit under the
Gramm-Rudman Act.
   ``An agricultural budget cutting twice as deep as the
Gramm-Rudman sequester is not a kinder and gentler budget,'' Leahy
said.
   ``When the 1990 reagan budget was released, I expressed my hope
that it was designed to make the Bush budget kinder and gentler,''
Leahy said. ``I also expressed my fear that the Reagan farm cuts
would undermine a tough U.S. negotiating position in the GATT
talks,'' he said. ``I am very disappointed that the Bush budget is
neither kinder to the farmer nor tougher on our competitors in the
GATT negotiations.''
   The GATT is the 97-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade,
which governs much of global commerce. Talks on updating the
agreement have been going on for the last two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
