<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-EggFuror     02-09 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Egg Furor,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Minister Leaves Grilling Without Egg on Her Face</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former junior health minister Edwina Currie emerged
smiling Wednesday from a grilling by fellow lawmakers over her
remark that most British egg production was affected by food
poisoning bacteria.
   ``She stonewalled every question and acted like a grande dame,''
said lawmaker Ann Winterton, a fellow Conservative Party member,
after the session of the House of Commons Select Committee on
Agriculture.
   For nearly eight weeks Mrs. Currie resisted the committee's
summons to appear before it to explain her remark which outraged
poultry farmers and led to tons of unsold eggs.
   In an off-the-cuff remark in a brief TV interview she said:
``Most of the egg production in this country, sadly, is now infected
with salmonella.''
   Her notorious words came during a scare over dangers from eating
eggs, when one possible cause of infection mentioned was bad feed
given to chickens.
   As farmers filed lawsuits against the government seeking
compensation, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher ordered Mrs. Currie
to resign nine days before Christmas.
   Mrs. Currie told the committee she hadn't meant that most eggs
were affected by salmonella bacteria, as one committee member
suggested. She said that was a misrepresentation by the media.
   Mrs. Currie said she still believed that a significant number of
birds in a significant number of laying flocks were infected. So
many eggs were eaten every day that even if only a small proportion
of them were affected by the bacteria, they amounted to a very large
number, she said.
   Mrs. Currie, 42, showed up before the bipartisan committee after
it threatened to force a House of Commons motion compelling her to
appear. The Times of London said this procedure was last used 350
years ago.
   The government is paying out nearly nearly $7 million in
compensation for 108 million eggs destroyed and some 450,000
slaughtered chickens. It also launched an $865,000 advertising
campaign to reassure people they could eat eggs without fear _
although it was best to hard-boil them for little children, the
elderly and the sick.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
