<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-Japan-NewCenters Adv16   02-09 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-New Centers, Adv 16,0906</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thu AMs, Feb. 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Centers Sprouting in Japan as Tokyo Fills to Its Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSAKA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese are beginning to look away from
Tokyo as the nation's power center and toward places like Osaka or
Kumamoto in the far-off south for new development and economic
influence.
   The new thrust: Japan is not just Tokyo.
   For many Japanese now crammed into the capital city, it could
mean a return to their roots in the countryside for good jobs and
less stressful living.
   Here in the heart of this industrial city a dozen new skycrapers
tower over the Osaka Castle, a 400-year-old landmark, casting their
shadow on a serene historic site but at the same time looming as a
new symbol of decentralization in Japan.
   The complex, called Osaka Business Park, is one of dozens of
large-scale development projects launched by local business groups
in a campaign to reverse the flow of economic power to Tokyo.
   Not only mighty regional centers like Osaka but smaller and more
remote towns also have begun their own development projects that are
luring high-tech industry and beckoning their talented offspring
home from Tokyo.
   One such place is Kumamoto, 560 miles southwest of Tokyo, about
as far away from the capital as you can get without leaving Japan
proper. It is the first of 26 locations designated as a
``technopolis'' by the Ministry of Internatinal Trade and Industry.
   The model city there already has research facilities and is to be
expanded to encompass two cities, 12 towns and two villages and
cover nearly 40 square miles.
   It's tranquil, ``affluent and easy-going'' says Morihiro
Hosokawa, the local governor. It also has an abundance of flat,
cheap land.
   The area already has persuaded major corporations like Honda
Motors and Matsushita Electric to set up branch offices. It is also
the home of Kyushu NEC, which claims to be the world's largest
producer of integrated circuits.
   For decades, Tokyo has been at the pinnacle of Japan's highly
centralized society, drawing much of the best the nation had to
offer. But as its concentration of political power and its growing
role as a world financial center stretch its physical and spiritual
limits, more Japanese are beginning to think the capital's dominance
should be reduced.
   Planners also warn that another earthquake in Tokyo like the one
that killed 143,000 people in 1923 could devastate the country's
centralized infrastructure and severely damage both the Japanese and
world economies.
   Osaka, Japan's business and industrial center before World War
II, is in the western Kansai region about 250 miles southwest of
Tokyo.
   Community and business leaders there have begun a massive
development program for the region of more than 13.5 million people.
The project calls for the building of Japan's first 24-hour
international airport, a Kansai Science City for students,
researchers and their families, and the Asia and Pacific Trade
Center, planned with the hope of displacing Hong Kong as a major
distribution center for Asia once the British colony reverts to
Chinese rule in 1997.
   By the year 2000, direct investment in the projects will total at
least $122 billion, analysts say, with indirect investment possibly
doubling that figure.
   During Japan's postwar rush to reindustrialize, few questioned
Tokyo's dominance. With the best schools, jobs and entertainment,
Tokyo drew millions who dreamed of better lives as well as hundreds
of companies wanting to be near government agencies, banks,
financial markets and up-to-date information.
   As a result, more power has become concentrated in Tokyo than in
almost any other single city in the world.
   Thirty million people live in the greater Tokyo metropolitan area
_ a quarter of Japan's population crowded into 2 percent of its area
_ triggering the highest land prices in the world; choice commerical
real estate was selling for $6.7 billion an acre last year. For
those unable to afford to live in Tokyo itself, commuting to work
can take more than four hours a day.
   While Tokyo's attraction still hasn't faded, people in rural
areas and cities like Osaka have begun emphasizing their own local
strengths and diversity.
   ``Cultural and technological over-centralization is dangerous,
and if we don't do something about it, it's likely to create cracks
in our society,'' says Kazuro Kuriyama, head of research for the
Kansai Economic Federation, a grouping of Kansai businesses.
   For many Japanese, regional revitalization means a return to
traditional values at a time when so many people no longer live with
their relatives or in their hometowns.
   Towns are reviving and promoting local festivals, crafts and
delicacies, while TV shows such as ``Rediscover Japan'' and
``Wonderful Trip Around Japan'' introduce the lifestyle and customs
of local communities.
   Beer companies are introducing ``local flavor'' brews designed to
appeal to local pride and taste, and the post office plans to
release a new series of regional stamps.
   Even the national government is encouraging a shift away from
Tokyo.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita has said the government will
distribute 100 million yen ($800,000) to each of 3,200 or so
villages, towns and cities for use in improvement projects.
   The Cabinet also is moving 79 secondary government bodies out of
Tokyo.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, Feb. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890209-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1413EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-BehindtheScreams Adv17   02-09 1187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Behind the Screams, Adv 17,1217</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Feb. 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Horror Filmmaker Slashes More Bodies for the Buck</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karen Russell's frantic screams rattled
windows up and down Valley Spring Lane, but no Samaritans on this
quiet suburban street abandoned their Thursday night suppers to come
to her rescue.
   Even Miss Russell's friends and colleagues _ standing just yards
from the violent poolside assault _ kept perfectly still.
   Finally, when he had seen enough, Dave DeCoteau looked at the
fallen woman, put his hands in his pockets, and smiled a thin smile.
``OK,'' he said. ``Let's move on.''
   As the director of the low-budget horror film ``Beverly Hills
Corpse,'' DeCoteau's mission was to produce dead bodies as quickly
as possible _ such efficiency is the only way cheap movies can make
a profit. The ugly death of Miss Russell, slain by corpse-like hands
rocketing out of a swimming pool, left one less butchering to film.
   Sparing every imaginable expense _ actors brought their own
costumes, crew members earned minimum wage and almost everything but
the 16mm film itself was borrowed _ the makers of ``Beverly Hills
Corpse'' were able to film half a dozen garrotings and impalings in
only five days.
   A visit to the ``Beverly Hills Corpse'' set illuminates a
different, frequently overlooked side of Hollywood. Unlike
flamboyant, high-budget productions that swim with celebrities and
hype, this film reflects true, unknown blue-collar labor _ much
work, little acclaim.
   Where directors Steven Spielberg and Francis Ford Coppola might
use a dozen or so camera setups in a day, DeCoteau (``Nightmare
Sisters,'' ``Creepozoids,'' ``Lady Avenger'') raced through 57 moves
in one 13-hour shoot. In the time it takes ``serious'' movie makers
to shoot just one 15-minute sequence, the 90-minute ``Beverly Hills
Corpse'' was already in the can.
   ``OK. Let's move on,'' is the battle cry of this brand of film
making.
   The plot of ``Beverly Hills Corpse'' is admittedly witless. A few
studly young men stroll into a house, chat with two women who don't
wear much clothing, have sex with them, and then pretty much
everybody dies.
   The movie does not pretend to be anything it is not. Said
screenwriter Ross Perron, asked if he minds his scripts being called
exploitive: ``Why should I mind? They are.''
   Its lack of sophistication aside, ``Beverly Hills Corpse'' could
become more profitable than, say, ``Tequila Sunrise'' or a large
percentage of the major studio releases now costing an average $17
million apiece.
   Made on a budget of only $50,000, ``Beverly Hills Corpse'' can,
with any measure of domestic and international videocassette sales,
realize a net gain.
   The dilemma on the set, then, was to keep costs so low they're
subterranean, but still spit out a movie that, if little else, was
in focus. Though shots were hurriedly lighted and most scenes were
captured in only one or two camera takes, DeCoteau's genius rests on
an aptitude to make really cheap films look only semi-cheap,
delivering them on budget and on time. Only 26, he has directed or
produced 12 B titles.
   ``Beverly Hills Corpse'' relied upon a good-natured, well
choreographed ensemble of young technicians and struggling actors
united by the challenges of guerrilla film making. A motorcycle used
in one scene was appropriated from sound mixer D.J. Ritchie. ``We
cannibalize everything,'' said co-producer and first assistant
director Fred Kennamer. ``We used my car in `Assault of the Killer
Bimbos.'''
   Given a rare chance to work in a highly competitive business, the
cast and crew of ``Beverly Hills Corpse'' willingly accepted pay far
below union rates and read dialogue so wooden the script gave them
splinters.
   ``All of us are stars on the way up. This is just a stop along
the way,'' said Mike Jacobs Jr., who is featured in ``Beverly Hills
Corpse'' as a rock singer named Eric who _ through some fluke of the
script _ actually walks away alive at the end of the movie.
   Out-of-work actress Lillie Fields (she played a nameless
screaming woman in the 1988 remake of ``The Blob'') shared Jacobs'
optimism. On the set not as a performer but as the ``craft
services'' supervisor, Ms. Fields spent one recent afternoon
refilling the carrot-stick tray at the film's small snack table.
   ``It's nice working here,'' said Ms. Fields, a theater graduate
of the University of Illinois who recently moved to Southern
California, ``because you make friends and they might have friends
and then they can say to their friends, `Hey, I have this friend who
needs a SAG card.'''
   Membership in SAG, the Screen Actors Guild, is a Hollywood
paradox: You can't act in a big feature film without a SAG card, but
you can't obtain a SAG card unless you've acted in a big feature
film.
   But for those actors and crew members who see ``Beverly Hills
Corpse'' as a step up to a more glorious future, there are others _
like actress Linnea Quigley _ who more or less revel on the lower
rungs.
   Miss Quigley, whose resume includes ``Hollywood Chainsaw
Hookers,'' ``Sorority Babes in the Slimeball Bowl-O-Rama,'' ``Blood
Nasty'' and the upcoming ``Assault of the Party Nerds,'' has
established herself as the Meryl Streep of the slice-and-dice genre.
Ask her to go topless (or more) or die a horrible death, and she'll
meet the challenge gamely.
   Said makeup artist Cindy Warren: ``She always knows her lines.
She's always on time. And she never messes up.''
   Yet it seems incongruous for Miss Quigley to appear in movies
featuring countless decapitations and other abuses: She is a
vegetarian and animal rights activist. ``I won't do a movie where
there's violence toward animals,'' she said.
   And though usually semi-nude on camera, she calls herself ``shy''
and says, ``I wouldn't feel safe at a nude beach.''
   Ultimately, though, it is Miss Quigley's and Miss Russell's naked
bodies, not their death scenes or acting talents, that will bring
``Beverly Hills Corpse'' whatever riches it might gather when it
debuts on videocassette later this summer.
   The film, lacking both requisite quality and financial backing,
will never make it to movie theaters. Like many of its independently
produced kin, its future will be decided at video stores both here
and abroad: With rentals costing a buck a night, home video fans
have much more tolerance for lesser films.
   And since there are no ratings for videos, there's no such word
as ``unsuitable.''
   ``Most foreign markets won't accept adult movies,'' said
screenwriter Perron. ``So horror movies (with nudity) fill the niche
_ they pass right by the censors.''
   While Perron talked, the real art of slasher film making was
being discussed in the next room, where makeup artist Warren
conferred with special-effects expert Rick LaLonde.
   They wanted to make sure an upcoming throat slashing went well.
As the two held up their own concoctions of fake blood, Ms. Warren
suddenly looked very serious and said, ``Do you want the more
jugular blood or the capillary blood?''
   On such fine points, bad horror movies become better.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Feb. 17</NOTE>
