<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-GM-Framingham Adv12   02-09 1064</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-GM-Framingham, Adv 12,1094</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Feb. 12, and Thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>As GM Shrinks, Main Street Pinched</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Grniet is cq in 28th graf; this story also on financial wires</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX8 of Feb. 7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When General Motors Corp. idles its
sprawling assembly plant here in August, one of the main engines
driving this New England town's economy will shift into neutral.
   About 1,200 employees already are on furlough, and 2,000 more
will be laid off. Framingham will lose its largest employer, which
last year paid $830,000 in local taxes, spent $19 million with local
suppliers and had a payroll of $59 million.
   Sharon McWey, a 28-year-old single mother who earned $13.18 an
hour at the plant, wonders who will pay the bills if she or her
5-year-old daughter gets sick.
   Leonard Milo, owner of a Framingham hardware store, worries he
may have to lay off some of his 11 employees. ``One thing affects
the next,'' he said. ``You can't keep everyone on when you're losing
a customer that did $100,000 worth of business.''
   GM says the troubled plant, which has gone through at least five
shutdowns since 1977, may one day reopen. But industry analysts
doubt it, and many workers no longer can tolerate the
on-again-off-again nature of the operation.
   The same painful uncertainty is felt in Leeds, Mo., Pontiac,
Mich., Norwood, Ohio, and other communities nationwide where the No.
1 automaker has been reducing production capacity for the first time
in its 80-year history.
   GM, which has suffered a steady erosion in its share of the U.S.
car market over the past several years, announced last April that it
would start closing plants in an effort to bring capacity into line
with sales.
   The reaction on Wall Street has been enthusiastic; GM's stock
rose $1.25 to $73.375 a share on the day of the announcement and has
since climbed to about $93.
   But the impact on Main Street has been severe.
   ``Talk to any shop owner, any pizza place, any package store in
this town,'' said Kenneth R. Mercer, a 34-year-old Framingham native
who worked at the GM plant for four years. ``It's not just the 3,000
jobs. It's a whole domino effect.''
   GM says the 40-year-old Framingham plant is one of four in North
America making Buick Centurys and Oldsmobile Cutlass Cieras, all of
which have been running at well below capacity. Eliminating
Framingham, GM says, will make the other three _ in Oklahoma City,
Ste. Therese, Quebec, and Ramos Aripze, Mexico _ more efficient.
   Framingham, meanwhile, is feeling recriminations.
   Some workers blame Local 422 of the United Auto Workers for
refusing to agree to work-rule changes that might have saved the
plant and their jobs. Some union activists accuse executives of
mismanaging the plant.
   If there is a consensus, though, it is that the plant's fate was
sealed on a single night two years ago _ June 17, 1986 _ when GM
asked for a zoning change to allow the 54-acre facility to expand
and build plastic-body mini-vans.
   Framingham, population 65,100, calls itself ``the largest town in
America,'' because it is the largest community still run by an
old-fashioned New England town meeting.
   With the Yankee independence that town meetings are known for,
residents peppered GM officials that June night with questions about
noxious emissions, storage of plastic resins and truck traffic.
   Jim Hanscom, Framingham's director of public works, remembers the
answers as incomplete and the GM officials as haughty.
   ``It appeared they thought they were above questions,'' he said.
   After a lengthy debate, GM fell three votes short, 69-39, of the
two-thirds majority needed for a zoning change.
   This month, the automaker began retooling its North Tarrytown,
N.Y., plant to make the plastic mini-vans originally slated for
Framingham. On Feb. 1, GM announced that the Framingham facility
would shut down indefinitely because ``it does not have any new
product to manufacture.''
   Some residents saw the announcement as spiteful. But the
president of the local Chamber of Commerce, Michelle L. Flaherty,
said the town has only itself to blame.
   ``What infuriates me is that this plant had a product two years
ago that would have ensured its continuation into the 1990s, and the
town turned it down,'' she said. ``That's something we have to face
up to.''
   In other moves to reduce manufacturing capacity last year, GM
laid off 4,000 workers at a Firebird-Camaro factory in Norwood,
Ohio; 2,500 at a stamping plant in Hamilton, Ohio; 2,350 at a Fiero
plant in Pontiac, Mich.; and 1,300 at a Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac
facility in Leeds, Mo.
   Even with those closings, GM still has excess capacity and
probably will have to shut at least two more plants to meet its
stated goal of using 100 percent of its U.S. car-making capacity by
1992, said Thomas O'Grady, an analyst with Integrated Automotive
Resources Inc. in Wayne, Pa.
   Framingham may be better off than some other affected
communities, because it has a diverse economic base that includes
computer manufacturing, stationery making and a 375-room hotel.
   In addition, the unemployment rate in Massachusetts, at 3.3
percent, is the lowest of any major industrial state. To help
workers exploit job opportunities in the Boston area, GM and the UAW
have opened a retraining center, and Gov. Michael S. Dukakis has
announced a $250,000 state grant to help fund it.
   The Framingham plant reopened in May, after a November 1987
shutdown that put 3,700 out of work. When it reopened, more than
1,000 workers with 20 years or more of experience were among those
called back. Hopes began anew.
   ``Because there have been so many layoffs, the perception in
everyone's mind is that, `I'll get called back,''' said Arthur T.
Grniet, a 24-year veteran of the plant, after the latest layoff
announcement.
   But some workers, frustrated by the recurring layoffs and
startups that afflict the auto industry, are trying to ensure that
the coming shutdown is the last they have to endure.
   ``I know I'm going to make less money and everything,'' said
Julio Goncalves, 42, who was laid off and recalled four times in
nine years at the plant.
   ``But enough is enough. I've got to find another job and get on
with my life. ... Even if they reopen again, I don't think if I'm
going to come back.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, Feb. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
