<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0847</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board
said he expects many banks to acquire thrifts under the government's
savings industry rescue plan, but he doesn't believe the program
signals the death of the industry.
   M. Danny Wall also told a meeting of international bankers
Wednesday that the government actively would seek restitution from
fraudulent thrift barons, whose actions have contributed to the
industry's losses, said to be accruing at $500 million a month.
   He said the $90 billion bailout plan announced this week by
President Bush does not signal the demise of a financial institution
created in the 1930s to help Americans buy single-family homes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is proposing to rescue the
savings and loan industry with a 30-year, $200 billion financing
plan that would ease the pain in his administration and shift the
cost to the future.
   In fact, Bush, despite proposing the biggest government bailout
ever, will achieve an immediate $200 million savings in the 1990
budget he submits to Congress on Thursday, making it easier to keep
his ``no new taxes'' pledge in his first budget.
   Bush would spend only $1.9 billion in tax dollars in 1990,
compared with $2.1 billion proposed by the outgoing Reagan
administration. Reagan called for outlays of $18.5 billion in fiscal
years 1990 through 1993, $3.1 billion more than Bush would spend in
his first four budgets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arctic cold wave that blew through
California this week sent shivers through the state's
multimillion-dollar floral and citrus industries, ruining part of
the lemon crop and possibly boosting the price of a Valentine
bouquet.
   As the weather moderated in the state's major growing regions
Wednesday, growers assessed the cold-caused damage by slicing open
lemons and eyeing rows of drooping carnations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother of takeover strategist Asher Edelman
and another businessman were indicted for an alleged
multibillion-dollar phony tax shelter scheme that netted $511
million in improper tax writeoffs for unwitting investors.
   Asher Edelman was not charged with any wrongdoing or implicated
at all in the alleged scheme charged Wednesday against his brother,
Jon.
   The two defendants, Bernhard F. Manko, 48, of Lighthouse Point,
Fla., and Jon J. Edelman, 43, of Rye, N.Y., were accused of creating
more than $38 billion in ``pre-arranged, rigged and fraudulent''
transactions in government securities to generate tax losses for
investors in numerous limited partnerships.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOKSBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 60 years, Colgate-Palmolive
Co.'s toothpastes have helped whiten South Africans' teeth. Now, the
U.S. company wants to break ties with a town that has become a
symbol of white racism.
   A cordial corporate relationship with Boksburg, site of Colgate's
large manufacturing complex, soured in November after newly elected
right-wing town councilors decided to resegegrate parks and other
public facilities.
   Colgate joined other businesses in protesting the action, and has
requested its property be incorporated into the neighboring town of
Benoni so it no longer will pay taxes to Boksburg.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
proposed new rules that would crack down on stockbrokers who use
high-pressure telephone tactics to sell penny stocks.
   The stocks can be thinly traded and it is often difficult for an
investor to accurately judge their value. Brokers sometimes take
extra-large commissions on penny stock sales.
   The SEC rule, proposed Wednesday, would not entirely ban
unsolicited ``cold calls.'' However, it would require brokerage
firms to sign a written agreement with a new customer before
completing a transaction.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fancier foods, individual video machines and
money-back guarantees are among the amenities that big airlines are
offering to first-class fliers as competition for travelers
increasingly highlights service instead of price.
   The latest campaign was unveiled Wednesday by British Airways
PLC, which said it is investing $40 million to upgrade its
first-class service on long-haul flights beginning March 1.
   The changes, detailed at a news conference in New York, include
individual passenger video terminals at each seat, redesigned cabin
interiors, a new wine cellar and menus that allow passengers to eat
when they wish.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were little changed, bogging down after Tuesday's
advance that carried the market to new post-crash highs. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials closed with a 3.93 loss at 2,343.21.
   The dollar edged narrowly lower against several major currencies
Wednesday as traders appeared reluctant to speculate on currency
shifts in advance of President Bush's budget address Thursday.
   Bond prices mostly fell, reflecting trader disappointment with a
lack of buying interest in the federal government's debt-refinancing
auction of $9.5 billion in 10-year notes.
   Cattle futures settled narrowly mixed in cautious trading prior
to release of a report on the nation's cattle herds. Soybean futures
were down sharply; precious metals advanced; energy futures
retreated; and gold and silver futures strengthened.
</TEXT>
