<FIRST>r f BC-Kodak-Movies CORRECTIVE   02-09 0125</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kodak-Movies, CORRECTIVE,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>Members who used BC-Kodak-Movies, sent on FFF- and general newswires
Feb. 1 in advance for use weekend editions Feb. 4-5, are asked to use the
following.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press erroneously reported
the length of an average movie in a story about the 100th
anniversary of Eastman Kodak Co.'s motion-picture film products.
   The average movie, at 90 feet of film a minute, is about about
9,000 to 12,000 feet long. Kodak estimates filmmakers use at least
20 times more negative film than the finished product requires,
which means an average movie might use 180,000 to 240,000 feet of
film. If 1,000 prints are needed, a studio must buy 9 million feet
to 12 million feet of print film.
</TEXT>
