<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SteelTalks Bjt   02-09 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Talks, Bjt,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>USW Wants Early Negotiations With Steel Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Steelworkers officials say they will ask
four major steelmakers for an early start to contract negotiations
and will demand a share of the industry's renewed profits when the
talks begin.
   ``Our people have made great sacrifices for a great many years.
We might as well get at it,'' USW President Lynn Williams said
Wednesday.
   Contracts covering about 43,700 union members are due to expire
July 31 at Bethlehem Steel Corp., Inland Steel Industries Inc.,
Armco Inc. and National Steel Corp., the third- through
sixth-largest producers respectively.
   ``We're prepared to meet on a schedule that's mutually
satisfactory,'' said Bethlehem spokesman Henry Von Spreckelsen.
   The union has agreed to two consecutive rounds of contract
concessions since 1983.
   ``Our members are working in 1989 for 1982 wage rates at best,''
the USW said in a 36-page statement approved by a 400-member
strategy committee.
   The USW will negotiate separately but concurrently with the
companies. The talks will cover 20,500 workers at Bethlehem, 11,600
at Inland, 7,000 at National and 4,700 at Armco. The USW represents
only a portion of the workers at Armco.
   The contract with the largest producer, USX Corp., runs to early
1991. Second-ranked LTV Corp. and Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp.
both are in Chapter 11 reorganization and will negotiate when they
emerge from bankruptcy court.
   ``Our union's fundamental goal is ... to raise the standard of
living for our members in every possible way by negotiating improved
income, cost-of-living protection, better benefits and working
conditions and more secure employment,'' the committee statement
said.
   After losing $12 billion from 1982-86, the U.S. steel industry
made profits of more than $3 billion in 1987-88 and is expecting
another good year in 1989.
   ``Our members have made an enormous contribution to the success
of the industry,'' Williams said. ``The success they've had should
be justly and fairly shared with our members.''
   He said union negotiators will emphasize a basic wage increase
over profit sharing.
   ``They're entitled to have some guaranteed improvement'' in pay,
Williams said.
   The union also wants restrictions on mandatory overtime and the
hiring of non-union contractors.
   Williams said all the companies are requiring excessive overtime
rather than hiring additional employees, which increases pension and
benefit expenses.
   ``We think that's wrong,'' he said.
   The companies' claim that overtime is necessary because skilled
workers are not readily available is ``a reflection of the failure
of the industry to maintain its training and apprentice programs,''
Williams said.
   For similar reasons, non-union contractors are used to maintain
equipment and clean plants, he said.
   USW attorneys said they've found cases where companies have
contracted for janitorial services at $50 to $70 per hour and
maintenance services at $75 to $100 per hour when USW members could
have done the work for half as much or less.
   ``Some of these prices blow your mind,'' said chief Counsel
Bernie Kleiman.
   According to Bureau of Labor Statistics figures released by the
union, from December 1982 to October 1988 the average hourly
earnings of steelworkers, including overtime earnings, rose 2.5
percent, from $14.40 to $14.76, while those of coal miners rose 20.8
percent, from $13.20 to $15.95, oil refinery workers rose 22.2
percent, from $13.49 to $16.49, and auto workers rose 24 percent,
from $12.98 to $16.09.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890209-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 0302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;Ls-Wall Bjt   02-09 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls-Wall, Bjt,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Board Chairman Supports Bank Takeovers Of Thrifts In Rescue
Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The multibillion-dollar savings and loan crisis
doesn't mean the death of the industry, but more banks may assume
the role of thrifts, the chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board says.
   ``You have to understand in this country we have had a very high
commitment to home ownership,'' a goal aided by savings and loans,
M. Danny Wall told a meeting of international bankers Wednesday.
   Wall also said the government actively would seek restitution
from fraudulent thrift executives, whose actions have contributed to
the industry's losses, said to be accruing at the rate of $500
million a month.
   He said the $90 billion bailout plan announced this week by
President Bush does not signal the demise of a financial institution
created in the 1930s to help Americans buy single-family homes.
   Wall, who is from South Dakota, said there were ``thousands of
banks'' in that part of the country whose business was much the same
as thrifts, which traditionally have catered to individual
depositors or mortgage seekers.
   ``Over time, I'm convinced we should allow those kinds of
institutions to borrow from federal home loan banks,'' he said.
   Wall said the plan for dealing with the hundreds of troubled
thrifts includes a reversal of a Federal Reserve ban on allowing
bank holding companies to own thrifts.
   Under the plan, which must be approved by Congress, banks would
be allowed to absorb insolvent thrifts immediately and acquire
healthy institutions beginning in 1991.
   ``We are overruling the Fed, legally,'' Wall said, adding that he
expected banks to enter the thrift industry as soon as they are
allowed to.
   Wall told a meeting of the Institute of International Bankers
that the expected infusion of investment money from banks would
invigorate and perhaps save the thrift industry.
   One of the possible results of the plan is the eventual merger of
the banking and savings and loan industries. Savings institutions
have lower capital requirements than banks, a practice that would be
modified under the government plan.
   Wall said he supported Bush's proposals, which include abolishing
the three-member Federal Home Loan Bank Board that regulates the
nation's 3,100 thrifts. The bank board's regulatory apparatus would
be placed under the supervision of the Treasury Department.
   The plan also would place the insolvent Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., which insures thrift deposits, under authority of
the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which insures deposits at
commercial banks and regulates the 8,000 state-chartered banks.
   Wall also pledged to crack down on thrift institution fraud, and
cited a $50 million infusion of money under the Bush plan to beef up
federal prosecution of such crimes.
   He said the bank board, which does not have the power to
prosecute cases, last year obtained $100 million in settlements,
excluding a $50 million malpractice settlement with a Philadelphia
law firm involved in the failure of a Florida thrift that has yet to
be paid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890209-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 0832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Philippines-Westinghouse     02-09 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Westinghouse,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippines Opposes Mediation Of Nuclear Plant Suit Against Westinghouse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippines President Corazon Aquino says
Westinghouse Electric Corp. wants to cover up alleged bribes to her
predecessor by using an international body to secretly settle a
lawsuit over a $2.3 billion nuclear plant.
   ``Defendants ... don't want a public accounting in their own
country,'' Mrs. Aquino said Wednesday in a statement issued through
the Philippines embassy in Washington. ``They would rather have a
secret arbitration in Switzerland where evidence of their action
would be kept secret.''
   The Philippines filed court papers Wednesday in U.S. District
Court here opposing arbitration.
   In December, the Aquino government sued Westinghouse, a
subsidiary and plant designer Burns and Roe Enterprises Inc., an
Oradell-based engineering firm.
   The government says the contract for the nuclear power plant
should be canceled because of allegations that bribes were paid to
former President Ferdinand Marcos. Other allegations include
substandard work and construction of the plant, located on the
Bataan Peninsula about 60 miles west of Manila, near an earthquake
fault.
   Westinghouse says the lawsuit is politically motivated and that
independent analysts have verified the safety of the 620-megawatt
plant, which was completed in the final months of the Marcos
administration in 1985 but never put into operation.
   In mid-December, it filed a motion asking U.S. District Court
Judge Dickinson Debevoise to stay the lawsuit pending arbitration by
the International Chamber of Commerce in Geneva, Switzerland.
   In its 70-page memorandum, the Phillipines says a contract clause
calling for an arbritrator to resolve differences between the plant
builders and the Philippines is invalid because the state-run
National Power Corporation was forced to sign the agreement although
it opposed it.
   ``Rather than competing for the project on the merits, the
defendants conspired together to pay multimillion dollar bribes for
the benefit of former President Ferdinand E. Marcos to assure they
were awarded the contracts for work on the project,'' the memorandum
says.
   The payments were allegedly arranged through Herminio Disini, who
was married to the first cousin of Marcos' wife, Imelda, and wired
to secret Swiss bank accounts, it said.
   ``We deal here with a criminal scheme of bribery, graft and fraud
carried out by the defendants at the highest level of the Philippine
government,'' the document says. ``It is this criminal scheme that
invalidates the arbitration clauses upon which the defendants base
their motions.''
   Westinghouse officials, who said they only briefly reviewed the
new documents, said they contained no new information.
   ``They are trying to avoid arbitration ... by saying there was
some type of fraud,'' Westinghouse attorney Louis J. Briskman said.
``There is no evidence showing fraud by Westinghouse.''
   The memorandum was accompanied by four volumes of evidence
documenting the government's claims.
   Although the volumes were not immediately available, a statement
from Philippine Justice Secretary Sedfrey Ordonez said they included
over a dozen sworn statements from top Marcos officials opposing the
construction of the plant, including the head of the power
corporation.
   Also included are statements from a former Burns and Roe
executive and Westinghouse sales representative who allegedly
participated in the scheme, and documents seized in Hawaii after
Marcos fled the Philippines, Ordonez said.
   ``The Hawaii documents prove that President Marcos' favoring of
Westinghouse at the expense of the government and NPC was not
disinterested, but was done by Marcos to protect his financial stake
in the transaction,'' Ordonez said.
   Marcos has since been indicted on unrelated federal racketeering
charges in the United States but has not appeared before the court
due to illness.
   Westinghouse plans to file a response in March, continuing to
push for arbitration, and the judge is expected to make his ruling
sometime after that, Briskman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
