<FIRST>u f PM-Olivetti 1stLd-Writethru f0033 02-09 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Olivetti, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0033,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Information Technology Firm To Make Inroads In U.S. Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To CORRECT day to Wednesday from Tuesday, SUBS 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's Olivetti Co., a leading information
technology company, will strengthen its presence in the American
market through its purchase of ISC Systems Corp, a bank automation
concern, company executives and analysts said.
   The Spokane company announced Wednesday it has agreed to be
acquired and subsequently merged with Bunker Ramo Corp. of Shelton,
Conn., a wholly owned subsidiary of Ing. C. Olivetti &amp; Co., of
Ivrea, Italy.
   The deal will create one of the leading computer systems
suppliers serving the financial services industry, analysts said.
   ``This acquisition reinforces our worldwide position in banking
automation,'' Vittorio Cassoni, Olivetti's managing director and
chief operating officer, said in a prepared statement. ``It greatly
expands our market share in North America, complementing our leading
role in Europe and Japan.''
   The merger transaction, valued at approximately $174 million,
calls for the purchase of all outstanding shares of ISC common stock
at $12.25 per share in cash.
   The combined companies, which will have headquarters in Spokane,
had revenues of approximately $250 million in 1988, of which ISC's
share was $175 million.
   The merger would give the new company the third-largest market
share among firms selling automated financial services systems,
behind IBM and NCR, said John Lindeblad, current president and chief
operating officer of ISC Systems, who will remain in that capacity
in the new company.
   About 25 percent of Olivetti's sales of more than $6 billion in
1988 were to the banking industry, but little of that was in the
United States, said Ted DeMerritt, ISC Systems chairman and chief
executive officer.
   Analysts who follow ISC Systems said the merger offers a good fit
of companies in both domestic and international markets.
   Daniel Nelson, an analyst with Ragen MacKenzie in Seattle, said
Olivetti could gain from ISC's presence in Asia, while ISC would get
a toehold in the European market dominated by Olivetti. The Spokane
company, which has a large share of the domestic savings and loan
market, also stands to benefit from its association with Bunker
Ramo's commercial banking ties, he said.
   ``There are probably some synergies involved,'' agreed Dain
Bosworth analyst William Whitlow in Seattle. ``They can take ISC
software and couple it with Bunker Ramo hardware and tie it all into
Olivetti mainframes. It's probably a better package and it gives
Olivetti a better product to market.''
   James D. Lindner, president and chief executive officer of Bunker
Ramo, will become chairman and CEO of the as-yet unnamed company.
DeMerritt will become vice chairman.
   ISC Systems is a leading supplier of Pinnacle branch automation
systems to savings and loans, credit unions, and commercial banks in
the U.S. It also markets its products in Latin America, the United
Kingdom, Asia and Canada.
   Bunker Ramo supplies branch automation systems, mostly to
commercial banks.
   ISC Systems announced Dec. 22 it would begin discussions with a
possible suitor. The announcement coincided with a restructuring
that could eliminate as many as 120 jobs at its Spokane operations,
where 750 people were employed as of Jan. 1.
   DeMerritt said the merger will mean the loss of some jobs and
reshuffling of others. The reorganization announced before the
merger will continue, he said.
   ISC Systems spokesman Wes Lynch said the restructuring, expected
to be completed by June, will result in a workforce of between
630-650 people.
   The acquisition and merger is pending approval by ISC
shareholders and federal regulatory agencies, DeMerritt said.
   ISC was founded in 1977 and its products serve more than 2,700
financial institutions, employing 1,700 worldwide.
   Bunker Ramo, which employs about 600 people in the U.S., was
purchased by the Olivetti Co. in 1986. Its systems are found in 750
financial institutions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
