<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined broadly today as interest
rates rose in the credit markets.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 12.14 to 2,331.07 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by nearly 3 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 270 up, 760 down and
477 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 27.07 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite
direction from interest rates, fell about $5 for each $1,000 in face
value today.
   The Treasury was scheduled to auction $9.5 billion of new 30-year
bonds today as the final step in its quarterly financing.
   An issue of 10-year notes sold on Wednesday was met with what
analysts described as a cool reception, suggesting that interest
rates would have to move up to increase demand.
   The interest-rate outlook has also been unsettled by the prospect
of a large new amount of government borrowing to help finance a plan
to straighten out the problems at many savings institutions.
   Losers among the blue chips included Ford Motor, down { at 55|;
McDonald's, down \ at 51}; American Express, down [ at 31\, and
International Business Machines, down ] at 126|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .56 to 167.13. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 1.01 at 326.22.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average closed with a 3.93
loss at 2,343.21.
   Advancing issues and declines were evenly balanced on the NYSE,
with 732 up, 729 down and 500 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 189.42 million shares, against 217.26
million in the previous session.
