<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Halliburton     02-09 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Halliburton,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Field Services Firm Reports Fourth-Quarter Earnings Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Halliburton Co. said Thursday its earnings plunged
36 percent in the final quarter of 1988 due to the reorganization of
its logging and geophysical businesses.
   The oil field services firm reported net income of $11.8 million,
or 11 cents a share, on revenue of $639 million. That compares with
earnings of $34.1 million, or 32 cents a share, on $456 million in
revenue in the same 1987 quarter.
   ``Lower worldwide drilling activity during the last three months
of 1988 put pressure on our oil field services group's
profitability,'' Halliburton President Thomas H. Cruikshank said.
   Cruikshank said about 335 fewer drilling rigs were active
worldwide during the fourth quarter of 1988 than a year earlier.
   ``We believe this weakness in oil field service markets will
continue during the first half of 1989,'' he said.
   Halliburton reorganized its logging and geophysical business
units in the fourth quarter by forming Halliburton Geophysical
Services Inc. and Halliburton Logging Services Inc.
   The company said the restructuring cost $27.2 million in the
quarter. Halliburton said it expects savings by reducing duplicate
efforts, cutting staff and realigning international operations.
   For the full year, Halliburton reported earnings of $93.6
million, or 89 cents a share, on revenue of $2.17 billion. That is
nearly double 1987 earnings of $48.1 million, or 45 cents a share,
on revenue of $1.55 billion.
</TEXT>
