<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Warner     02-09 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Warner,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner Posts 9.8 Percent Profit Increase in 4th Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. said Thursday its
fourth-quarter profit rose 9.8 percent, driven by best-ever
performances for the period by its filmed entertainment and its
cable and broadcasting divisions.
   Warner, which also reported strong gains by its recorded music
operations, said it earned $101.1 million, or 63 cents a share, for
the final three months of 1988, compared with $92 million, or 59
cents a share, in 1987.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose 17.6 percent to $1.20 billion from
$1.02 billion a year earlier.
   For the year, Warner earned a record $423.2 million, or $2.65 a
share, up from $328.1 million, or $2.09 a share, in 1987.
   Full-year revenue rose to $4.21 billion from $3.40 billion a year
earlier.
   The 1988 figures included an after-tax gain on investments of
$33.2 million while the 1987 results reflected a $39.6 million gain.
   Steven J. Ross, chairman and chief executive, said, ``The
worldwide demand for our entertainment products has never been
stronger and the outlook for our businesses in the future remains
bright.''
   He said the filmed entertainment division posted its best fourth
quarter ever, reflecting strong results from television syndication,
international theatrical film rentals and video sales. Its new film
releases during the quarter included ``Accidental Tourist,''
``Dangerous Liaisons'' and ``Tequila Sunrise.''
   Warner's cable and broadcasting business posted record operating
income for the quarter and the year, and music division results were
up 50 percent for the quarter and reached a record for the year.
   Warner acquired the money-losing programmer Lorimar Telepictures
in January, too late for inclusion in Warner's 1988 results.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
