<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   02-09 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Nearly Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened nearly
unchanged today on the Chicago Board of Trade in light activity
ahead of this afternoon's grain supply-and-demand report from the
Agriculture Department.
   ``Boy, it's dead in here,'' said market analyst Walter Spilka of
Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   There was no confirmation of Wednesday's rumors that the Soviet
Union had canceled some of its U.S. soybean purchases. Those rumors
had triggered a sharp decline in soybean futures prices on Wednesday.
   Meanwhile, the USDA said this morning that it had accepted a
Soviet bid for 600,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices. The business had been expected, so the confirmation had
little effect on prices.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.28\ a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to } cent higher with March at $2.65\ a bushel; oats were {
cent lower to { cent higher with March at $2.09 a bushel; soybeans
were 1{ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with March at $7.46{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were sharply lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange following Wednesday's USDA cattle
inventory report, which showed the U.S. cattle herd to be about 2
million head larger than most analysts had expected.
   Most cattle futures prices plunged the permitted daily limit of
1.50 cents a pound at the opening and remained severely depressed
after about 1{ hours of trading.
   Live cattle were 1.40 cents to 1.50 cents lower with February at
73.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were 1.50 cents lower across the
board with March at 82.92 cents a pound; live hogs were .45 cent to
1.22 cents lower with February at 42.15 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .55 cent to .97 cent lower with February at 37.75 cents
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures finished mixed on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
