<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-RJRNabisco-S&amp;P 1stLd-Writethru   02-09 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-RJR Nabisco-S&amp;P, 1st Ld-Writethru,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>RJR Nabisco Dropped from Two S&amp;P Stock Indexes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with expiration of tender offer.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts Inc. began the final
process of acquiring RJR Nabisco Inc. today upon the expiration of
its record $24.53 billion tender offer for the stock of the food and
tobacco giant.
   The New York investment banking concern said stockholders had
tendered more than 215.6 million RJR Nabisco shares, or about 96.8
percent of the Atlanta-based company's outstanding common stock.
   The exact number of shares tendered would be determined in a
count over the next few days, said Ruth Pachman, a spokeswoman for
Kohlberg Kravis.
   Under terms of the tender offer, Kohlberg Kravis will pay $109 a
share in cash for about 74 percent of RJR Nabisco's outstanding
common stock. In a second step after the acquisition is completed,
Kohlberg Kravis will issue preferred stock and converting debentures
for the remaining shares.
   Checks for the cash portion of the offer were expected to be
mailed later this month.
   On Wednesday, RJR Nabisco was dropped from two Standard &amp; Poor's
Corp. stock averages, reflecting its eventual transition from a
publicly held company into a private one.
   In addition, Tiger International Inc., a pending acquisition of
Federal Express Corp., was dropped from S&amp;P's composite index of 500
stocks, S&amp;P said.
   The companies were replaced after the close of New York Stock
Exchange trading by First Union Corp. and King World Productions on
the S&amp;P 500 Index. RJR was replaced on the S&amp;P 100 Index by MCI
Communications Corp.
   Ms. Pachman said RJR stock would continue to be traded on the
NYSE until the acquisition was completed. Tiger also continued to
trade on the NYSE.
   Kohlberg Kravis won a record bidding struggle for the nation's
19th largest industrial company on Nov. 30, making it the largest
takeover in history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
