<DOCNO> AP890209-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RailroadAntitrust     02-09 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Railroad Antitrust,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Merger Of Railroad Equipment Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has issued a preliminary
injunction to block the planned merger of two railroad equipment
manufacturers.
   U.S. District Judge Richard Enslen on Wednesday granted the
federal government's request to halt the merger, pending the outcome
of the lawsuit filed in Grand Rapids, Mich., last month by the U.S.
Department of Justice Antitrust Division.
   Federal authorities contend that the merger of Jackson Jordon
Inc. of Schaumberg, Ill., and Canron Inc. of Toronto would violate
antitrust laws.
   The companies are two of only three worldwide that produce
automatic tampers, which are used to align and level railroad tracks.
   The government also contends that documents filed by the
companies indicate either Jackson Jordon's plant in Ludington,
Mich., or the Canron plant in Columbia, S.C., would close if the
deal is allowed to go through.
   Also named as a defendant in the lawsuit is Ivaco Inc. of
Montreal, Canron's parent.
   Ivaco is the largest producer of tampers in the United States,
while Jackson Jordan is the third largest. The only other company
making the parts is Plasser &amp; Theurer Co. of Austria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
