<DOCNO> AP890209-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AccountingRules     02-09 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Accounting Rules,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>FASB Proposes New Rules To Record Pension Benefits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board today
announced a controversial proposal to change the way companies
account for pension benefits, a plan which could significantly
impact company profits.
   The proposed new rules, scheduled to take effect in 1992, would
require U.S. companies to deduct promised post-retirement medical
and insurance benefits as they are earned, or while an employee is
still working for the company.
   It would eliminate the ``pay-as-you-go'' accounting method
currently used by most companies. As such, companies in many cases
under the new rule would have to deduct from their income statements
the amount of the earned benefits, instead of simply deducting the
amount the companies actually paid in a given year.
   Critics of the proposal have complained that it would impact
financial results too greatly, as well as being difficult to manage.
   The new rules would deal only with financial reporting of benefit
obligations but does not address the funding of pension benefits,
FASB officials said.
   The plan comes at a time of soaring health care costs, longer
life expectancy and earlier retirements which are posing economic
problems for many companies, according to FASB Chairman Dennis R.
Beresford.
   Beresford said the proposal would make financial statements more
informative and complete and would enhance disclosure of promised
benefits.
   ``It will require companies to publicly acknowledge their
existing commitments to investors and other users of financial
statements who in turn can evaluate the implications of those
promises,'' Beresford said.
   He also said the proposed accounting would not change the nature
or extent of the current pension promises.
   ``The cost of providing the promised benefits is the same before
and after the proposed accounting is implemented,'' Beresford said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890209-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-NorthwestJets     02-09 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northwest Jets,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Orders 10 Airbus A330 Jetliners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten Airbus A330 jetliners worth a total $860
million have been ordered for Northwest Airlines, which plans to use
the high-tech aircraft in the North Atlantic and on high-volume
domestic routes, NWA Inc. said Thursday.
   NWA, Northwest's parent, said the order was the largest to date
of the A330s, valued at $86 million each.
   The A330 is a two-pilot, two-engine aircraft seating 303
passengers in a configuration of three different fare classes.
   The first A330 will be delivered in July 1994 with the remaining
nine airplanes to enter the Northwest fleet by the end of 1994, NWA
said.
   ``We have a strong commitment to the Airbus A330,'' said Steven
G. Rothmeier, NWA's chairman and chief executive officer. ``The A330
is state-of-the-art technology with efficient Pratt &amp; Whitney
engines that provide superior operating economies with great
customer comfort and appeal.''
   The A330 will incorporate the technological advances that Airbus
has pioneered with the A320, including fly-by-wire flight control
and enhanced avionics, the company said.
   Northwest has ordered 100 of the smaller A320s for domestic use
and 20 of the larger A340s for international travel.
   Northwest also selected Pratt &amp; Whitney's PW4000 to power the new
A330s. The engine order is worth $250 million, Pratt &amp; Whitney said.
</TEXT>
