<FIRST>r f BC-Cook-Maxwell     02-09 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cook-Maxwell,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maxwell Exercises Option to Buy Thomas Cook Travel USA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp. said Thursday that a
company controlled by British publisher Robert Maxwell has agreed to
buy Thomas Cook Travel Inc. USA, one of the nation's biggest travel
agencies.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed. The sale is subject to
federal regulatory approval.
   Separately, Thomas Cook Group Ltd. of Britain said it had reached
a licensing agreement with Maxwell that permits him to continue
using the Thomas Cook name in connection with the travel agency.
   Maxwell obtained an option to buy the agency last fall when he
agreed to pay $750 million for Dun &amp; Bradstreet's airline guide
publishing business. That purchase was completed in December.
   He is making the travel agency buy through his Pergamon Group PLC.
   ``We are determined to grow the business both internally and
through an aggressive acquisition policy that will establish Thomas
Cook Travel Inc. as a dominant force in the U.S. travel business,''
Maxwell said in a statement.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet, the world's largest marketer of business
information and services, had acquired the U.S. agency from Thomas
Cook Group's parent, Midland Bank PLC, in March 1985.
   Maxwell said the agency is the fourth largest in the United
States, handling $365 million in airline reservations sales and
getting $45 million in commission revenues in 1987. It operates 60
full-service offices.
   As part of his licensing agreement with Thomas Cook Group,
Maxwell agreed to cooperate internationally with Thomas Cook Group
as part of a worldwide network providing travel services.
   Maxwell, who has extensive media interests in Europe, has been
expanding rapidly in the United States, buying the publishing giant
Macmillan Inc. for nearly $2.6 billion last year.
</TEXT>
