<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     02-09 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Drop Sharply Amid Interest Rate Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange dropped
sharply Thursday in erratic trading punctuated by concerns about
interest rates.
   Caution prevailed following the market's recent strong surge, and
participants were unwilling to push prices above the psychologically
significant 2,100-point level on the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index.
   Persistent fears of rising rates in the United States, which
could forestall a hoped-for decline in Britain's interest rates,
focused attention on U.S. President George Bush's presentation of
the fiscal 1990 budget.
   At the close, the FT-SE 100-share index was down 17.1 points, or
0.8 percent, at 2,079.1. The index dropped as much as 19.7 points as
market makers knocked prices lower in early business. There was
little selling pressure hitting shares, dealers said.
   Selective buying at lower levels pulled the FT-SE index up to its
best level late in the morning, when it was up 0.8 points. But the
market took another dive after Wall Street opened for business with
fresh losses.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index was down 11.8 points
at 1702.9. Overall volume was brisk, as 830.1 million shares were
traded, little changed from 830.9 million shares on Wednesday.
However, a good portion of this reflected trading between market
makers, dealers said.
   The Financial Times 500-share index closed at 1,175.23, down 7.30.
</TEXT>
