<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Colgate-Palmolive     02-09 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Colgate-Palmolive,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colgate's Quarterly Profit Posts Sharp Rise, Sales Up 6 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colgate-Palmolive Co. reported more than a
three-fold increase in 1988 fourth-quarter earnings Thursday, partly
because of the big consumer-products firm's sale of the Kendall
health care subsidiary.
   The company said earnings totaled $126.7 million, or $1.85 a
share, in the three months ended Dec. 31, up from $38.4 million, or
56 cents a share in the corresponding 1987 quarter. Sales rose 5.9
percent to $1.21 billion from $1.14 billion.
   Earnings for the entire year totaled $317.8 million, or $4.64 per
share, a five-fold increase over the $54 million, or 78 cents per
share for 1987. Sales totaled $4.7 billion last year, up 8.4 percent
from 1987's $4.36 billion.
   In addition to a $125 million gain on the Kendall sale,
Colgate-Palmolive's financial figures were affected by a $42
million, or 61 cents a share, accounting charge to cover a one-time
payment under a new royalty and research agreement at the Hill's Pet
Products division.
   Excluding those two special items, the company said
fourth-quarter earnings totaled $43.7 million, or 64 cents a share,
up 13.9 percent from 1987's final three months. For the full year,
earnings minus the special factors totaled $234.8 million, or $3.43
per share.
   Reuben Mark, Colgate-Palmolive's chairman, president and chief
executive officer, said the improvement reflected the effectiveness
of cost reduction programs, plus particularly strong performances by
overseas operations and Hill's Pet Products.
</TEXT>
