<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0301</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices took a spill today as interest rates
rose in the credit markets.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 20.71 to 2,322.50 by
3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 537 up, 928 down and
471 unchanged.
   Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite
direction from interest rates, fell more than $10 for each $1,000 in
face value.
   The Treasury was scheduled to auction $9.5 billion of new 30-year
bonds today as the final step in its quarterly financing.
   An issue of 10-year notes sold on Wednesday was met with what
analysts described as a cool reception, suggesting that interest
rates would have to move up to increase demand.
   The interest-rate outlook has also been unsettled by the prospect
of a large new amount of government borrowing to help finance a plan
to straighten out the problems at many savings institutions.
   Losers among the blue chips included Coca-Cola, down { at 47};
General Motors, down 1 at 92]; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down
{ at 31{, and Union Carbide, down ] at 29].
   First Union climbed 1 to 22{ and King World Productions gained 1|
to 26|. The stocks were added to Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock
composite index, prompting buying by index funds set up to match the
performance of the index.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 1.35 to 166.34. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 1.37 at 325.86.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 188.08 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
