<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Italy-AT&amp;T     02-09 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Italy-AT&amp;T,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Holding Company Approves AT&amp;T Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's giant industrial state holding company on
Thursday approved a proposed partnership agreement between American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and Italy's telecommunications equipment
maker Italtel.
   The holding company, Istituto per la Ricostruzione Industriale
(IRI), said its executive committee unanimously approved the
proposal.
   Earlier this week, Societa Finanziaria Telefonica Stet PA, the
sub-holding company for IRI in the telecommunications industry,
approved the partnership between its subsidiary Italtel and the
giant U.S. telecommunications group.
   IRI, as the controlling shareholder of Stet, needed to give its
own green light to the proposed joint venture.
   The approval by IRI was widely expected and the proposal now
awaits final approval by the Italian Government. Minister of State
Industry Carlo Fracanzani, despite initial reservations about the
deal, is expected to give his approval.
   The victory for AT&amp;T concluded 14 months of preliminary talks
between Italtel and four foreign contenders for the lucrative
partnership. Offers by Siemens AG of West Germany, Alcatel NV of
France and Sweden's Telephon AB LM Ericsson were rejected by Italtel.
   By entering into a partnership with Italtel, AT&amp;T stands to win a
big slice of the $26.5 billion in orders for equipment and
technology the Italian phone company SIP SpA has planned over the
next four years.
   Italtel, following government approval, is expected to
immediately start the conclusive round of negotiations in the hope
the partnership can become operative before the summer.
</TEXT>
