<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Textron     02-09 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Textron,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Textron Reports Higher Quarterly Earnings, Revenue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textron Inc. on Thursday reported a 28
percent increase in fourth-quarter income, but said earnings fell
8.5 percent in 1988, mainly reflecting an after-tax loss related to
an adverse arbitration ruling.
   For the three months ended Dec. 31, income amounted to $64
million, or 74 cents a share, up from $50 million, or 55 cents a
share, in 1987's corresponding quarter. Revenue totaled $1.98
billion and $1.84 billion in the same two quarters.
   Profit, after taxes, for all of last year was $234.4 million, or
$2.67 per share, compared with $256.3 million, or $2.92 per share in
1987. Revenue came to $7.3 billion in 1988 and $7.2 billion in 1987.
   Last year's results included a $37.7 million after-tax loss
stemming from a $28 million adverse arbitration ruling involving a
former insurance subsidiary of Avco Financial Services insurance
business, and from a $9.7 million loss due to the early redemption
of high interest debt rate.
   The increase in 1988 income reflected higher operating profits in
the commercial products area and in the propulsion segment as
Textron's Lycoming division recorded record revenue and profit
following a mid-year seven-week work stoppage, the company said.
   The Providence-based Textron is a multi-industry company with
operations in three sectors: aerospace technology, commercial
products and financial services.
</TEXT>
