<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     02-09 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $2.26 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High short-term interest rates are pulling
investors' cash into money market mutual funds, pumping the funds'
assets up to new highs, the Investment Company Institute said
Thursday.
   Assets of the nation's 453 money market mutual funds grew $2.26
billion in the week ended Wednesday as they set a record for the
fifth consecutive week, the institute said.
   The rise, to $287.62 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed an $18.5 million increase in the funds' assets
the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund
trade group.
   The increase was most pronounced for funds run by brokerage
firms, where individuals and institutions often park their money in
preparation for longer-term investment opportunities, said Jacob
Dreyer, the institute's vice president and chief economist.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 224 general purpose funds rose $649.3 million to $90.87
billion, assets of 92 broker-dealer funds increased $1.78 billion to
$122.51 billion, and assets of 137 institutional funds fell $171.4
million to $74.24 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.37 percent from 8.40 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 8.37 percent from 8.36 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 31
days, down from 32 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.35 percent as of Wednesday from 6.33 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was unchanged at 5.14 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.41
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.37 the
previous week. Yields were 8.67 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.63
percent; 8.74 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.70 percent; and 8.81
percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.80 percent.
</TEXT>
