<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1709EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Sears     02-09 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Sears,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourth-Quarter Earnings Down 78.8 Percent; Restructuring Cited</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. reported record
fourth-quarter revenue Thursday but a 78.8 percent drop in earnings,
attributing the results to one-time costs in the behemoth retailer's
fight to spruce up its image.
   Sears' earnings of $117.4 million, or 32 cents a share, for the
three months ended Dec. 31 compared with $554.4 million, or $1.46
per share, for the century-old company in the year-earlier period.
   The fourth consecutive quarterly earnings decline was attributed
to a $500 million outlay for the massive restructuring announced
last fall. The company is attempting to streamline and overhaul its
market approach to offer low pricing, more contemporary displays and
outside brand names.
   One analyst said he considers the fourth-quarter showing a
prelude to a major upswing for the company.
   ``Sears lacked two ingredients to growth,'' said analyst John
Landschulz with Cowen &amp; Co. in Chicago. ``One was competitive
pricing. The other was a power format _ a really aggressive
marketing tool. I think these changes address both these key
weaknesses.''
   Sears has not yet begun an all-out promotional campaign to alert
consumers to its metamorphosis. But Edward A. Brennan, company
chairman and chief executive officer, also predicted an improved
balance sheet, calling 1988 ``a year of major transition.''
   The fourth-quarter plunge reflected after-tax accounting charges
of $442 million for the restructuring of Sears Merchandise Group and
$58.6 million for a loss on the sale of Sears' Allstate group life
and health insurance, the company said.
   Fourth-quarter revenue totaled a record $14.56 billion, up 9
percent from $13.36 billion for the year-earlier period.
   Sears has said the restructuring includes the planned sale of the
landmark Sears Tower and Coldwell Bankers commercial real estate
subsidiary, plus the buyback of 10 percent of its 380 million
outstanding shares.
   The company said it would concentrate on consumer-oriented
businesses _ retailing, insurance, residential real estate and
financial services.
   Before the restructuring charge, the company said, fourth-quarter
earnings totaled $618 million or $1.65 per share.
   For the year ended Dec. 31, earnings totaled $1.45 billion or
$3.84 per share, 11 percent down from $1.63 billion or $4.30 per
share in 1987. Revenue totaled a record $50.25 billion, up 9.5
percent from $40.95 billion in 1987.
   Sears said 1988 results include the adoption of new income tax
and insurance accounting standards, and discontinuance of Allstate's
group life-health operations and Coldwell Banker's commercial
division.
   Revenue for all previous periods was restated for the
discontinued operations and the new accounting standard, the company
said.
   Sears Merchandise Group reported a fourth-quarter loss of $113.5
million after the $442 million restructuring charge. Before the
charge, the group's fourth-quarter income was $328.5 million, down
from $414.9 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
