<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A falling dollar and rising interest rates sent
stock prices broadly lower Thursday, pinning the Dow Jones
industrial average with its largest loss since the first session of
1989.
   Dow Jones's average of 30 blue chips fell 20.17 to 2,323.04, for
its biggest point drop since it lost 23.93 on Jan. 3.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
504 up, 1,003 down and 461 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 224.22 million
shares, up from 189.42 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 256.79 million shares.
   The dollar fell in foreign-exchange trading, and prices of
long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite direction
from interest rates, dropped more than $15 for each $1,000 in face
value.
   The Treasury auctioned $9.5 billion of new 30-year bonds Thursday
as the final step in its quarterly financing.
   That and an issue of 10-year notes sold on Wednesday met with
what analysts described as a cool reception, suggesting that
interest rates would have to move up to increase demand.
   The interest-rate outlook has also been unsettled by the prospect
of a large new amount of government borrowing to help finance a plan
to straighten out the problems at many savings institutions.
   Analysts said traders in all the markets turned cautious as they
awaited President Bush's budget message scheduled for Thursday night.
   Trading activity on the Big Board was swollen by dividend-related
transactions in three stocks _ Houston Industries, down \ at 28;
Philadelphia Electric, unchanged at 20~, and Allied-Signal, down ]
at 35.
   Losers among the blue chips included Coca-Cola, down { at 47};
General Motors, down { at 92~; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down
\ at 31}; International Business Machines, down | at 126], and
Philip Morris, down 1| at 109\.
   First Union climbed 1 to 22{ and King World Productions gained 1{
to 26{. The stocks were added to Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock
composite index, prompting buying by index funds set up to match the
performance of the index.
   Miniscribe dropped 1 to 4~ in the over-the-counter market. The
company, which makes disk drives, said it expects to report a loss
for the fourth quarter of last year.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $24.71 billion, or 0.84
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slumped 1.56 to 166.13.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 3.15 to 342.16, and the
500-stock composite was down 2.59 at 296.06.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped 1.58 to 406.39. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 325.36, down 1.87.
