<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     02-09 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped sharply Thursday as traders
speculated that President Bush would say nothing new in his budget
message about cutting the federal deficit.
   In its biggest one-day decline in weeks, the dollar lost roughly
1.2 percent of its value against such currencies as the West German
mark, Japanese yen, British pound and Swiss franc.
   The sharp drop came after several steady sessions in which
dealers had been reluctant to trade actively because of uncertainty
about what Bush would say in his Thursday evening address.
   On Thursday, traders guessed the speech would be negative or at
best neutral for the dollar and decided to sell before others did,
said Marc Cohen, a vice president at Republic National Bank of New
York.
   ``It's almost the market attempting to anticipate the
anticipation of others,'' Cohen said. ``Everybody saw somebody
making it for the door and said, `Wait.'''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.11 Japanese yen to a closing 129.39 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 128.53 yen. In New York, the dollar sank to
127.93 yen from 129.38 yen late Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7540, compared with
$1.7423 late Wednesday. In New York, the pound rose to $1.7645 from
$1.7440.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8475 West German marks, down from
1.8698; 1.5675 Swiss francs, down from 1.5895; 1.1836 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1844; 6.2875 French francs, down from 6.3640;
and 1,347.5 Italian lire, down from 1,363.6.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.8585 West German marks, down from 1.8720; 1.5801
Swiss francs, down from 1.5916; 6.3225 French francs, down from
6.3725; 2.0990 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1140; 1,355.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,364.25; and 1.1832 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1847.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid of $395.58 a troy ounce,
compared with $395.07 a week ago. Financial markets in Hong Kong
have been closed for the Chinese lunar new year celebrations.
   In London gold was trading at a late price of $394.25 a troy
ounce, compared with $390.25 bid late Wednesday. In Zurich,
Switzerland, the bid price was the same as in London, $394.25, well
up from $390.85 bid late Wednesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $394.40 a troy ounce from $396.20. Later, Republic
National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $393.25 an ounce from
$394.25.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.90 a troy
ounce from $5.88 bid late Wednesday. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery fell to $5.891 a troy ounce from $5.917.
</TEXT>
