<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     02-09 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cattle Futures Crunched By Bearish USDA Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A government report showing a larger-than-expected U.S. cattle
herd knocked cattle futures prices to the mat Thursday on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange but analysts were skeptical of the
report's accuracy.
   On other markets, cotton futures prices fell sharply; grains and
soybeans were mixed; precious metals futures declined; and energy
futures were mixed.
   Prices for all cattle futures except the February live cattle
contract plunged the permitted daily limit of 1{ cents at the
opening bell and stayed limit-down for the rest of the session. The
contract for February delivery of live cattle settled 1.40 cents
lower at 73.97 cents a pound while the near-month feeder cattle
contract, for delivery in March, settled at 82.92 cents a pound.
   Pork futures prices fell in sympathy with the cattle market. Live
hogs finished .50 cent to 1.05 cents lower with February at 41.90
cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .12 cent to 1.13 cents lower
with February at 37.57 cents a pound.
   The sell-off was triggered by Wednesday's semi-annual USDA cattle
inventory report, a head count of the nation's cattle herd. The USDA
reported there were 99.5 million cattle and calves in the United
States as of Jan. 1, only a few thousand fewer than the previous
year.
   The industry consensus expectation was for the herd to total
fewer than 98 million cattle. The USDA report implied that after six
years of thinning cattle numbers, producers were starting to rebuild
their herds.
   But many analysts said they did not believe the report,
especially its implication of an extremely high birth rate in the
second half of 1988.
   ``We had a 92 percent calving rate, the highest in 15 years, in a
year when you had the driest, hottest summer since 1932,'' said Tom
O'Hare, an analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   ``This looks like one of those aberrational things where you've
got to wonder what's going on here,'' he said. ``There are just too
many contrary things to come into (the report) to really believe
it.''
   Analysts said the bulk of the futures selling appeared to have
come from speculative commodity funds, not cattle producers or beef
processors, possibly an indication that the beef industry also was
skeptical of the USDA numbers.
   Cotton futures prices fell sharply on the New York Cotton
Exchange on expectations that another USDA report would be bearish
for the cotton market.
   And so it was. In a monthly supply-demand report issued after the
close of trading, the USDA estimated the U.S. cotton stockpile on
Aug. 1 would stand at 9.2 million bales, compared with the January
estimate of 8.8 million bales and the Aug. 1, 1988 stockpile of 5.8
million bales.
   Cotton settled .80 cent to 1.75 cent lower with March at 57.64
cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures were mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade in dull trading ahead of the same USDA supply-demand report.
   In the report, the government lowered its estimate for 1988-89
Argentine soybean production to 9 million metric tons from 11
million metric tons and lowered its 1988-89 Argentine corn
production forecast to 6 million metric tons from 8 million.
   The USDA also lowered its 1988-89 Soviet grain production
estimate by 5 million metric tons to 195 million.
   Analysts interpreted the report as neutral to slightly bullish
for grain and soybean futures.
   Wheat settled 1} cents to 3\ cents lower with March at $4.25\ a
bushel; corn was \ cent lower to 1\ cents higher with March at $2.65
a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 3{ cents lower with March at $2.06 a
bushel; soybeans were 1\ cents lower to } cent higher with March at
$7.46 a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures retreated modestly in
technically-inspired trading on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled $1.10 to $1.30 lower with April at $398 a troy
ounce; silver was 2.4 cents to 3 cents lower with March at $5.915 a
troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices finished narrowly mixed on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in an uneventful session.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 10 cents lower to 9
cents higher with March at $17.39 a barrel; heating oil was .46 cent
lower to .27 cent higher with March at 48.61 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .30 cent to .58 cent lower with March at 48.36
cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
