<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-TexasAir     02-09 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Texas Air,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Air Posts $224.4 Million Fourth-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern-Machinists Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp., the nation's largest airline
company, reported a $224.4 million fourth-quarter loss Thursday,
attributing the results to travails that ranged from federal safety
probes to labor-management turmoil at its Eastern and Continental
subsidiaries.
   The October-December performance compared with a $265.6 million
loss in the year-earlier period, and widened the overall 1988 loss
to $718.6 million _ 54 percent greater than the $466.2 million Texas
Air lost in 1987.
   Miami-based Eastern reported losses of $101.7 million for the
quarter on revenues of $844.4 million. That compared with a loss of
$143.4 million on revenues of $1 billion in the same period a year
earlier.
   Houston-based Continental incurred a fourth-quarter loss of $99.2
million on revenues of $1.1 billion. During the same period in 1987,
Continental lost $78.8 million on revenues of $1.1 billion.
   Fourth-quarter revenue for the parent company totaled $2 billion
vs. $2.1 billion in the year-earlier quarter. For all of 1988, Texas
Air revenue totaled $8.6 billion, the same as the year earlier.
   Eastern lost $335.4 million on revenues of $3.8 billion for all
of 1988. In 1987, Eastern lost $181.7 million on revenues of $4.4
billion.
   Continental lost $315.5 million on revenues of $4.7 billion for
all of 1988, vs. a $258.1 million loss on revenues of $4.1 billion
in 1987.
   In a statement, Texas Air said the 1988 results ``reflected the
numerous and unprecedented challenges faced by both Continental and
Eastern during the past year'' and that future results at the two
airlines ``will reflect the fact that these challenges are being
successfully met.''
   In 1988, both airlines were subject of an unprecedented
investigation by the Department of Transportation and the Federal
Aviation Administration, which determined the two carriers were run
safely.
   The probe, however, concluded that labor turmoil at Eastern must
be defused before it creates risks to passengers.
   The turmoil intensified this week with Eastern's militant
machinists, who were voting on whether to authorize a strike next
month.
   Last week, Continental's president, Martin Shugrue, quit after a
year on the job, becoming the carrier's sixth former president in as
many years.
</TEXT>
