<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1810EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     02-09 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All three measures of the nation's money supply
advanced in late January, the Federal Reserve Board reported
Thursday.
   The Fed said its narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose
$900 million to a seasonally adjusted $787.1 billion in the week
ended Jan. 30 from $786.2 billion in the previous week.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose $600 million to a
seasonally adjusted $3,072.0 billion from $3,071.4 billion the
previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, increased $900 million to a
seasonally adjusted $3,920.6 billion from $3,919.7 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   The Fed last year set a provisional target for 1989 of 3 percent
to 7 percent growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent growth in
M3. The Fed has not set a target for M1 growth since early 1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,067.8 billion, a 4.3
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13
weeks. M3 averaged $3,911.4 billion, up 5.2 percent, while M1 rose
2.0 percent to an average of $787.8 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported discount window
borrowing, exclusing extended credit, averaged $698 million a day in
the week ended Wednesday, up from $263 million in the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $288.0 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, down from
$290.7 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
