<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices were mixed in subdued
trading Thursday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 10
cents to $17.39 a barrel after losing 21 cents in Wednesday's
session. Contracts for delivery later in the year were mixed.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the March contract
for unleaded gasoline declined 0.58 cent to 48.36 cents a gallon,
while domestic heating oil fell 0.46 cent to close the day at 48.61
cents a gallon.
   Other contract months were mixed.
   Analysts said prices remained in a narrow trading range
throughout the session with volume relatively light.
   Prices have fluctuated in recent weeks, as uncertainty set in
following several weeks of steadily rising prices. Investors have
been reluctant to take positions as they await more information on
the market's direction, analysts said.
   Prices had been climbing steadily since last November when the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed to lower its
production. However, energy analysts said the market softened in
recent weeks partly on technical factors after the rapid rise and as
investors await word on whether OPEC is adhering to its agreement.
