<FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-89 1921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-KodakCuts     02-09 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kodak Cuts,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Wants To Cut Costs By 15 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. said Thursday it wants
to cut its non-essential costs by 15 percent and may do so by
trimming its work force, selling businesses or ending product lines.
   ``I think it would be inaccurate to call this a job reduction
plan,'' said Kodak spokesman Paul Allen. ``We're asking unit
managers to start looking very closely at their businesses and start
making some decisions from the viewpoint of profitability.''
   Allen said costs directly related to raw materials and production
won't be subject to the cutbacks, but that all of the company's
products and business units will be reviewed to determine whether
they're worth keeping.
   ``Over the last eight years Kodak has made a lot of strategic
acquisitions,'' Allen said. ``What we haven't done is a lot of
strategic divestment.''
   The announcement came a day after Kodak reported record sales and
earnings in 1988.
   Kodak's 1988 profit rose 19 percent to a record $1.4 billion, or
$4.31 a share, compared with $1.2 billion, or $3.52 a share, in
1987. Sales rose 28 percent to a record $17.03 billion, up from
$13.3 billion in 1987.
   The results were boosted by the contribution of Sterling Drug
Co., which Kodak acquired in February 1988.
   Allen said the comprehensive look at the company is part of the
changes that have taken place at Kodak since the company began a
massive reorganization in 1984.
   In a presentation to employees Wednesday, part of an ongoing
series, Chairman Colby Chandler outlined the study but didn't say
which businesses, products or employees would be affected.
   Stock analysts said that even the company may not know for sure.
   ``It could include some of the things in the electronics area, or
office equipment, or batteries,'' said Peter Enderlin, an analyst
with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York. ``It doesn't have
to be businesses in trouble. Some of the joint ventures they have
are still very small and may have a lot of potential but aren't
worth the trouble to Kodak.''
</TEXT>
