<HEAD>Braniff to Move HQ to Orlando, Expand Facilities in Kansas City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Braniff Inc. announced Thursday it will move
its headquarters from Dallas to Orlando and expand support
facilities in Orlando and in Kansas City to the tune of $40 million
and 1,400 jobs in the next year.
   Kansas City will remain the airline's primary hub, Braniff
Chairman William G. McGee told an Orlando news conference. But the
carrier wants to participate ``in one of the most dynamic growth
areas of the country'' by moving its corporate base to Orlando.
   The airline, which began operating in Central Florida a year ago
with the acquisition of Florida Express, will build new maintenance
facilities at both Kansas City and Orlando as well as a headquarters
building in Orlando, McGee said.
   ``This aggressive expansion program coupled with our already
announced plans to increase our fleet by a net of 22 additional
aircraft this year will fuel a 35 percent company-wide growth in
employment over the next 12 months,'' McGee said.
   He estimated the annual economic impact of the expansion program
at $250 million in Kansas City and $50 million in Orlando.
   The headquarters move is to begin in May and involve about 125
professional and clerical workers now at Love Field in Dallas. The
airline also will build a $10 million maintenance facility in
Orlando.
   The company wants to ``reinforce our commitment to the growth and
prosperity'' of the Kansas City hub by building a $10 million
maintenance operation there, reopening a reservations center,
expanding the number of airport gates and increasing daily flight
departures to 105 by mid-summer, McGee said.
   The number of employees in Kansas City will climb from 1,475 to
2,000 by mid-summer, he said, and jump from 720 to 1,165 in Orlando
during the coming year.
   Some 450 Braniff employees will remain in Dallas, mainly in
financial and administratrive jobs, company officials said.
   The chairman called Braniff a ``niche carrier'' that is ``fast
becoming a major carrier'' with good growth potential in a highly
competitive industry. ``We expect to turn a profit in 1989,'' he
added.
   Braniff filed for bankruptcy protection in 1982 with nearly $1
billion in debt. It started flying again in 1984 as a low-cost,
no-frills carrier.
   The airline was acquired by investors last summer, shifted most
of its flight operations to Kansas City and began trying to attract
more business travelers by increasing its daily departure schedules.
It then ordered more than $2 billion worth of new airplanes.
   ``We will need these (new) facilities and the new personnel to
support our growth plan,'' McGee said.
   The Philadelphia-based investor group controlling the company is
CoreGroup, headed by Jeffrey R. Chodorow and Arthur Cohen.
   Braniff serves 31 destinations from Kansas City and 16 from
Orlando. It has more than 4,000 employees, including 440 pilots, and
operates 53 aircraft.
</TEXT>
